<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel criticizes EPA ecological data on Hudson PCBs  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL HILL
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- An Environmental Protection Agency
study that found animals endangered by PCBs in the Hudson River was
criticized by independent experts who questioned its value.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a peer review panel said Friday that the federal
EPA's ecological assessment lacked enough information to be used by
the agency as it considers whether to order a dredging of the upper
Hudson. Two of the seven panel members called the EPA's work
unacceptable, and one suggested starting some work over.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is so far short of what is needed,'' said panel member
Lawrence Kapustka.
</P>
<P>
   The critical comments are a blow to the EPA as agency officials
move to wrap up their long process on whether to dredge. EPA
officials could not say Friday if this development would delay the
EPA's proposal on a course of action, which is due in December.
</P>
<P>
   EPA Hudson River Project Manager Alison Hess said the agency
would consider the recommendations and make the appropriate
revisions. But she added that the agency had already established
the human health risk posed by PCBs sufficiently enough to go ahead
with a study on the best course of action for the river.
</P>
<P>
   Hess was referring to another EPA report that found health risks
to people eating PCB-contaminated fish from the upper river are
higher than acceptable levels. A separate peer review panel agreed
with that contention on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ecological review panel, which met on Thursday and Friday,
was the last of four peer review panels to scrutinize the EPA's
work on the river.
</P>
<P>
   This panel looked at a report in which the EPA claimed fish in
the river are at risk due to PCBs -- particularly larger fish that
eat other fish such as largemouth bass and striped bass. The agency
also concluded that other animals that eat river fish -- like
eagles, belted kingfishers, great blue herons, mink and river otter
-- are similarly at risk.
</P>
<P>
   A central complaint of panel members was a lack of information --
things like population data, ecological survey data, toxicity data.
Panel member Dwayne Moore said the report gave him no basis for
deciding the best course of action for the river.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the two panelists who called the EPA report unacceptable
-- Kapustka and Moore -- four others called for major revisions. The
seventh panelist left early and has yet to make a recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a rough one for us,'' Hess conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution from General Electric factories on the Hudson is
largely blamed for PCBs legally dumped for years into the river.
The substance, used as insulating material in transformers and
other electrical equipment, was banned by the federal government in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   GE, which could be forced to spend billions of dollars if a
dredging is ordered, has been a vocal dredging opponent.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman said Friday's development illustrates fatal
flaws in the EPA's work. Spokesman Mark Behan also noted that two
peer review panelists that looked at human health concerns earlier
this week had called for major revisions to that report.
</P>
<P>
   ''The core of EPA's scientific case has been called into
question,'' said Behan.
</P>
<P>
   GE has funded a study that found the river is cleaning up
naturally. More recently it launched an advertising campaign citing
the opposition of local government to dredging and landfilling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
