<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State police detail investigation of death of elderly man  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) -- Harold Carter and Mary Anne Voorhees sat next
to one another in Oneida County Court. They never spoke nor did
they make eye contact as a state police investigator was questioned
about the disappearance of the elderly man they're accused of
murdering.
</P>
<P>
   Senior State Police Investigator Dennis P. Dougherty, a 20-year
veteran of the force who was assigned to the case, revealed in more
than two hours on the witness stand Friday that Carter gave three
statements detailing what happened to Glenn Morgan Jr. the night he
disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Although defense attorney Joseph P. Giruzzi tried to portray
investigators as desperate because Morgan had been missing for
several days, Dougherty said Carter was willing to talk and very
cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ''We told him it was very important to us and more important to
the Morgan family that he be found and have a proper funeral and
burial,'' Dougherty testified. ''For the first time, he showed a
little bit of emotion. He acted like he was very sad about what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, 42, and Voorhees, 53, each is charged with two counts of
second-degree murder, first-degree robbery, and second-degree
robbery in connection with the death of Morgan, a retired postal
worker who disappeared after celebrating his 73rd birthday last
Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   His decaying corpse was found nine days later about 15 feet down
a brush-strewn embankment in suburban Utica by a woman walking on a
nearby sidewalk. She smelled a strong odor and called police.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities still don't know what caused Morgan's death and
probably never will because his body was so badly decomposed. It
was discovered several miles down the road from the Whitesboro
American Legion post where Morgan met Voorhees that night.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, the defendants are being tried at the same
time before two juries. Oneida County Judge Barry Donalty decided
it made sense to conduct the trials together because the same
witnesses will testify against both defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The trial entered its dual-jury phase on Friday, the fourth day
of testimony. Evidence was presented that related only to Carter.
Donalty excused the Voorhees jury until Monday, when evidence
concerning Voorhees will be heard and the Carter jury will not be
present.
</P>
<P>
   Investigator Dougherty said Carter agreed last Aug. 25 to write
the Morgan family an apologetic letter but had a difficult time
focusing on what to say, calling it ''the worst day of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty said Carter admitted in each confession to striking
Morgan. He also agreed to take troopers to the body.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was our goal that day -- to find Mr. Morgan's body,''
Dougherty said.
</P>
<P>
   In a confession lasting three hours, which he signed, Carter
told troopers he had known Voorhees for six years and knew all
about her routine for hustling older men, buying them drinks,
taking them to secluded spots where she performed oral sex, and
then taking their cars and money.
</P>
<P>
   Dougherty said Carter changed his confession three times in a
two-day period, adding details each time. Carter said in his final
statement that Morgan fell unconscious after he struck him, then he
and Voorhees took the body to a boat launch and went drinking
again. Carter said when they returned later, Morgan's body was
cold, so they tossed it into a dumpster.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution plans to call about 50 witnesses in the trial,
which is expected to take about two weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
