<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conservative Party head says he will deliver 350,000 votes for Lazio </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The head of the state Conservative Party
says he expects to deliver at least 350,000 votes to help
Republican Rick Lazio in his U.S. Senate race against Hillary
Rodham Clinton, a potentially decisive boost in a close race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think our people are really energized,'' said Michael Long
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Long's prediction came on the eve of his party's state
nominating convention at which the little-known Long Island
congressman is to officially be named its candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, the state Liberal Party's leadership was meeting in
New York City to give its backing to the first lady. The path was
cleared for Clinton to get the Liberal Party nod after Republican
New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani dropped out of the Senate race
to deal with his prostate cancer. One of Giuliani's closest
political advisers is Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's withdrawal from the race, and Lazio's quick entry
into it, also opened the way for the Republican and Conservative
parties to restore their traditional partnership in statewide
races. Long had refused to get behind Giuliani because of the
mayor's strong support for abortion rights and his closeness to the
Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   While Lazio has said he is an abortion rights supporter, he has
repeatedly voted to cut off federal Medicaid money to pay for poor
women's abortions and favors a ban on what critics call
''partial-birth abortion.'' That has been enough to win Long's
support.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican seeking statewide office in New York has won
without Conservative Party support since 1974. Conversely, no
Democrat has been elected governor or U.S. senator in New York
without Liberal Party backing since it was founded more than 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the state Conservative Party began airing a
television advertisement promoting Lazio on Albany-area TV stations
and on an all-news New York City cable TV station.
</P>
<P>
   The ad drew a put-down Friday from a Giuliani adviser because it
was produced by Nelson Warfield, a veteran New York political
operative who had been critical of Giuliani's Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never thought much of his political commentary and I don't
think much of his political advertising,'' said Bruce Teitelbaum,
Giuliani's Senate campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Told about Teitelbaum's comment, Warfield said: ''I thought we
all had the same target -- Hillary Clinton. It's disappointing to
see some other folks have different agendas.''
</P>
<P>
   Warfield, Bob Dole's presidential campaign spokesman in 1996,
has been a top adviser to cosmetics heir Ronald Lauder, who ran
unsuccessfully against Giuliani for the GOP nomination for mayor in
1989. Giuliani narrowly lost the general election that year to
Democratic nominee David Dinkins who Giuliani then beat in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party backing can be critical in New York elections.
Three-term Democratic incumbent Mario Cuomo was beaten by
Republican George Pataki in the 1994 governor's race on the
strength of the 328,695 votes he received on the Conservative Party
line.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
count votes they receive on third-party ballot lines.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Independence Party, the state arm of the national
Reform Party, will hold its state nominating convention on Monday
in Albany. Its chairman, Frank McKay, said Friday he wasn't certain
who might end up with the party's nomination and that there might
be a Sept. 12 primary to determine the nominee. McKay said it was
possible that neither Clinton nor Lazio would qualify for such a
primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 0013 </TRAILER>
