<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Critics say fee for finding money in bankruptcy case is too high and too soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Bankruptcy trustee Richard Breeden says he
has nearly finished his work in the Bennett Funding case and wants
to be paid early, even though years of lawsuits and legal
proceedings remain.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no more billing, no more collecting, no more people
to manage or sell hotels,'' said Breeden. ''Substantially all of
the things that I can control have been completed.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waiting for the outcome of the last lawsuit, Breeden
has asked a federal judge to award him $4.8 million to $12.3
million now. The money would be a special payout based on a
percentage of the money already repaid to creditors. Breeden is
entitled to as much as 3 percent of the money he collects.
</P>
<P>
   Breeden, a former chairman of the U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission, has spent four years collecting money for creditors of
10 Bennett companies. Under Breeden's direction, workers collected
leases, sold property and three hotels, and made deals to get money
back for the creditors.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has collected $500 million, meaning he could earn up
to $15 million if paid the full 3 percent commission. He already
has received $2.7 million, representing $50,000 a month draw, plus
a $250,000 one-time special payment.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he has paid $44 million to the lawyers,
accountants and other professionals assisting in the case.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bennett Funding companies collapsed in a fraud and
bankruptcy scandal in 1996, the companies owed $1 billion to at
least 21,000 secured and unsecured creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Former chief financial officer Patrick Bennett and several other
company officials were convicted of a variety of fraud and money
laundering charges. Bennett was sentenced last month to 30 years in
federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the 10,000 unsecured creditors have received 8.5
percent of what they were owed. By the end of the case, Breeden
estimates investors will get 32 to 43 cents back on the dollar -- or
$320 to $430 on a $1,000 investment.
</P>
<P>
   Breeden's request, however, is facing some challenges.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer representing a committee of unsecured creditors,
Daniel Stolz, is vehemently opposed to paying Breeden's commission
before the end of the case.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to evaluate a trustee is to rate his entire
results, Stolz said. Breeden hasn't finished his tasks, Stolz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our objection we suggest that if the court had to do a
report card on the trustee at this point, the only grade that could
be assigned is incomplete,'' Stolz said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Trustee Guy Van Baalen also objects to Breeden's
request. Van Baalen's job is to monitor cases and their fees as
they go through the bankruptcy process.
</P>
<P>
   Both plan to argue against Breeden's early payment when the
question comes before U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Stephen D.
Gerling July 11.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.75 million for four years worth of work is pretty good
compensation, Stolz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see a lot of the investors feeling sorry for somebody
who earns $600,000 a year plus his expenses,'' Stolz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
