<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DEC gives water permit approval for Hudson River power plant  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state Department of Environmental
Conservation has imposed a limit on the amount of river water a
proposed plant in the Hudson River Valley could use to less than
200,000 gallons a day.
</P>
<P>
   DEC Commissioner John Cahill issued the water discharge permit
Friday, requiring PG&AMP;E Generating to use the ''best technology
available'' to control its river water usage at its proposed
electric generating plant in Athens, Greene County.
</P>
<P>
   The State Pollution Discharge Elimination System (SPDES) permit
issued to PG&AMP;E prevents the plant from withdrawing more than
180,000 gallons water each day.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier ruling by an administrative law judge had proposed a
water intake structure that would have allowed about 4.2 million
gallons of water per day to be taken and required the use of a
filtering device called a Gunderboom. A Gunderboom would fit over
water intake structures and prevent fish from being damaged or
killed when water is pulled into the system.
</P>
<P>
   In his decision, Cahill said federal and state laws mandate the
use of the best technology available in power plants. He rejected
using a Gunderboom, citing the state's relative inexperience with
the technology and the lack of information on how the device would
work at the Athens plant.
</P>
<P>
   Cahill also found that the state's policy on river water quality
is sufficiently protective so that the Athens plant would not harm
the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   DEC spokeswoman Jennifer Post said that with the limit on how
much water the plant could withdraw from the Hudson, ''it appears
that those limits would require the dry cooling technology,'' which
would be more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Athens plant is the first major power plant to be proposed
in New York in nearly a decade, and Pataki administration officials
have said it and others will be needed to meet heightened peak
power demands starting in a few years. The proposed facility will
be a 1,080-megawatt electric generating plant that would be powered
by natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have argued that the plant would spoil the scenic Hudson
River Valley area and harm the fish habitat or create undue
pollution in the river.
</P>
<P>
   Post said that the issuance of a SPDES permit is a ''significant
step'' in getting the final approval of the power plant. PG&AMP;E
applied in August 1998 for approval from the state Board on
Electric Generation Siting and the Environment, and the board is
scheduled to make a decision later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Siting Board will incorporate this decision and any other
permits into its analysis ... as expeditiously as possible,'' board
spokesman Edward Collins.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E officials did not immediately return a telephone call
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Messages left for environmental activists fighting the project
were also not immediately returned Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 0015 </TRAILER>
