<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State looking for more jobs from Adelphia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Gov. George Pataki told Adelphia
Communications executives the state might increase its financial
incentives for the cable company's expansion plans if Adelphia
commits to creating more than the 1,000 jobs it already has
promised to Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ''We reminded them the more jobs they can commit to, the more we
can help,'' Charles Gargano, executive director of Empire State
Development Corp., told The Buffalo News in Friday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Gargano, Pataki, Adelphia chairman John Rigas and his son,
Timothy Rigas, executive vice president of the Coudersport,
Pa.-based company, met in Albany Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The intent was to try to explore ways to wrap this deal up,''
Gargano said. ''We all want it to happen, the Rigases wanted it to
happen, and they understand we're trying our best. It was a very
frank and open discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia, the fourth-largest cable communications company in the
United States, wants to build a $125 million operations center
employing more than 1,000 people on Buffalo's waterfront. It's
hoped the project would prompt further development.
</P>
<P>
   Talks have been underway since January but a major sticking
point has been determining ways to relieve Adelphia's financial
problems at HSBC Arena, the waterfront venue for the NHL's Buffalo
Sabres, which the Rigases also own.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres are expected to lose $20 million this year, in part,
Adelphia officials say, because of the 30-year lease they inherited
when Rigas took control of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Adelphia is seeking a $13 million annual subsidy as the price of
building its new operations center in Buffalo and guaranteeing the
long-term financial viability of the Sabres, the newspaper
reported. The state, city and county reportedly have offered a
total of $60 million.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said it is important to wrap up talks before the
State Legislature leaves Albany in mid-June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 0016 </TRAILER>
