<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, June 2, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jobless Rate Up To 4.1 Percent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's unemployment rate rose to 4.1 percent in May
as businesses cut 116,000 jobs, the biggest reduction in nine years. Today's
report triggered a rally on Wall Street, where it was viewed as the best
evidence yet that the red-hot economy is slowing enough to keep the Federal
Reserve from boosting interest rates further. ''This is a strong indication that
the economy is throttling back from its very robust growth of the past year,''
said Mark Zandi, senior economist at RFA Dismal Sciences in West Chester, Pa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Defense Highlights US-Russia Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- At a Kremlin summit held in the twilight of one man's
presidency and the beginning of the other's, Bill Clinton and Vladimir Putin
will be measuring one another on issues that will outlast them both. Clinton
flies to Moscow on Saturday after five days of conferences and ceremonies with
western European allies, who are restive about at least one proposal he'll take
to Putin: the idea of amending an arms control treaty so the United States can
build a limited anti-missile defense system.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin: Teamwork To Fight Missile Threat
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian political and military officials lined up Friday
behind President Vladimir Putin's proposal that Russia and the United States
work jointly on a nuclear defense against so-called rogue nations. President
Clinton was due to arrive in Moscow on Saturday for talks with the new Russian
leader. Topping the agenda at the summit will be the U.S. proposal to modify the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. The United States wants to construct a
national missile defense against possible nuclear strikes by states such as
North Korea and Iran, which it fears may acquire nuclear weapons. Russia objects
to ABM Treaty changes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Governors Refer to DNA Tests
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Reflecting growing fears around the country that
innocent people are on death row, two Republican governors this week decided to
let science sort it out. Virginia Gov. Jim Gilmore approved new DNA tests in
hopes of establishing conclusively whether a former death row inmate raped and
murdered a woman 18 years ago. And Texas Gov. George W. Bush blocked an
execution for the first time in his career to allow DNA tests.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ex-Con Convicted in O'Hair Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- An ex-convict was acquitted today of conspiring to
kidnap atheist Madalyn Murray O'Hair and her family but found guilty of
extorting money from them. O'Hair, her son Jon Garth Murray and granddaughter
Robin Murray O'Hair disappeared in 1995 along with $500,000 in gold coins.
Authorities believe they were killed and dismembered, though their bodies were
never found. Gary Paul Karr, 52, convicted on four counts involving extortion
but acquitted on a fifth count, conspiracy to kidnap, faces life in prison under
the so-called federal three strikes law because of his prior convictions.
Sentencing was set for Aug. 4.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ramsey Investigator Quits Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A Denver private investigator working for John and Patsy
Ramsey to help solve their daughter's slaying announced today that he has left
the investigation. In a written statement, H. Ellis Armistead said he ended his
work on the JonBenet Ramsey case because of ''the events that are taking place
in the media.'' He did not elaborate and could not be reached for further
comment today.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nasdaq Rises 231; Dow Ends Up 143
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index wrapped up its best week in
history today as investors poured money back into the technology stocks they had
abandoned amid fears of rising interest rates. Stocks soared after the
government's employment report raised hopes that economic growth is slowing to a
less inflationary pace. The Nasdaq rose 230.88 points, or by 6.4 percent, to
close at 3,813.38. The index rose a stunning 19 percent this week. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 142.56 points to close at 10,794.76. For the week, the
Dow shot up 4.8 percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Beat Knicks, Make NBA Finals
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Reggie Miller scored 34 points and made five 3-pointers --
four in a span of 6{ minutes late in the game -- to lead the Indiana Pacers past
New York 93-80 tonight in Game 6 of the Eastern Conference finals. With the win,
the Pacers are vaulted into the NBA Finals for the first time ever. Returning to
Madison Square Garden, the scene of some of his greatest performances, Miller
played the villain again and came through in the clutch.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
