<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Images Hide Pacific Ethnic Tensions  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Flick through the tourist brochures and
South Pacific island nations could scarcely be more inviting:
swaying palm trees fringe white sandy beaches that gently slope
into the crystal waters studded with coral reefs.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the palm trees, the reality in many of the islands is
far from idyllic as traditionally tribal cultures struggle to adapt
to poverty and Western democracy imposed on them by colonial
masters who have long since left.
</P>
<P>
   The problems have been highlighted by the turmoil in Fiji, where
armed rebels stormed parliament on May 19 and took the
democratically elected government hostage, forcing the resignation
of the country's president and a military takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts fear the coup, led by failed businessman George
Speight, could spark more unrest across the South Pacific, which
looks to the Fijian capital Suva as its regional hub.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be more Speights in Fiji in the future and, one
fears, in other South Pacific states,'' Fiji expert Brij Lal of the
Australian National University wrote in Thursday's edition of The
Australian newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, some conflicts already were bubbling throughout the
region.
</P>
<P>
   -- In the Solomon Islands, one ethnic faction has taken up arms
to force another off the nation's main island, Guadalcanal. Dozens
of people have been killed in fighting in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   -- Parts of Papua New Guinea have been pushed close to anarchy
recently by infighting and lawlessness in a nation that hundreds of
tribes call home.
</P>
<P>
   -- International peacekeepers continue to patrol Bougainville, an
island in eastern Papua New Guinea. A 10-year secessionist war in
Bougainville cost thousands of lives before a cease-fire was signed
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   -- In Samoa, two former Cabinet ministers were sentenced to death
earlier this year for their part in the assassination of a
government colleague, a plot that revolved around attempts to stamp
out corruption. The ministers' sentences have since been commuted
to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Roderick Alley, a political science professor at Victoria
University in New Zealand's capital, Wellington, says many of the
Pacific's problems are rooted in attempts by former colonial powers
to impose Western democratic systems on traditionally tribal
societies.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a link in terms of colonial legacy of government
systems grafted on to these cultures,'' he said. ''Indigenous
people are complaining about the loss of their land or the
violation of culture and custom.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding credence to that argument is Tonga, one of the region's
most stable countries -- it is ruled by a prime minister appointed
for life by the country's monarch.
</P>
<P>
   Speight has claimed he launched his coup on behalf of all
indigenous Fijians, whom he says have been marginalized by a 1997
constitution that he claims gave Fijians of Indian descent too much
power.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry, taken hostage and then deposed
by Speight's coup, was Fiji's first ethnic Indian prime minister.
Indians descended from cane cutters brought to Fiji by British
rulers form a sizable minority in Fiji.
</P>
<P>
   But ethnic tensions are just one factor in the mix.
Mismanagement and corruption also has eroded government authority
throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   There is ''a legacy of poor public management ... and also quite
serious corruption in Papua New Guinea, a certain amount in the
Solomons, certainly some in Vanuatu,'' Alley said.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts agree the Pacific does not always live up to its
peaceful image, they cite some success stories.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Fry, of the Australian National University's Research
School of Pacific and Asian Studies, pointed to the Samoan
assassination case as ultimately a victory for law, order, strong
government and independent courts in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was dealt with as a murder, the people responsible are in
jail, and the government went on,'' Fry said.
</P>
<P>
   Peace has returned to the islands of New Caledonia after years
of sporadic violence between independence supporters trying to
break away from colonial ruler France and pro-Parisian forces. A
plan is in place for the country's transition to self-rule.
</P>
<P>
   And while there are still peacekeepers in Bougainville, a
cease-fire has held there for years and negotiations are under way
with a view to giving it limited autonomy from Papua New Guinea.
</P>
<P>
   But even in rock-solid democracies like New Zealand, there
remain rumblings from indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
   Speight was visited Friday by a delegation from a radical group
of Maori, New Zealand's first people.
</P>
<P>
   Tama Iti, spokesman for Tino Rangatira Tanga, a group that
advocates Maori sovereignty in New Zealand, said indigenous people
throughout the Pacific had been dominated by and discriminated
against by colonialist settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The colonialists ''got what they wanted through the barrel of a
gun,'' Iti said. ''The system of government we have in New Zealand
is based on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0115 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Chided in Luxembourg Standoff  </HEADLINE>
By CONSTANT BRAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The world's largest journalists' group
has asked that Luxembourg police tactics be investigated after
officers posing as a TV crew lured a gunman into an ambush to end a
hostage crisis. One journalism professor, however, said he would
excuse the deception because lives were saved.
</P>
<P>
   When the gunman emerged for an ''interview'' Thursday holding a
child in one arm and a grenade in the other, police posing as
cameramen shot him twice in the head. That led to the rescue of 25
children and three adults held hostage for about 30 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are disturbing tactics,'' cautioned Aidan White, general
secretary of the Brussels-based International Federation of
Journalists, which represents more than 450,000 journalists
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each year many journalists die reporting on incidents of
violence. ... Their life is dangerous enough without adding to
their difficulties,'' White said Friday in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Luxembourg police defended their strategy, saying it minimized
the threat to the hostages. Interior Minister Michel Wolter said
the hostage-taker's demand for TV airtime gave police an
opportunity to get a clear shot.
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern University journalism professor Nicholas Daniloff
said the tactic was ''a case of deception, and journalists as a
whole try not to be deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   And Fred Brown, chairman of the Society for Professional
Journalists' Ethics Committee, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''This just adds to the sense that journalists are not always
what or who they appear to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Daniloff said the situation called for extreme measures.
Since the hostages were freed unharmed and the hostage-taker
arrested, Daniloff said he would be inclined to forgive this case.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a question of saving lives,'' he said. ''You can
argue that the results justified what was done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostage-taker Neji Bejaoui, an unemployed Tunisian immigrant,
was shot at the day-care center in Wasserbillig, a village of 2,300
people in eastern Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Bejaoui was recovering from his injuries Friday after surgery,
and police said his wounds were no longer life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities released details Friday about the 39-year-old gunman
who brandished a pistol, a hand grenade and a knife as he seized
his hostages Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Luxembourg government said Bejaoui had a history of violence
and was convicted of assault in 1998. He had been seeing a
psychiatrist for several years. Its statement called Bejaoui ''very
unstable'' and said he suffers from paranoia and craves attention.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said Bejaoui, who lived in the nearby village of
Manternach and obtained Luxembourgish nationality in 1991, was
seeking to avenge a 1994 decision to deny him custody of his two
children. Residents of Wasserbillig said he blamed the day-care
center for the loss of custody when he and his wife separated.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Jean-Claude Juncker said police were forced to
act when Bejaoui demanded to flee in a car with three children. The
government said the decision to act also came after Bejaoui brought
crying children to the telephone, then refused to speak to police
negotiators.
</P>
<P>
   Police then sent in the two officers disguised as journalists
with Radio Television Luxembourg. Col. Pierre Reuland of the
Luxembourg police said the force requisitioned cameras and other
equipment from RTL.
</P>
<P>
   He refused to comment on reports police had used a gun hidden in
a camera, but RTL Station Manager Vic Reuter said the camera was
returned with no damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got a legal request, so we had no opportunity to refuse
it,'' Reuter told The Associated Press. ''They wouldn't tell us
what it was for. We discovered the use just like the rest of the
journalists, only after it had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Reuter said he had mixed feelings about the operation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course we are happy we could contribute (to the rescue). On
the other hand, we are journalists and are conscious of the fact
this might have consequences,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bejaoui seized 37 children and the three teachers Wednesday at
the Sparrow's Nest center. He released eight children that day and
then demanded a flight to take him to Libya. He freed two toddlers
Thursday morning and two more around noon, leaving three adults and
25 children aged 2 to 11 as hostages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
