<HEADLINE> Diamond Panel Planned in Congo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council has decided to create
a panel of experts to investigate how the exploitation of Congo's
diamonds and other natural resources has fueled the country's war.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member panel would take six months to collect
information on the illegal exploitation of resources -- traveling to
Congo and other countries if need be -- and report back to the
council with recommendations, according to a statement formally
adopted Friday by the 15 ambassadors.
</P>
<P>
   Congo has accused Rwanda and Uganda of backing rebels in the
country so they can have access to Congo's diamond and gold mines.
</P>
<P>
   The council's statement also suggested, however, that the team
would look into government-controlled exploitation of natural
resources and how that has prolonged the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The statement distinguished between ''illegal exploitation''
that violates Congo's sovereignty and how the basic ''exploitation
of the natural resources and other forms of wealth'' has fueled the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have accused President Laurent Kabila's government of
using its diamond holdings to solicit support from neighboring
countries in its war against the rebels. Zimbabwe, Namibia and
Angola have backed Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council, already concerned at how diamonds have
fueled Angola's civil war, asked Secretary-General Kofi Annan in a
January resolution to suggest ways to curb the exploitation. Backed
by France, Annan recommended a panel of experts, similar to the one
that uncovered massive violations of a diamond ban on Angola's
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Annan has also recently suggested that the council look into how
Sierra Leone's rebels have benefitted from that country's diamond
mines, which some estimate have earned the rebels $200 million a
year since 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0116 </TRAILER>
