<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Integrating Russia  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- President Clinton is taking a mixed message of
hope and concern over the future of democracy in Russia to his
first summit meeting with President Vladimir Putin. Clearly,
though, he is extending a hand of friendship to the new leader.
</P>
<P>
   After a close-up look at an emerging new course in European
politics, known as a Progressive or Third Way movement, Clinton was
flying today to Moscow with limited expectations of persuading
Putin to help clear a way for a new U.S. anti-missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   Candid about concerns over Russia's future, and speaking after
another move by Putin to consolidate his power over regional
chiefs, Clinton said Friday on what probably is his last trip to
Europe as president that much needs to be done to achieve European
unity. And that, he said, includes the development of ''a Russia
that is fully democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Expressing concern about Russia's direction and dismay over its
forceful crackdown on rebels in the republic of Chechnya, Clinton
also said ''there clearly is reason for hope in Russia's remarkable
journey over these last few years from dictatorship to democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That means no doors can be sealed shut to Russia,'' he
declared, specifically mentioning NATO, the Western military
alliance, and the 15-nation European Union which focuses on trade
and security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Full normalization of relations with Moscow will bring about
''the end of our vision of an undivided continent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is eyeing Clinton, as well. The former KGB official is
known for listening intently and saying little. He has already
warned that if Clinton chooses to go ahead with a missile shield
against North Korea, Iran and other so-called ''rogue states,''
Russia might abandon the whole regimen of arms control accords with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aims to reassure Putin that Russia was not the target of
the anti-missile shield. He is offering to share some of the future
technology with Russia and with other ''civilized'' friendly
nations.
</P>
<P>
   And once in Moscow, Clinton and Putin are expected to announce
their intention to cooperate in strengthening early warning
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reflected on Europe's past and its future in Aachen as
he accepted the Charlemagne Prize, awarded annually by the town's
city fathers to those who do the most to advance European unity.
</P>
<P>
   He is the third American to win the award in its 50-year
history, and the first U.S. president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited the sacrifices of many Americans who helped
rebuild Europe in the years since World War II, and to the work of
previous recipients.
</P>
<P>
   In a sun-drenched ceremony Friday outside the city's famed
Aachen cathedral, Clinton saluted the ''shining light of European
union.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Europe is more united, more democratic and more peaceful than
ever,'' Clinton said. But, he added, ''The job or rebuilding Europe
is not finished.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the ''first piece of unfinished business'' was to
resolve long-simmering tensions in southeastern Europe. He said
that not only means peace in the Balkans but a full partnership for
Turkey with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
   As for Russia, Clinton said, ''There is certainly reason for
hope,'' despite many remaining obstacles and the state of Russia's
still-fragile democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he cited ''Russia's remarkable journey'' since the fall
of the Berlin Wall in 1989 and told a crowd of several hundred
villagers and international dignitaries:
</P>
<P>
   ''We must build real institutional links to Russia. It will not
be easy. But it is possible, and absolutely necessary,'' the
president said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0116 </TRAILER>
