<DOCNO> APW20000603.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czar Nicholas II To Be Canonized  </HEADLINE>
By ANNA DOLGOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- After years of deliberation, the Russian Orthodox
Church seems close to canonizing the nation's last czar, Nicholas
II -- already regarded as a saint by many Orthodox believers.
</P>
<P>
   The church's council of bishops will meet in August, and it is
expected to rule that Czar Nicholas Romanov and his family deserve
sainthood for the humble way in which they accepted death at the
hands of the communist Bolsheviks, said Father Maxim Maximov,
secretary of the Holy Synod's commission on canonization.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my view it will be positive,'' Maximov said of the
council's decision.
</P>
<P>
   A weak but imperious ruler, Nicholas was executed in 1918 by a
Bolshevik firing squad. He has already been canonized as a martyr
by the Russian Orthodox Church Abroad, a group that broke away from
the Moscow patriarchate over its acceptance of the Soviet regime.
</P>
<P>
   The exiled church has made Nicholas' canonization by the Moscow
patriarchate a precondition for reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Many inside the main branch of the Church are also pushing for
the czar to be declared a saint, with some clerics telling their
parishioners that he is already a saint, regardless of the Church's
official decision.
</P>
<P>
   A weeping icon of Nicholas has been touring Orthodox churches;
the myrrh that it leaks is regarded as a miracle, and evidence of
the czar's sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   ''Canonization has already taken place, for the Lord himself has
glorified him, and weeping are his icons,'' said Father Igor
Konkov, a priest who leads the congregation at the 17th-century
Church of the Nine Martyrs in central Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ''For a believer, the question is settled,'' Konkov said. ''It's
our (church) hierarchy that's holding it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Scaffolding reaches to the ceiling of the dimly lit nave of the
church, which is covered with frescoes. The church has become a
center of grass-roots support for canonizing the last czar.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-aged parishioner stood near the entryway, holding out a
small reproduction of the weeping icon as he spoke of the miracles
he believes it has worked.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have been healed, and their everyday problems have been
solved,'' said the parishioner, who gave only his first name,
Alexander. ''People ask and receive what they have asked for.''
</P>
<P>
   The patriarchate still refuses to give the Romanovs martyr
status, which is meant for those who have died for their faith. But
the Synod's commission has recommended that the family be canonized
as passion-bearers, for suffering their fate with Christian
humility, Maximov said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nicholas II rejected offers by foreign governments to smuggle
him out of the country,'' Maximov said.
</P>
<P>
   An aura of mystery and violence surrounds the last czar, and
believers talk about his canonization as a sacred obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Russia carries the burden of the sin of regicide,'' said
Alexander. ''And to atone for this sin, it takes repentance by
every person, and the glorification of the sovereign.''
</P>
<P>
   Deeper inside the Church of the Nine Martyrs, almost deserted on
a Friday afternoon, an elderly woman with a dark scarf covering her
head was bent in prayer over a copy of another icon of Nicholas.
Believers say that portrait once leaked blood -- a miracle and
potent sign in the Orthodox tradition.
</P>
<P>
   After Nicholas and his family were shot by the Bolsheviks, their
bodies were burned and the remains dumped in a mass grave outside
the Ural Mountains city of Yekaterinburg.
</P>
<P>
   The nine skeletons were recovered from a roadside pit in 1991,
and repeated DNA testing confirmed their identities as Nicholas,
his wife, three of their children and four servants.
</P>
<P>
   The remains were reburied in 1998 in St. Petersburg, the
traditional place of interment for the royal dynasty. The bodies of
Nicholas' two other children were never found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0119 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Town Welcomes New Bush Ranch  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN PARROTT
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRAWFORD, Texas (AP) -- The road to Gov. George W. Bush's country
home winds through rolling pastures dotted with wildflowers and
cactus, chin-high stalks of corn and bales of golden hay.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle outnumber people along Prairie Chapel Road, the stretch
in western McLennan County where Bush bought a 1,580-acre spread
last August and is building a new home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can get out in the middle of that ranch and talk to the
cows,'' Bush said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's when they start talking back that makes me a little
nervous,'' he joked in that interview, with Yahoo on the Internet.
But he concluded more seriously, ''I do get away and I can find
solitude and that's really important.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the nearby town of Crawford say Bush has found the
perfect place to escape big city bustle and high-pressure politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good town to wind down in,'' said Lola Solero, who runs
an antique store called the Lonesome Dove. ''There's nothing
nerve-racking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the one-stoplight town of 700 say they hope Bush's new
weekend home will become a vacation Texas White House if the
Republican contender wins the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can see it attracting tourists and small businesses to
town,'' said Mayor Robert Campbell. He said he hopes Bush will
follow the example of President Johnson, who often returned to his
LBJ Ranch near Johnson City and delighted in showing off the land
to visitors.
</P>
<P>
   From the road, Bush's new ranch looks like any other farmland in
the area. There are no signs with the Bush name on the fenced-in
property. The only entrance, by a dirt road, has a locked metal
gate.
</P>
<P>
   The property is about 18 miles west of Waco, about 90 miles
north of the governor's mansion in Austin and just northeast of
Fort Hood, which could be used to land Air Force One.
</P>
<P>
   The big draw for Bush and his wife, Laura, was the beautiful and
varied topography, said Kenneth Engelbrecht, whose family sold Bush
the property. Bush has not released financial details of the
purchase but local real estate agents have said the land is
probably worth $800 to $900 per acre, or at least $1.2 million. The
county tax appraiser's office says the market value is $988,353.
</P>
<P>
   The property, which adjoins a tributary of the Middle Bosque
River, features waterfalls cascading over limestone cliffs, hiking
trails and plains of native grasses and wildflowers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew if they ever saw it, they'd have to have it. It's that
pretty,'' said Engelbrecht, who has lived there his entire life and
still oversees the property and several hundred head of cattle.
</P>
<P>
   The Bushes have renovated a 60-year-old farmhouse that
Engelbrecht's parents built, and are building another home on the
property.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will have a huge porch that wraps around the house that
catches all the southerly breezes,'' said Texas Secretary of State
Elton Bomer, a Bush family friend.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, an avid fisherman, has built a private fishing lake on the
land, which will be stocked with largemouth bass, Bomer said.
</P>
<P>
   And Mrs. Bush has insisted that contractors building the new
house preserve trees on the property, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The property also has native wildlife, including turkey, but
Bush said he has no plans to go hunting for the big birds.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd rather look at them than shoot them,'' he told Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors say they know the Bushes are in town only when they
see a convoy of cars or Secret Service agents buying hamburgers at
the town's only restaurant, a converted gas station called The
Coffee Station.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his wife sold their home in Dallas after his 1994
election as governor. They've been living in the governor's mansion
since then.
</P>
<P>
   Some Crawford residents say they hope Bush's presence leads to
economic development in Crawford, which consists of two blocks of
mostly empty storefronts on Texas Highway 317.
</P>
<P>
   The town once had four grocery stores, a drugstore, movie
theater and car dealership. Now most residents work and shop in
Waco, although the city does boast five churches and a growing
school district.
</P>
<P>
   Max Shaw said he has mixed feelings about the impact of his
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''We might get a grocery store again,'' Shaw said. ''But then
again I might have to quit (raccoon) hunting out there. The Secret
Service might not like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0119 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passengers Wait 8 Hours on Runway  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- About 200 passengers on a United Airlines flight
bound for Washington, D.C. sat on the runway at O'Hare
International Airport for more than eight hours Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Flight 1806 was scheduled to take off at 1:44 p.m. The wheels
finally left the tarmac at 9:53 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 777 was one of hundreds delayed by a string of
thunderstorms on the East Coast, United Airlines spokesman Kurt
Ebenhoch said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was only one flight path open and that was through St.
Louis and priority was given to flights already in the air,''
Ebenhoch said. He said air traffic controllers continued to delay
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had known the delay would have been this long, we would
never have left (the gate),'' Ebenhoch said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was forced to return to the gate twice, once to refuel
and once to replace crew members who had been on duty too long
under Federal Aviation Administration rules.
</P>
<P>
   There were no meals available to the passengers during the
delay, but Ebenhoch said the flight crew passed out granola bars
stored on the plane for unexpected delays.
</P>
<P>
   United decided not to cancel the flight because all the other
storm delays would have made it difficult for the passengers to
make other plans to reach their destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Some passengers were allowed to make brief trips into the
terminal when the plane was called back, but most remained onboard
during the delay, Ebenhoch said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, winter weather led to a similar flight delay at
Detroit Metropolitan Airport, with passengers stranded aboard a
Northwest Airlines flight for more than eight hours. The incident
led to a class-action lawsuit filed by passengers inconvenienced by
the delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0120 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Senator Questions SBA Practices  </HEADLINE>
By OWEN S. GOOD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican senator wants answers from Small
Business Administration chief Aida Alvarez for why employees sign
their own travel expense vouchers and why she has spent so much
time on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., said in a statement that those
practices amount to an abuse of the SBA's travel and expense
accounts. In a letter to Alvarez dated Thursday, Coverdell, R-Ga.,
a member of the Senate Small Business Committee, also criticized
the SBA's use of ''advance teams,'' and the practice of SBA
employees approving their own trips and reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am troubled by the potential abuse of taxpayer dollars by
the SBA,'' Coverdell said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell listed 63 SBA employees who approved their own
expenses without review in the past year, and gave eight examples
of their expense vouchers, ranging from $250 to $2,000. All but two
of the 63 cases involved either district directors or regional
administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell also upbraided Alvarez for spending one-quarter of her
working days on the road ''in light of the agency's problems in its
core programs.'' And he asked why advance personnel were necessary
for SBA trips when the agency has 70 field offices, some of which
are staffed by as many as 50 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''It baffles me why you as the Administrator of the SBA need an
'advance team' under any circumstances,'' Coverdell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate comment from the SBA.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Small Business Committee Chairman Christopher S. ''Kit''
Bond, R-Mo., requested the travel expense documents from the SBA a
year ago, according to Coverdell's letter.
</P>
<P>
   ''The paperwork provided by the SBA raises some troubling issues
about potential abuse of taxpayer dollars,'' Coverdell's chief of
staff, Zaid Ojakli said Friday. ''And we're looking forward to an
explanation from them.''
--------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
