<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners 7, Padres 4  </HEADLINE>
By JIM COUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Jamie Moyer returned from a seven-week stint on
the disabled list and pitched five innings for the win as the
Seattle Mariners beat the San Diego Padres 7-4 Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Martinez, who hit .441 with 10 homers, 32 RBIs and 24 runs
scored in May, picked up where he left off in the new month by
going 2-for-5 with a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez got to stay in the lineup because the designated hitter
is used in interleague games played at AL parks.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer (3-1), who was sidelined because of a strained muscle in
the back of his left shoulder, was activated before the game. He
gave up Tony Gwynn's single and Phil Nevin's 14th home run in the
first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer limited the Padres to two hits in the next four innings
before being replaced by Brett Tomko.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Sprague, replacing Ryan Klesko at first base, committed a
two-run throwing error in the second to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   After John Olerud led off the Seattle second with a double, Matt
Clement (5-4) walked Jay Buhner. David Bell bunted and Sprague
threw wildly over second baseman Bret Boone, allowing both runners
to score.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko did not start because of a slightly stiff back. He
pinch-hit in the ninth and struck out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners went ahead with two runs in the third. With one
out, Martinez singled and Clement followed with walks to Olerud and
Buhner to load the bases. Bell hit an RBI single and Dan Wilson had
a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   After Alex Rodriguez drew a walk from Matt Whiteside in the
seventh, Martinez followed with his 16th home run of the season.
The Mariners got another run in the inning when Mark McLemore drew
a bases-loaded walk by Carlos Almanzar.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres scored twice in the eighth on Nevin's RBI single and
a wild pitch. Kazuhiro Sasaki pitched the ninth for his eighth save
in nine chances.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer, pitching for the first time since April 14, struck out
three and walked one.
</P>
<P>
   Clement, who lost for the fourth time in his last five
decisions, had three wild pitches, giving him 12 for the season and
tying him with Cincinnati's Scott Williamson for the most in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
Notes: San Diego lost for the second time in eight games. ...
Seattle's Rickey Henderson came out of the game after six innings
because of a stiff neck. ... 3B Carlos Guillen was optioned to
Triple-A Tacoma when the Mariners activated Moyer. Guillen was
hitting .143 with no home runs and five RBIs in 23 games this
season. He began the season as Seattle's starting 3B, but lost his
job when he went on the DL April 13-27 with a pulled left
hamstring. ... The Padres announced that LHP Matt Whisenant has
cleared waivers and been outrighted to Triple-A Las Vegas.
Whisenant was designated for assignment on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
