<HEADLINE> Blue Jays Said Up For Sale Again  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Interbrew SA, the Belgian brewery that owns the
Toronto Blue Jays, will soon receive a new set of offers to buy the
team, the Toronto Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Among those interested in purchasing the team, valued at $150
million by its owner, are Rogers Communications, Bell Canada
Enterprises, CanWest Global and Sportsco, which last year bought
the SkyDome, the Blue Jays' ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Although baseball commissioner Bud Selig said Friday he hasn't
heard anything about a proposed sale, a Blue Jays official speaking
on the condition he not be identified said the organizations are
among the ''multiple parties interested'' in the team.
</P>
<P>
   Interbrew had the team up for sale in 1997, but yanked the
two-time World Series champions off the market because the
uncertainty distracted many of the team's top players.
</P>
</TEXT>
