<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Land Mine Detection Devloped  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID PITT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- With land mines left over from past wars posing a
threat to peacetime populations, scientists at Georgia Institute of
Technology say they may have a way of detecting the devices as they
lay hidden from sight.
</P>
<P>
   The trick? Detect them with sound.
</P>
<P>
   Associate professor Waymond Scott and his team of researchers
say they have made progress with a system that shakes the ground to
create sound waves that could be used to detect all kinds of mines.
</P>
<P>
   Their findings were presented Friday at the 139th annual meeting
of the Acoustical Society of America in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The team has been testing the system in the lab with anti-tank
and anti-personnel land mines.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to take the experimental system out into the field
doing the studies we're doing now in a more real environment,''
Scott said. ''The first most important thing we need to clearly
understand is how waves in the ground interact with mines so that
we can reliably detect them and find the best way to configure
different sensors.''
</P>
<P>
   Current systems using ground-penetrating radar can't tell the
difference between mines and rocks, roots, cans or sticks, Scott
said. Metal detectors, on the other hand, see every metal can,
scrap and shell casing, resulting in a high false alarm rate.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, there are 26,000 injuries or deaths a year from land
mines and about 100 million mines remain buried, according to
statistics compiled by the State Department, Red Cross and United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Tech mechanical and electrical engineers and
students are experimenting with a system that uses an
electrodynamic shaker in direct contact with the soil to create
measurable sound waves. As the waves travel through the ground, a
radar measures changes when the waves bounce off of a land mine.
</P>
<P>
   Scott predicted that a manufactured system to detect mines could
be from five to 10 years away.
</P>
<P>
   ''These things always take much longer than it would seem
because some of these things that seem rather simple can take a
long time to figure out the first time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Acoustical Society of America: http://asa.aip.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
