<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Reporters Held in Philippines  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOLO, Philippines (AP) -- Muslim rebels holding 21 hostages on a
southern Philippine island captured a group of German journalists
and held them for ransom, police said today.
</P>
<P>
   The group, together with a Filipino coordinator and two other
people, were released late Friday after paying $25,000 to members
of the Abu Sayyaf group, Inspector J.G. Sabdani of the Sulu
provincial police force said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists -- three from Germany's ZDF television, two from
Sat. 1, two from RTL television and one Der Spiegel reporter -- were
stopped by the rebels in the village of Bandang in Talipao near
Jolo, about halfway to the rebel camp.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels took their personal belongings like shoes,
wristwatches, bags, notebooks and other valuables, police said. One
journalist said the rebels also seized a satellite telephone.
</P>
<P>
   They were herded inside a cottage where the rebels demanded $1
million for their freedom, but the amount was later lowered to
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels then told four of the journalists to go back to Jolo
to collect the cash and threatened to behead one of those remaining
if they do not return with the money. The group was released after
the four handed over the cash, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The group had planned to visit the rebel camp to interview 21
hostages -- three Germans, two French, two Finns, two South
Africans, a Lebanese, nine Malaysians and two Filipinos -- who were
seized from the Malaysian resort of Sipadan April 23 and taken to
Jolo Island in the southern Philippines, about an hour away. Jolo
is 590 miles south of Manila.
</P>
<P>
   A government negotiating panel met rebel leaders for their first
round of talks to free the hostages last week.
</P>
<P>
   Chief negotiator Robert Aventajado said today he expects the
second round of talks to be held next week.
</P>
<P>
   In the first negotiations, Aventajado rejected two of the Abu
Sayyaf's three formal demands -- an independent Islamic state and a
commission to investigate the treatment of Filipinos in neighboring
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels also asked that foreign fishing boats be prevented
from poaching.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels said they will prepare a response to the government's
stance before the second round of negotiations. The rebels are
expected to also ask informally for a sizable cash payment.
</P>
<P>
   While the Abu Sayyaf, the smaller of two guerrilla groups
fighting for an independent Islamic state, espouse political
ideals, many say they are bandits who survive by kidnapping and
extortion. Most agree, however, that crime and disaffection in the
southern Philippines stem from poverty and discrimination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
