<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phone Book Misidentifies President  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENEVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- It's not a wrong number in a phone
book but the wrong name of a native son that has callers abuzz in
northeastern Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Although Andrew Johnson's statue in downtown Greeneville graces
the cover of the new Sprint Yellow Pages, the nation's 17th
president has been misidentified as fellow Tennessean Andrew
Jackson, the seventh president.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess it's appropriate that in the new century, people still
don't know who Andrew Johnson is or where he's from,'' said Tom
Ferguson, president of the Greene County Partnership/Chamber of
Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But local residents know.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the first president to be impeached -- in 1868 over
his dispute with Congress on Reconstruction -- and attendance at the
Andrew Johnson National Historic Site in Greeneville shot up after
President Clinton was impeached in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wilhoit, a spokesman for Kansas City, Mo.-based Sprint, said
the error is ''embarrassing in a big way,'' but a correction isn't
likely because many of the 48,000 copies of the phone book already
have been distributed.
</P>
</TEXT>
