<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bob Hope Makes Mark on Hometown  </HEADLINE>
By BART JONES
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) -- Bob Hope Drive. Bob Hope Cultural
Center. The Bob Hope-Chrysler Golf Classic.
</P>
<P>
   It's impossible to miss the impact that the 97-year-old
entertainer has had on the Palm Springs region, flush with second
homes for Hollywood's rich and famous, presidents, magnates and
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   As Hope recovers from a bout of gastrointestinal bleeding, many
people in the sun-soaked Coachella Valley paused to reflect on just
how much he means to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bob Hope is Palm Springs and that's how we all feel,'' Mark
Graves of the Palm Springs/Desert Resorts Convention and Visitors
Authority, said Friday. ''He's been the driving force behind
building the valley.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope's presence is everywhere. He's the honorary mayor of Palm
Springs and host of the well-known golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Even Eisenhower Regional Medical Center, where Hope is being
treated, wouldn't have been built without him -- Hope donated the
100 acres of land on which the hospital is built.
</P>
<P>
   Hope was taken to hospital Thursday and received blood
transfusions before the bleeding in his colon stopped. He was in
critical condition early today, but Dr. Gary Annunziata said he
expected that to change shortly.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital was taking in hundreds of faxes from around the
world with encouraging words for Hope, Annunziata said.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital lobby already features a Bob Hope showcase with a
large portrait of him and his wife, Dolores, along with
memorabilia, including some of his golf clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Next door is the Dolores Hope Outpatient Care Center.
</P>
<P>
   When newcomers arrive in the Palm Springs area, one of the first
things they do is drive over to see Hope's house in Rancho Mirage,
said Eisenhower spokeswoman Lea Goodsell.
</P>
<P>
   There used to be a time when callers to the Convention Center
were greeted by an answering machine with a recording from -- who
else -- Bob Hope.
</P>
<P>
   His weeklong golf tournament each year gives the region several
days of national TV exposure and injects about $30 million into the
local economy, said longtime Hope friend Bob Bremson. The
tournament donates $1 million to the hospital and pumps additional
money into other charities.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just an awesome man,'' said Rosemary Lopez of nearby La
Quinta. The 32-year-old housewife and mother of two said she and
her family would often see Hope around town, and he always waved.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, whose father had a heart attack Friday, said she met Mrs.
Hope in the hospital elevator and she appeared to be in good
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Hope started coming to Palm Springs in the 1930s after he
arrived in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ''Originally it was his hideout,'' Bremson said. But others soon
discovered it.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the desert region around it is a fabricated paradise.
Once covered with brush and cactus surrounded by craggy mountains,
it is now covered with golf courses, mansions and lush grass yards
that require nearly constant watering.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Hollywood stars arrived, most of the land was owned
by Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   The year-round population stands at 260,000 people and jumps to
a half million during the winter, when snowbirds from northern
states arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Rancho Mirage is known as a playground for presidents -- golf
lovers Dwight Eisenhower and Gerald Ford have had homes here.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists drive down Frank Sinatra Drive, Gerald Ford Drive,
Dinah Shore Drive and Ginger Rogers Road. The medical center is on
Bob Hope Drive.
</P>
<P>
   Though is name is everywhere, locals say Hope is no snob around
town, often seen treating a friend to an ice cream cone or sharing
dinner at a local restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   And when he drives around town, it isn't in some limousine with
dark windows, Lopez added.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's such a down-to-earth person.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hope Enterprises Inc.: http://www.bobhope.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
