<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 02:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainer Bob Hope Hospitalized  </HEADLINE>
By BART JONES
<TEXT>
<P>
   RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) -- Bob Hope is well enough to sit up
and watch television, but isn't up to cracking any jokes yet about
the medical condition that put him in the hospital, his doctor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hope still was listed in critical condition early today,
Dr. Gary Annunziata said he expected that to change shortly.
</P>
<P>
   He said the 97-year-old entertainer appeared to be making a
speedy recovery from the gastrointestinal bleeding for which he was
hospitalized on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The condition is common in older people and not considered
life-threatening. ''This kind of thing will cure itself,'' the
doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   Hope's vital signs were strong, he was taking liquids and was
well enough Friday to take in a little television, Annunziata said.
But so far, the doctor said Hope hadn't cracked any jokes with him.
</P>
<P>
   The master of the one-liner was taken to Desert Regional Medical
Center in Palm Springs after waking up with stomach pains Thursday
morning. He later was moved to Eisenhower Regional Medical Center
where, coincidentally, he had been scheduled for a checkup on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital spokeswoman Lea Goodsell said Hope's spirits were
clearly improving.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's shaking hands, smiling,'' she said. ''We're starting to
see the essence of Bob Hope emerge from all the treatments.''
</P>
<P>
   Delores Hope, the entertainer's wife of 66 years, hasn't left
her husband's side since his hospitalization and was watching
television with him on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we need a crowbar to get her away from him,''
Annunziata said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0250 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 05:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urged To Note Chechen Murder  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW KRAMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- In a report loaded with harrowing descriptions of
murder, rape and looting, Human Rights Watch has detailed an
alleged Russian rampage in Chechnya and urged President Clinton to
push Russia to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The New York-based rights group released the report on Friday,
one day before Clinton was to arrive in Moscow for a summit with
President Vladimir Putin. The United States has criticized Russia
for its offensive in Chechnya, but the summit is expected to focus
on other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The report gives an expanded account of previous allegations
that Russian servicemen went on a rampage in Aldi, a suburb of the
Chechen capital Grozny, a few days after rebels fled the relentless
Russian assault on the city.
</P>
<P>
   At least 60 civilians were killed by angry and drunk soldiers
who plowed through the suburb, shooting at will -- even at children,
the elderly and household pets -- the report says.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some killings were accompanied by demands for money or
jewelry, which served as a pretext for execution if the amount was
insufficient,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The soldiers were not happy with 300 rubles ($10) and shot him
and Zina and Khussein Abdulmezhidov in the yard,'' Aldi resident
Luisa Abulkhanova was quoted as saying, referring to friends and
neighbors who were victims. The report also gives accounts of six
rapes.
</P>
<P>
   After initial denials, Russian authorities have assigned three
civilian prosecutors to the case, but have refused to classify the
incident as a war crime.
</P>
<P>
   But ''as far as we know, not one serviceman has been suspended
from duty, let alone indicted, for the wholesale massacre of
civilians,'' said Human Rights Watch researcher Malcolm Hawkes.
''There's a culture of impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We are urging President Clinton to push the massacre in Aldi
firmly on the agenda with President Putin,'' said Hawkes.
</P>
<P>
   The killing reportedly began Feb. 5, after rebel fighters had
fled the capital and some residents were just beginning to relax,
believing the war had passed them by. Police units were conducting
a sweep operation intended to locate rebels disguised as civilians,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops entered the suburb on Feb. 4, after the city had
endured five months of siege and daily bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone, especially the elderly, were happy that everything
was over. That night was the first night my father slept in the
house,'' the report quoted Aldi resident Sultan Aidayev as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has criticized Russia for using excessive force in
Chechnya and is expected to repeat this objection during the
summit. But Washington has taken no action against Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations called on Russia last month to open an
inquiry into allegations of massacres and other war crimes, but
Russia's response has been slow.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged killings at Aldi were one of three reported large
massacres in Chechnya. The two others reportedly occurred in the
village of Alkhan-Yurt in December and the Grozny suburb of
Staropromyslovskaya in January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0504 </TRAILER>
