<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 05:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Newspaper Temporarily Closed  </HEADLINE>
By DANICA KIRKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Kosovo's U.N. administrators
temporarily shut down a newspaper tied to Kosovo Albanian leader
Hashim Thaci today in a bid to crack down on reporting that
inspires hate and ethnic intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Police and NATO-led peacekeepers moved into the Pristina offices
of the newspaper, Dita, closing down the eighth floor of the
capital's press building and barring editors from their offices.
</P>
<P>
   The move is certain to fuel controversy over an April 27 article
that accused a U.N. translator of membership in a Serb paramilitary
organization. The translator was found stabbed to death two weeks
later.
</P>
<P>
   The unsolved crime sparked a dispute about whether the article
was an example of journalistic freedom, or simply irresponsible
reporting that fed the province's climate of hate.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations closed the newspaper's doors for eight days
to drive home the point that vigilante justice would not be
permitted in this troubled southern province, which is struggling
to overcome a decade of oppression under Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to send a message, imperfect as it is, that there is a
justice system,'' said U.N. spokeswoman Nadia Younes. ''You do not
take the law into your own hands.''
</P>
<P>
   In an executive order, the top U.N. administrator in Kosovo,
Bernard Kouchner, cited not only the article about slain U.N.
translator Petar Topoljski, but also Dita's lack of contrition
about the matter. The newspaper sent Kouchner an open letter
insisting it would continue to publish the names of individuals
''involved against Albanians.''
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner's order said the pattern ''would inevitably put such
persons at risk of life from vigilante violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Dita publisher Behlul Beqaj, a longtime political adviser to
Thaci, huddled outside Dita's offices with other staff members for
about 30 minutes after the closure, trying to decide what to do
next.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just like Milosevic,'' said Gezim Salihu, the newspaper's
managing editor. When asked how many police officers and NATO-led
peacekeepers were involved in the shutdown, Salihu simply said,
''Enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice by ethnic Albanian newspapers of branding
individual Serbs as war criminals -- most in advance of any formal
charge or even an investigation -- has alarmed Western officials who
administer the province. They say that freedom of the press must be
weighed against fears that vigilante justice will prevent Kosovo
from ever being at peace.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations and the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe have long debated whether to impose press
restrictions during the tense postwar period, but had refrained,
aware that such a move is likely to provoke criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Petar Topoljski, 25, who was found stabbed to death
May 14, however, seemed to push Kouchner to act in defense of one
of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Beqaj and editors across the capital, Pristina, argue that if
the Western officials had done a better job of organizing a
criminal justice system in Kosovo, they wouldn't feel compelled to
publish such allegations. For his part, Beqaj said he's not backing
down.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can say that if we discover the facts about an individual,
we are not doing it for hate,'' he said. ''But if we cover up the
facts, we will provoke more hate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0531 </TRAILER>
