<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Stage 28 Attacks in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Chechen guerrillas attacked Russian
positions in Chechnya 28 times over the past 24 hours while Russian
warplanes continued the bombardment of rebel bases in the southern
mountains, officials said today.
</P>
<P>
   Su-25 attack planes and helicopter gunships have flown 52 combat
missions since Friday, mainly attacking targets in the Argun and
Vedeno gorges, a key refuge for the rebels, the military command's
press service said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the press service, six rebel strongholds and a
communications facility were wiped out by the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops raided a rebel base near the southern village of
Sharo-Argun on Friday, killing 18 rebels and wounding 40, the
military said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   The command said military checkpoints and units of federal
forces are constantly being fired on in hit-and-run attacks, and
Russian positions had come under fire 28 times over the past 24
hours.
</P>
<P>
   They were the latest in a series of small attacks in
Russian-controlled territory that show the Chechen fighters are far
from defeated, despite Russian claims that organized rebel
resistance has been crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Ministry officials said today they had found and
neutralized several explosive devices planted by the rebels since
Friday. Two bombs were defused near a market in the village of
Kurchaloi and a road connecting Kurchaloi and the village of Novaya
Zhizn was cleared of mines, the officials said, according to the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops rolled into Chechnya in September, occupying the
lowland areas and driving rebel bands into mountain strongholds.
Though the rebels have not mounted large-scale operations recently,
they have stepped up guerrilla attacks that have cost the Russian
scores of casualties in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 500 rebels remain at large in the capital Grozny, the
military command's press service said today. They continue to
attack Russian positions and vehicles in Grozny, even though the
Russians took control of the Chechen capital more than four months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were driven out of Chechnya in a 1994-96 war.
They re-entered in September after Islamic militants based there
seized several villages in the neighboring Russian region of
Dagestan, and after about 300 people died in apartment bombings the
government blames on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
