<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dissidents Seek Tiananmen Deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Eight dissidents from northeast China have
appealed to the government to compensate those imprisoned and the
families of those killed in the Tiananmen Square crackdown 11 years
ago, a human rights group said today.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to President Jiang Zemin and Premier Zhu
Rongji, the dissidents said the government was ''absolutely wrong''
to crush the pro-democracy protests centered on Tiananmen Square,
said the Hong Kong-based Information Center for Human Rights and
Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The government sent in troops who shot their way through Beijing
on June 3-4, 1989, killing hundreds, possibly thousands, and ending
seven weeks of protests.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent commemorations, authorities stepped up security today
and extra military police patrolled in front of Tiananmen gate,
which overlooks the vast square in central Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Beijing dissident Ren Wanding said police visited his
home Friday and ''told me not to carry out any activities.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Ding Zilin, a prominent campaigner for victims of the
1989 crackdown whose 17-year-old son also was killed, said
plainclothes police were stationed outside her house and that her
phone had been cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Ding were unsuccessful. The phone appeared to ring but
no one picked up, even though Ding's friends said she was at home.
</P>
<P>
   In their letter, the dissidents, from northeastern Jilin
province, called for the release of political prisoners and for
political reforms and democracy, said the Information Center, which
reported the letter.
</P>
<P>
   They also demanded compensation for victims' families and for
the thousands of people imprisoned in the crackdown, and urged the
government to reverse its verdict that the 1989 demonstrations were
a ''counterrevolutionary rebellion'' that had to be quelled, the
Information Center said.
</P>
<P>
   It said the letter was drafted by dissident Liang Liwei and
signed by the seven others.
</P>
<P>
   The government has never allowed an investigation into the
crackdown or a full accounting of those killed, injured and
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   Families of those killed planned quiet memorials.
</P>
<P>
   Su Bingxian, whose 21-year-old son was killed with three bullets
to the chest, said she, her husband and their surviving two
children would spend this evening together in commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang Xianling said she placed flowers under a portrait at home
of her 19-year-old son who was killed and would visit his grave
Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0707 </TRAILER>
