<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 07:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Integrating Russia  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- President Clinton is taking a mixed message of
hope and concern over the future of democracy in Russia to his
first summit meeting with President Vladimir Putin. Clearly,
though, he is extending a hand of friendship to the new leader.
</P>
<P>
   After a close-up look at an emerging new course in European
politics, known as a Progressive or Third Way movement, Clinton was
flying today to Moscow with limited expectations of persuading
Putin to help clear a way for a new U.S. anti-missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is important is that President Putin is signaling that he
is open to discussions,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
told the German news media today.
</P>
<P>
   And, she said, it was ''very interesting'' that the Russian
leader seems to be saying there is some kind of threat from North
Korea and that ''we should look at it together.''
</P>
<P>
   But ultimately, she said, the decision Clinton is pondering
''must be a decision based on American national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   At the conference here on new political directions, Clinton said
there were ''great opportunities'' through global cooperation to
solve such problems as social injustice and hunger. ''There are
things we can do to help each other and help our people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the leaders agreed to set up groups to identify the
problems and move toward a practical way of dealing with them.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of unity, Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres
said experts would assemble in Lisbon next month to start work on
identifying the problems. ''We don't have to wait for the whole
architecture to be restructured to tackle these issues.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And President Ricardo Lagos of Chile said ''there is a very
important network to tackle future tasks, the values that we have
enshrined in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Lagos said cooperation in setting interest rates should be
considered.
</P>
<P>
   In a communique, the 14 leaders pledged to seek international
social agreements to promote ''an idea of community'' worldwide.
Special attention was called for in fighting unemployment and on
creating a climate that encourages the development of technology
and the entrepreneurial spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after another move by Putin to consolidate his power
over regional chiefs, Clinton said Friday on what probably is his
last trip to Europe as president that much needs to be done to
achieve European unity. And that, he said, includes the development
of ''a Russia that is fully democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Expressing concern about Russia's direction and dismay over its
forceful crackdown on rebels in the republic of Chechnya, Clinton
also said ''there clearly is reason for hope in Russia's remarkable
journey over these last few years from dictatorship to democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ''That means no doors can be sealed shut to Russia,'' he
declared, specifically mentioning NATO, the Western military
alliance, and the 15-nation European Union which focuses on trade
and security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Full normalization of relations with Moscow will bring about
''the end of our vision of an undivided continent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is eyeing Clinton, as well. The former KGB official is
known for listening intently and saying little. He has already
warned that if Clinton chooses to go ahead with a missile shield
against North Korea, Iran and other countries regarded by the
United States as ''rogue states,'' Russia might abandon the whole
regimen of arms control accords with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aims to reassure Putin that Russia was not the target of
the anti-missile shield. He is offering to share some of the future
technology with Russia and with other friendly nations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked today about his differences with Putin over a missile
defense system, Clinton said: ''We'll talk about it in Russia; it
won't be long now.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in Moscow, Clinton and Putin are expected to announce their
intention to cooperate in strengthening early warning systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 0719 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
