<HEADLINE> One U.N. Worker Freed in Georgia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) -- Kidnappers of a United Nations observer
team released one of five hostages Saturday, and the freed man
reported that all remaining captives were alive and being treated
well, a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnappers freed Ismed Zade, an ethnic Abkhazian who works for a
British non-governmental mine-clearing organization, said Veselin
Koshtev, the political counselor with the U.N. mission in Georgia.
Abkhazia is a separatist province of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The other hostages are Danish military observers, a Briton from
the mine-clearing organization, and an Abkhazian translator.
</P>
<P>
   The team was last seen on Thursday in the remote Kodor Gorge,
the only part of Abkhazia that is still under Georgian control.
They were reported missing on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Zade told U.N. representatives that all hostages were alive and
treated well, Koshtev said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the kidnappers planned to contact the authorities,
using radios seized from their captives.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. observers have been targeted previously in the region. Five
observers, a U.N. doctor and a translator were seized in October in
the Kodor Gorge, near where the team was working Thursday; all
seven were released unharmed after two days.
</P>
</TEXT>
