<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Aid to Latin America  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- President Clinton said Saturday that democracy
''is under great strain in Latin America,'' largely because of a
rise in drug-traffickers and terrorists in Colombia and other
nations, and urged action to strengthen governments under stress.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents of Brazil, Argentina and Chile joined 11 other
leaders at a Berlin conference on progressive governance.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been an enormous amount of economic and political
reform in Latin America in the last decade, but ... because of the
rise of narco-traffickers and terrorist activities in Colombia and
other countries, democracy is under great strain in Latin
America,'' Clinton said at a closing news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should make sure that we do whatever we can to see that the
economies work for ordinary citizens ... and that we try to
strengthen those governments that are under particular stress.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has worked to persuade Congress to help Colombia and
the other countries in the Andean regions to deal with the impacts
that narco-traffickers and civil wars have had on the region.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is weighing a proposed $1.6 billion in aid designed
mostly to combat drug trafficking, but also would bolster
Colombia's sagging economy and address social problems.
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism on Capitol Hill is based partly on the human rights
record of the Colombian Army and a suspicion of links between the
army and paramilitary units.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
