<HEADLINE> US Supports Serb Return From Croatia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) -- The United States will set aside $5
million to support the return of Serbs who left Croatia during and
after the 1991 war, according to a statement by the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The money will be used as a humanitarian assistance both for the
return and the reintegration of Serbs -- for the repair of houses
and to provide incentives to entrepreneurs
</P>
<P>
   On her visit to Bosnia in March, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright praised the efforts of Bosnia and Croatia for the return
of refugees and announced financial aid from the Clinton
administration totaling $1 million for the reconstruction of about
100 homes on each side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of good will, both sides agreed to let 4,000 Bosnian
Croat and Croatian Serb refugees return home within the next three
months. The refugees fled their homes during ethnic wars in the
Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, some 30,000 Serbs who fled Croatia now live in the
Serb part of Bosnia and about 70,000 Croats who escaped from their
homes in Bosnia took refuge in Croatia, according to U.N. figures.
</P>
