<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Withdraws Vote Observer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- The Commonwealth withdrew a senior election
observer from Zimbabwe on Saturday over his links to a firm with
close ties to the government of President Robert Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Moses Anafu was en route to London after being recalled from
the Commonwealth observer mission in Harare, Commonwealth
Secretary-General Don McKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   The mission is due to monitor Zimbabwe's June 24-25
parliamentary elections, which pit Mugabe's long-ruling Zimbabwe
African National Union-Patriotic Front party against the fledgling
Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   The Times newspaper reported Saturday that Anafu, a senior
Commonwealth adviser on Africa, was also a non-executive director
of Oryx Diamonds Ltd. Oryx holds a concession to sell diamonds from
areas of the Democratic Republic of Congo that are under Zimbabwean
military control.
</P>
<P>
   The British government and others have condemned the selling of
diamonds from African war zones.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon said Anafu last week had assured him that he had not
yet been appointed a non-executive director and had received no
remuneration from the company.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday Anafu admitted ''he had received payment for
some travel costs,'' McKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   Given Anafu's confirmation of his involvement with Oryx, ''it is
inappropriate that he continue to be involved in the Commonwealth
observer mission in Harare,'' McKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon added that the Commonwealth Secretariat would
''consider the wider implications of this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's election campaign has been marred by attacks on
opposition supporters and candidates that have led to more than 20
deaths, and overshadowed by the government's support for black
squatters who have occupied white-owned farms. The government
itself announced Friday that it would immediately start seizing 804
mostly white-owned farms
</P>
<P>
   The farmers say the agitation for land reform is really a cover
for a ZANU-PF terror campaign against the opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
