<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Loan Sharks Spark Debate  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT STODDARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Sales at Nobuhiro Komukai's construction company
were plunging, and he couldn't pay his 11 employees. He needed
cash, and quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But with mainstream banks slashing lending amid the country's
prolonged economic slump, Komukai turned instead to Nichiei Co.,
Japan's biggest non-bank commercial lender.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, the threatening calls demanding repayment started
pouring in -- and they continued every two hours, every day for
three months.
</P>
<P>
   Komukai's situation isn't unique. In Japan, tales of exorbitant
interest rates and overzealous collection tactics have made front
page news and been the focus of long hours of debate in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The victims are generally like Komukai -- the owners of small- or
medium-sized businesses strapped for cash by the worst economic
slump to hit Japan in decades.
</P>
<P>
   Shunned by banks, they got loans from what seemed to be
respectable financial institutions. What they found, however, was
not much different from the neighborhood loan shark.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was overcome with fear,'' Komukai said of the months of
calls he said began when he fell behind on his loan payments, which
included a 30 percent interest rate. He recently got Nichiei to
stop the calls by borrowing from a friend to pay off the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The burst of Japan's speculative bubble in the late 1990's left
many businesses in a cash-flow crunch. Banks, saddled with their
own debt, responded to the crisis by adopting tightfisted lending
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the economic downturn, commercial lenders in the
mid-1990s began listing their shares on the prestigious first
section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange, allowing them to gain access
to cheap loans from banks -- often borrowing at interest rates as
low as 1.7 percent and then lending to businesses like Komukai's at
rates as high as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mainstream banks, the commercial lenders require no
collateral as long as the borrower can find a guarantor.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Nichiei and Shoko Fund -- the second-biggest commercial
lender -- control about 90 percent of Japan's $76 billion small
business loan industry.
</P>
<P>
   Nichiei alone reported a net profit of $307.8 million for the
year that ended March 31, 1999, a 23 percent jump over the previous
year.
</P>
<P>
   Such profits have attracted investors such as United States
financial giants Goldman Sachs International, Chase Manhattan Bank
and State Street Bank and Trust, who are among the biggest
shareholders of Nichiei and Shoko Fund, according to Toyo Keizai, a
Japanese financial information service.
</P>
<P>
   The lenders play a crucial role.
</P>
<P>
   With banks refusing to provide loans, many small and
medium-sized businesses, the backbone of Japan's economy, would
likely collapse without lenders like Nichiei. An estimated 80,000
companies have borrowed from commercial lenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason why these firms have flourished over the last
decade is because the mainstream financial system has been dead in
the water,'' said Chris Calderwood, chief economist at Jardine
Fleming Securities (Asia) Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without their willingness to lend without collateral, many
more firms would have presumably bitten the dust,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a lack of regulation, critics say, has allowed overzealous
lenders too much leeway.
</P>
<P>
   Kenji Utsunomiya, a lawyer representing 150 Nichiei debtors who
have filed suit for alleged harassment, said the those making the
most money in Japan right now are ''loan sharks and commercial
lenders.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has responded to complaints by ordering Nichiei
to suspend operations at its 180 nationwide branches for one week
in February. And on Jan. 18, former Nichiei employee Eisuke Arai
was sentenced to 18 months in prison for trying to extort payments
from a loan guarantor.
</P>
<P>
   Nichiei spokesman Tomoharu Yoshida said the company has never
used violence to collect payments, but added that Nichiei -- whose
president and founder resigned in February -- is screening
prospective borrowers more closely now.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won't stop until we're certain that this won't happen
again,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1122 </TRAILER>
