<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Microcredit' Loans Give Big Help  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUASTATOYA, Guatemala (AP) -- Snow cones bought the house, the
stove, the 21-inch TV. They even have Berta Alicia Ortez and her
husband talking about indoor plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ''We used to worry about where the food was going to come
from,'' said Ortez, 32, who got a ''microcredit'' loan worth nearly
$260 three years ago and turned it into a snow cone cart. ''Now we
have enough money to build a new bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   Her savior is a heavy yellow bicycle frame fitted with a canopy,
a cooler for ice, a hand-crank blender, foam cups and white plastic
spoons and jars of strawberry, banana, chocolate and orange syrups.
</P>
<P>
   From this contraption, Ortez sells about 200 snow cones a day
for 1 quetzal each -- about 12 cents -- in this town of 2,000 people
in the mountains 45 miles northeast of Guatemala City.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hardest part is the hills,'' said Ortez, who has mounted a
car stereo over the bike's cooler to play a tune she pirated from
an ice-cream truck.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Ortez and seven other women formed the ''Friendship
Group,'' which secured a $270 loan from a local United
Nations-affiliated charity.
</P>
<P>
   The interest-free loan helped them open a small one-room store
near the center of a nearby village, El Progreso.
</P>
<P>
   ''All you needed was initiative,'' said Adilida Maroquin, 55,
who served as the group's president. ''It was like being paid for
an idea.''
</P>
<P>
   The shop, which offers Coke and Pepsi in glass bottles, purified
water and beef and bean tostados cooked by Maroquin in a tiny
kitchen, proved such a success that the women applied for
individual loans and struck out on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Some began making and selling tortillas. Some used plants to
make organic shampoo. Some became handicraft artists.
</P>
<P>
   Ilda Elsira originally applied for a loan to bake bread and sell
it out of her home. When that business stalled, she switched to
raising, slaughtering and selling chickens, an operation run
entirely out of her cluttered backyard.
</P>
<P>
   ''The best day for us is Sunday when we sell 25 chickens a lot
of times,'' said the 33-year-old. ''If you sell something as
popular as chickens you will never stop getting orders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1123 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Leaders Address Prosperity Gap  </HEADLINE>
By COLLEEN BARRY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- President Clinton, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
and a dozen world leaders endorsed a set of broad principles
Saturday meant to distribute more evenly the fruits of the
burgeoning global economy: wealth, technology and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The conference on ''Progressive Governance'' -- the new buzzword
for the attempt to balance pure capitalism with pure socialism --
expanded a core group of six nations that met in Florence in
November to include poorer countries trailing behind in an age of
rampant globalization.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders addressed that growing gap during the three-hour
session, announcing three programs that wealthy nations will pursue
at the next summit of the Group of Seven biggest industrial powers
and Russia. They are: spreading educational opportunities, closing
the technology gap and fighting infectious diseases, especially
AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe that you can have social justice and deal
with all these other challenges we face unless you have effective,
progressive government that makes the most of the new economy and
deals with its rough edges and difficulties as well,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't believe in just laissez-faire economics but we don't
believe that government alone can solve these problems or just
ignore them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rather grandiose goal of the conference is to improve
citizens' lives by focusing on issues once considered mostly
domestic -- but which increasingly bind nations in the complex
global economy -- such as immigration, education reform and job
creation.
</P>
<P>
   ''People want to live in a community, not merely work in a
market,'' the leaders said in a final statement.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said that entailed promoting ''common values,
democracy, social cohesion and the fight for human rights and
against racism and anti-Semitism.''
</P>
<P>
   The final document contained a number of broad pledges,
including one sought by Latin American participants for stronger
regulation of financial markets that have wreaked havoc on their
economies in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   South African President Thabo Mbeki said developing nations
understand and welcome the markets but want a voice in determining
the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need a global democratic system of policymaking,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders also stressed the need for new international social
agreements to promote ''an idea of community'' worldwide, to
coordinate the fight against unemployment and to create a climate
that encourages the development of technology and entrepreneurial
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The conference -- held in a former East German government
building decorated with stained glass windows honoring workers -- is
the most serious attempt by liberal leaders to take a coordinated
stab at solving problems outside of traditional international
forums that often exclude poorer countries.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders are also trying to address the critical problem of
how to apply common solutions to a collection of nations with
vastly different economic resources and social concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is not just with resources. The problem is how can
we forge cooperation,'' said Chilean President Ricardo Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the United States, Germany, Canada, France and Italy --
which all are members of both NATO and the G-7 -- the conference
included leaders from Sweden, the Netherlands, Portugal, Greece,
New Zealand, South Africa, Chile, Argentina and Brazil. British
Prime Minister Tony Blair, a leading proponent of the movement,
also known as the ''Third Way,'' skipped the conference to stay
home with his 2-week-old son, Leo.
</P>
<P>
   ''Progressive Governance and the Third Way are pro-family,''
Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1135 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Threat Shadows Summit  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- For more than a quarter-century, U.S.-Russian
summits have dwelled on ways to reduce the danger of nuclear
conflict. President Clinton's talks in Moscow this weekend are no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants a green light from President Vladimir Putin to
alter a landmark treaty banning national defenses against missiles.
On the theory that North Korea, Iran and possibly other ''rogue''
states might attack the United States in the years ahead, Clinton
is considering a partial shield. He is due to decide in late summer
or the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is weighing several factors, including cost and impact
on the carefully constructed architecture of arms control
agreements with the former Soviet Union and then Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Russia's initial insistence that construction of a
missile defense could touch off a race to build new missiles to
pierce the shield, Clinton's advisers were dampening any
expectations an accord will be concluded at the Moscow summit.
</P>
<P>
   In a pre-trip news conference, Sandy Berger, the president's
national security adviser, said he did not expect ''any
resolution'' of negotiations with Russia on a new round of cutbacks
in long-range nuclear warheads either.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said she
detected signals from Putin that he was open to discussion. But
ultimately, Albright said, the decision Clinton is pondering ''must
be a decision based on American national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin's signal of an openness to compromise came in an NBC-TV
interview in which he raised the possibility of working jointly
with the United States in building a defense against countries
whose missiles could threaten either nation.
</P>
<P>
   At Putin's urging, the Russian Duma, or lower house of
parliament, on April 14 approved the START II treaty that President
Bush concluded in his last days in office in January 1993. It sets
new and lower ceilings of 3,000 to 3,500 warheads apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are committed to working out a START III treaty
with even lower ceilings of 2,000 to 2,500. The Russians would go
further and pare down to 1,500, but the members of the U.S. Joint
Chiefs of Staff don't think that is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   With no sign of an agreement on defense or offense, Berger said,
''I never expected an issue as complex as this to be resolved in
this summit.''
</P>
<P>
   That is just as well in the view of Richard N. Haass, vice
president and director of foreign policy studies at the Brookings
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   ''The time is not right for major undertakings,'' Haass said.
Negotiations should be deferred for the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   Even more skeptical, Kim R. Holmes, vice president at the
Heritage Foundation, said even if Clinton and Putin managed to work
something out, it would run into stiff opposition in the
Republican-controlled Senate, where sentiment is strong against
committing the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a summit in search of a mission, and the worst thing
the President could do is to try to force an agreement on arms
control,'' Holmes said. ''It would be dead on arrival in the
Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   What would be worse, he said, would be to commit the next
president to an agreement he might have to undo, Holmes said.
</P>
<P>
   William E. Jackson Jr., an official with the U.S. Arms Control
Agency in the Carter administration, also is opposed to Clinton
taking up missile defenses with Putin this weekend -- but for
different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said the Clinton administration was going overboard in
trying to threaten the Russians -- with a breakout from the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty -- if the Russians won't give the
administration room to protect Vice President Al Gore from a
''soft-on-defense'' charge.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the likely Republican candidate for
the presidency against Gore, supports a far more extensive missile
defense than the one Clinton is considering.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, a senior U.S. official said recently that if Clinton
failed to persuade Putin to change the 1972 treaty, he would go
ahead with a decision on a limited defense -- 100 launchers and new
radar -- if he concludes that the program is in the U.S. national
interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1141 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 11:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estate Tax Explainer  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   How the estate tax works:
<TEXT>
<P>
   A person who dies in 2000 would owe taxes immediately on an
estate worth more than $675,000, unless the entire estate is left
to a surviving spouse, who can inherit it tax-free. When the
surviving spouse dies, an exemption of twice the single exemption
applies, which amounts to $1.3 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Tax rates begin at 18 percent on the first $10,000 of a taxable
estate and top out at 55 percent on those over $3 million. But
because of the $675,000 exemption, estate taxes in 2000 begin at
the 37 percent level.
</P>
<P>
   A 5 percent surtax is imposed on estates between $10 million and
$17.1 million. Above $17.1 million, the rate drops again to 55
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some special rules apply to family farms and small businesses.
They can claim a higher exemption of $1.3 million per person in
2000 and they can use special valuation rules to reduce estates by
up to $770,000. In addition, they can pay off estate taxes over 14
years at low interest rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1151 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
