<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts About Federal Estate Tax  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some facts about the federal estate tax:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Year created: 1916.
</P>
<P>
   Total estate tax returns in 1997: 42,901.
</P>
<P>
   Total adult deaths in 1997: 2.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Percent owing estate tax: 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gross value of 1997 taxable estates: $97.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gross value of 239 estates worth $20 million or more: $24.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gross value of 19,000 estates worth $1 million or less: $15.3
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Amount exempt from tax in 2000: $675,000 per person.
</P>
<P>
   Total estate tax revenue projected for 2000: $26.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue loss of gradual repeal through 2010: $105 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Annual revenue loss after full repeal: $50 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
