<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rich Stand To Gain From Tax Repeal  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Family farmers and small businesses are
leading the fight to repeal estate taxes, even though the very rich
stand to gain the most from such an action, sought by House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Internal Revenue Service records and independent studies show
that in 1997 about 20 percent of the taxable estates above the
exempt level of $600,000 were limited partnerships, closely held
stock, real estate or other typical assets held by small businesses
and farms.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, two-thirds of those taxable assets were stocks,
bonds, mutual funds, cash or insurance. Of the $97.6 billion in
gross taxable estates in 1997, almost half the value came from
those worth more than $5 million -- and the 329 richest had a
combined value of more than $24.6 billion combined.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of House members, including 45 Democrats, has found
merit in the case made by a powerful coalition: that the ''death
tax'' is killing farmers and small entrepreneurs, forcing farms to
be sold off and carved up by developers and forever eliminating
jobs provided by family businesses now compelled to liquidate.
</P>
<P>
   The House is set to vote this week on legislation that would
phase out the inheritance tax by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tax that is initiated by death, and I don't think that
should be a taxable event,'' said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., the
main GOP sponsor. ''These are very often normal people who have
worked hard all their lives. They are not multimillionaires.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 organizations are advocating repeal, including the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the National Federation of Independent
Business, the National Newspaper Association, a variety of farm
groups and associations representing winemakers, florists, factory
owners, grocers and insurance agents.
</P>
<P>
   Their print ad campaign shows a tombstone with an epitaph
reading, ''The Family Business.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they often talk of the devastating impact of the tax on
heirs, most of the real-life stories told by farmers and
small-business owners focus on the complicated and costly planning
steps they must take to avoid it. A simple estate tax plan can
easily cost $3,000, said Clint Stretch of the DeLoitte &AMP; Touche
accounting firm.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't show up in the statistics, but writing a check to
an estate tax planning lawyer is a pretty clear and present cost,''
Stretch said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Roger Hannay of Hannay Reels, Inc., of Westerlo,
N.Y., said he spends about $300,000 a year on insurance premiums to
ensure his manufacturing business does not have to be sold to pay
estate taxes, which would put his 150 employees put out of work.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still worry that I may have overlooked something that will
prevent my business from being passed on intact to my children,''
Hannay said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Appel, a wheat and barley grower in Colfax, Wash., said he
is ''concerned about how much time and money it will take to
consult countless attorneys and accountants about estate tax
planning.''
</P>
<P>
   To supporters, this estate tax planning burden falls most
heavily on the least wealthy farmers and entrepreneurs -- and even
more disproportionately on women and minorities -- while the richest
people can easily afford the costs and avoid the tax.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rich continue to find loopholes and the middle class gets
whacked,'' said Dan Brandenburg, federal affairs manager at the
National Federation of Independent Business.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has acted to ease the estate tax burden. A 1997 law
gives family-owned businesses and farms an exemption of up to $2.6
million per family this year, compared with $1.3 million for other
estates. They can also take advantage of special reduced-value
rules for estate purposes and defer tax payments for up to 14 years
at low interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''The trouble with the Republican leaders' approach is that it
gives colossal tax breaks to those who are already the most
fortunate,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, senior Democrat
on the House Ways and Means Committee. ''We can eliminate the
estate tax for all but the richest families and do it in a fiscally
responsible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangel has proposed an alternative that would raise exemptions
for farms and small businesses to $4 million per family and reduce
all rates by 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A similar approach is advocated by top White House officials,
who say President Clinton would veto the Republican repeal bill
partly because of its cost -- estimated at $50 billion a year when
the tax ends in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers and Clinton's
chief of staff, John Podesta, said in a letter to lawmakers that
the tax serves a purpose by ensuring that the wealthy cannot
entirely shield their incomes through tax shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ''The estate tax promotes the integrity and fairness of the
overall tax system by acting as a backstop to the income tax,''
they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 8
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: To read the bill, congressional site:
http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Repeal coalition: http://www.deathtax.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1152 </TRAILER>
