<HEADLINE> GOP Fights Lazy Congress Image  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republicans hoping to preserve their
thin majority this election year have reversed decades of stagnant
Democratic leadership with a slew of accomplishments, a congressman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those accomplishments include a balanced budget and welfare
reform, Rep. Brian Bilbray, R-Calif., said in the GOP radio address
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He was boasting of accomplishments that some Democrats point to
as accomplishments of President Clinton's administration. In fact,
they were the result of a cooperative effort.
</P>
<P>
   ''Despite 40 years of Democrat control, it took a Republican
Congess to clean the House,'' Bilbray. ''Oh yes, we've also
balanced the budget and provided the first surplus in a
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray said Republicans erased Congress' perennial ''do
nothing'' reputation with positive changes made in a bipartisan
manner.
</P>
<P>
   Among other achievements Bilbray cited: the lowering of the
national debt, a repeal of the Social Security earnings limit on
working senior citizens, a 5-year moratorium on taxing Internet
commerce, and increasing funding to school districts for special
education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should all be proud of the accomplishment Congress has made
this session and I believe that we will make even more important
legislative decisions before the year is over,'' Bilbray said.
''Instead of wallowing in partisanship, Republicans put together an
ambitious and thoughtful agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the House and Senate are working on HMO reform and
a prescription drug benefit for needy senior citizens. This week,
the House will consider repealing the tax on inheritance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bilbray, a surfer, also touted his ''Beach bill,'' which was
passed by the House. The measure would establish national water
quality criteria for testing and monitoring of beaches and make the
results public.
</P>
<P>
   ''After all,'' he said, ''you have a right to know what your
family is swimming in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
