<HEADLINE> Town leaders criticize Gejdenson on tribal issues  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORWICH, Conn. (AP) --Several town leaders from southeastern
Connecticut say U.S. Rep. Sam Gejdenson is not doing enough to
investigate questions about the federal recognition of the
Mashantucket Pequot tribe.
</P>
<P>
   Following a meeting with the town officials Friday, Gejdenson
called on the Mashantuckets to supply the documents that would
quell the genealogical debate -- documents promised to Congress when
the tribe was federally recognized in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   But officials say Gejdenson sidestepped their request for a
congressional hearing. Gejdenson said he would forward their
requests to the House Resources Committee that dealt with the
recognition process but suggested the towns work out their
differences directly with the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all feel there is a big difference between working toward
an outcome rather than just passing it along,'' Preston First
Selectman Robert Congdon said. ''I definitely left that meeting
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   In a new book ''Without Reservation,'' by author Jeff Benedict,
Gejdenson is characterized as pushing through the recognition and
land claims legislation without heeding warnings from other federal
officials that there were problems with the Mashantucket Pequots'
genealogy. The book, published by HarperCollins, claims the tribe
is not descended from the Pequots, and may have a thin blood link
to the Narragansetts in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   With several local Indian tribes seeking recognition, and the
possibility of more casinos and annexed land -- which is not
taxable, town officials say the recognition process needs to be
improved. They say the tribes receive preferential treatment while
the towns' problems are pushed aside.
</P>
<P>
   Gejdenson, a 10-term incumbent expected to announce his
candidacy this summer, said no one questioned the Mashantuckets'
genealogy when it was federally recognized in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ''Frankly, there was a general consensus that this was the
tribe,'' Gejdenson said.
</P>
<P>
   Gejdenson said he supported recognition of the tribe not so that
it could build a casino, but to lift the cloud of uncertainty over
surrounding properties. He said people throughout New London County
couldn't sell their homes because of the specter of annexation.
</P>
<P>
   ''My job is to do what I think is right for the state,'' he
said. ''Any politician who tries to do what's popular instead of
what's right doesn't deserve to hold office.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Mashantuckets said the tribal council would
consider meeting with the towns, as Gejdenson suggested.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1252 </TRAILER>
