<HEADLINE> Investigation of vehicle emissions fraud troubled, records show  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Until allegations of serious fraud
brought increased scrutiny, the Department of Motor Vehicles lacked
the manpower, expertise and equipment to properly investigate the
contractor running the state's mandatory vehicle emissions testing
program.
</P>
<P>
   Internal memos obtained by The Associated Press through a
Freedom of Information Act request show the department has known
for years that its investigative unit was underequipped.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Munson, the DMV official in charge of the $25 million
emissions testing contract with Envirotest Systems Corp., wrote in
a May 7 memo that the investigative unit consists of one detective
who is ''clearly short of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Munson said the DMV's emissions division could not do a
''sting'' operation to identify Envirotest employees who were
allegedly soliciting bribes in exchange for emissions certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Richard Blumenthal last month called for the
DMV to investigate the alleged fraud, including bribes and the
theft of emission stickers. The contract with Envirotest runs
through mid-2002.
</P>
<P>
   DMV spokesman Bill Seymour said at the time that the agency,
assisted by the state police, was already investigating.
</P>
<P>
   But Seymour acknowledged in an interview last week that the DMV
had trouble communicating the gravity of the problem to the state
police.
</P>
<P>
   In the May 7 memo, Munson said the DMV had confirmed several
cases of inspector fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, we have found that the state police are not
normally interested in pursuing cases,'' Munson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the problem was with the DMV, not state police, Seymour
said. Agency staff thought theft of emissions stickers amounted to
sixth-degree larceny; theft of a government document is actually a
felony.
</P>
<P>
   ''We weren't presenting the cases properly,'' Seymour said.
</P>
<P>
   State police spokesman Sgt. Paul Vance said authorities would be
happy to investigate such cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would never turn our back on any theft involving ... state
government,'' Vance said.
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, Munson said the low pay for Envirotest employees
creates an atmosphere that promotes fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ''Considering the cost of living and low unemployment rate in
Connecticut, Envirotest's $6.25 per hour starting pay rate is
ludicrous,'' he wrote. ''The problem of low wages combined with the
lack of incentive to grow in a position severely limits the labor
pool Envirotest can draw from.''
</P>
<P>
   Munson said DMV officials have repeatedly discussed the need for
improved surveillance equipment. He said it would take two video
surveillance cameras for each lane at inspection stations to deter
inspectors from engaging in illegal activity.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fraud investigations were hobbled by lack of manpower, not
having our staff focused clearly on what needs to be done,''
Seymour acknowledged. ''However, that has all changed in the last
month or so.''
</P>
<P>
   DMV officials said they are beefing up the investigative staff.
The agency has also used other means, such as audits of computer
records, to detect possible fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland has ordered an independent audit examining
both the DMV and East Granby-based Envirotest.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging its own shortcomings, DMV said Envirotest
has the primary responsibility for detecting and preventing fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Envirotest spokeswoman Martha Sanders said the company has
investigated wrongdoing and cooperated fully with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a zero tolerance in regard to that type of behavior,''
said Sanders, who said Envirotest regularly reviews employee pay
and incentives.
</P>
<P>
   The DMV correspondence cites other concerns about the program,
particularly staff shortages and long waiting lines at some
stations.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders said the company tries to staff stations properly and is
proud of its average waiting time, which she said was under 15
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But in the internal correspondence, DMV officials express
frustration after repeated discussions with Envirotest. The memos
say average waiting times are sometimes distorted by a practice
known as vehicle stacking, in which data for several cars is
entered into a computer before they are tested.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think basically what we have here is a long history of
recurring types of issues,'' said John Yacavone, chief of legal
services for DMV. ''I think that the contractor has many times
responded verbally, but they haven't taken the necessary actions to
do the job right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1252 </TRAILER>
