<DOCNO> APW20000603.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Generation Swamps Music Stores  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- First 'N Sync. Then Britney Spears. Then Eminem.
Now Kid Rock discs are flying off store shelves as a new generation
seizes control of the music business with a startling springtime of
sales.
</P>
<P>
   The three fastest-selling albums since accurate records have
been kept -- and maybe in music history -- have all appeared within
the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   Several factors have converged: a demographic bulge of young
people with disposable income, media that cater to them and hot
artists backed by marketers skilled at creating anticipation. And,
of course, music that fans can't wait to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether it's Britney, Eminem, Kid Rock or matchbox twenty, no
one's buying records that they don't like,'' said Jason Flom,
president of Lava Records. ''It's a sign the music business is
healthy because the music is good.''
</P>
<P>
   'N Sync sold a stunning 2.4 million copies of its ''No Strings
Attached'' album the first week it was available in March. In May,
Spears sold 1.3 million copies of her new album in a week and
Eminem 1.7 million, according to Soundscan, the company that
measures music sales.
</P>
<P>
   Before this year, Backstreet Boys had held the one-week record
with 1.1 million. Soundscan has been in operation since 1991, and
precise sales figures before then are considered unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   First-week sales have become a measuring stick like the first
weekend's box office receipts are for movies -- and only add to the
hype.
</P>
<P>
   Spears and 'N Sync have much in common: they sing mostly sunny
pop tunes, have nifty dance steps and looks that make teen-aged
boys and girls swoon. They even record for the same company, Jive
Records, which is known for a well-oiled marketing machine.
</P>
<P>
   Eminem's comical, foul-mouthed raps appeal to many of the rap
and rock fans who can't stomach the pop bands. He even revels in
making fun of them.
</P>
<P>
   All three albums were perfectly poised for mega-success. They
were followups to enormously successful debuts -- usually the time
of peak interest in a musician's career -- and were preceded by
successful singles that whetted their fans' appetites.
</P>
<P>
   All appealed to young people who absolutely, positively had to
have them right away.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there's anything new about the intensity of
fans,'' said Danny Goldberg, president of Artemis Records. ''When I
was a kid, I would go into a store every day when I heard a new Bob
Dylan record was coming. Getting it even two days late, I would
feel culturally deprived.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans aged 12 to 19 has grown from 28 million
in 1991 to 31 million now. In a good economy, their buying power
has increased exponentially: this age group spent $80 billion in
1990 and $153 billion last year, according to MTV.
</P>
<P>
   MTV, which has more viewers now than at any time in its nearly
20-year history, is the cultural destination of teens. ''Total
Request Live'' is like a national Top 40 radio station. MTV gives
plenty of well-timed exposure to its favorites: Eminem had his own
two-hour special the weekend before ''The Marshall Mathers LP''
came out, and 'N Sync drew 7,000 fans to MTV's Times Square studio
the day its album was released.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to support what we consider good albums,'' said Tom
Calderone, MTV's senior vice president for music programming.
''We're not going to do a two-hour special on an album that we
don't think is going to connect with our audience.''
</P>
<P>
   MTV's research is relentless -- on down to asking kids standing
in Times Square what albums they are looking forward to.
</P>
<P>
   Artists try to become ubiquitous near the time their albums
''drop'': Kid Rock was on ''Saturday Night Live,'' on the cover of
Rolling Stone and on thousands of cardboard cutout likenesses that
were shipped to music outlets, Flom said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the music industry is deeply suspicious of the
Internet because of its capacity to distribute music for free, it
has become a powerful tool for uniting fans and building the
anticipation for new music.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all about access,'' said Todd Cunningham, MTV's chief
researcher. ''You can be equally plugged in to pop culture in Des
Moines as if you were living in West L.A. or South Beach in
Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   When sales figures come out Wednesday, Flom expects Kid Rock
will have sold about a half million copies of ''The History of
Rock,'' even though it's largely a compilation of previously
released material.
</P>
<P>
   Some executives worry that such explosive successes may be so
distorting that the industry loses patience for promoting acts over
a long term. Macy Gray is now a Top 10 artist, for example, but her
album was out nearly a year before it caught on. The Dixie Chicks
sold 341,000 copies of their album in its first week; it has since
built steadily to 4.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a marathon, not a sprint,'' warned Mike Shalett,
Soundscan's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   The same week Eminem sold 1.7 million, Don Henley sold 114,000
copies of his new album, he noted. What message should his record
company take from those numbers?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the megasales are heartening for the music industry. A
few years ago, some experts worried that with the Internet, video
games and so many other entertainment choices, teen-agers wouldn't
be as interested in music as their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast. Haven't you heard those stereos blaring?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great sign that a new generation is bonding to music,''
Goldberg said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1304 </TRAILER>
