<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nations Seek Women's Equality  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Five years ago, the biggest global
gathering of women in history helped spur 189 countries to adopt an
ambitious plan to achieve equality of the sexes. Still very far
from that goal, the same nations meet Monday to try to agree on an
accelerated roadmap toward equality for women.
</P>
<P>
   But the Vatican and a group of Islamic countries are objecting
to the same proposals they did in Beijing in 1995 -- including
sexual and reproductive rights for women, adolescent sex education
and the definition of the family -- as well as some new ones.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's becoming very, very clear that there are a few countries
that are trying to stand in the way of progress,'' said Linda
Tarr-Whelan, the U.S. ambassador to the Commission on the Status of
Women.
</P>
<P>
   Tarr-Whelan pointed to Algeria, Sudan, Libya, Iran and to a
lesser extent the Vatican, saying there has been a ''backlash''
against the progress that has been made since Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are folks who like it the way they have it and are
trying to slow the whole process down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The final document outlining initiatives to spur implementation
of the 150-page Beijing platform was supposed to have been
completed this past week. But the ideological divide over a range
of issues was likely to keep negotiators working through much of
the five-day conference to try to reach consensus before it ends
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, delegates are celebrating the first successes
after Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The Beijing platform runs the gamut from promoting women's
inheritance rights to condemning rape in wartime and alleviating
the increasing poverty of women. For the first time, a U.N.
document declared that women have the right to decide freely all
matters related to their sexuality and childbearing.
</P>
<P>
   The platform also calls on governments to revise laws to ensure
women's equal rights, to provide equal education for girls, and to
put women in top decision-making positions in business and
government.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past five years, U.N. surveys show more girls are going
to school and more women are working and receiving health care.
There's also been ''a tremendous amount of women's rights and
anti-discrimination legislation'' though not all of it has been
implemented, said Assistant Secretary-General Angela King, the top
U.N. adviser on women.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will speak here Monday about
expanding the use of small loans to help poor women escape poverty
-- an issue she promoted at the Beijing conference, where it was
endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest achievement since Beijing ''is that women are really
on the agenda,'' said Charlotte Bunch, director of the Center for
Women's Global Leadership at Rutgers University in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But women remain underpaid, underrepresented in governments, and
under threat of physical and sexual abuse -- and three-quarters of
the world's poorest are women and children.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of conservative opposition, Susana Galdos, a member
of the Peruvian delegation, said she fears this week's conference
could reverse the gains of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the new document reaffirms the 189 nations'
commitment to the Beijing platform, every reference in it to sexual
rights is still bracketed -- signifying disagreement among
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Developing nations are trying to soften the Beijing platform's
strong affirmation that countries have a ''duty'' to protect human
rights ''regardless of their political, economic and cultural
systems.'' They have proposed language saying countries can
implement the platform ''with full respect'' to religious or
cultural backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican and conservatives object to the Beijing platform's
reference to nontraditional families, which they view as an implied
blessing of homosexual unions, single parents and couples living
together out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates also remain divided on newer issues, including the
effects of globalization on women and how to educate young people
about the dangers of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   And a reference in the new document to legal measures in a
growing number of countries ''to prohibit discrimination on the
basis of sexual orientation'' also remains bracketed. At Beijing,
lesbian rights were dropped from the final draft.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers estimate that 10,000 delegates and grass-roots
activists will attend the conference -- compared to at least 40,000
in Beijing. And on the eve of the opening session, nobody is
certain what the final document will say.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a backlash against women's visibility,'' said Bunch,
of Rutgers. ''There's a backlash against women pushing the
boundaries of the issues. And that's what we're seeing in this
process now -- the backlash.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she said, delegates have already agreed to the most
important provision -- the reaffirmation of the Beijing platform for
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Yakin Erturk, director of the U.N. Division for the Advancement
of Women, said the United Nations hopes the final document will go
further and call on member states to set deadlines to achieve
progress toward equality for women.
</P>
<P>
   Tarr-Whelan, the U.S. ambassador, said her pessimism has turned
to optimism that the final document ''will be the next roadmap to
give more concrete steps for action for achieving women's
equality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1308 </TRAILER>
