<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fourth-grade fife and drum corps steal the show wherever they go  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. (AP) -- They play just three instruments -- the
fife, the drum and the recorder. They prefer their own fancy moves
to marching in step. And when they line up alongside polished high
school bands, these 10-year-olds still manage to steal the show.
</P>
<P>
   The Watkins Glen Elementary School Fife and Drum Band is a rite
of passage in a town with a world-famous auto racing track. When
local pride is at stake, the band's stirring sounds can easily
drown out the rumble and roar of stock-car engines.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when many school administrators and taxpayers are
lending a tin ear to music education, this 65-member corps of
fourth-graders flourishes. It may also be the only organization of
its kind in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Competing against high school and middle school bands, the
Watkins Glen youngsters step lively through all manner of tunes and
get surprising range from their limited instrument collection.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're an amazing group. They're unbelievable,'' said Bill
Birkett, chairman of the Pageant of Bands in Gorham, where the band
was performing Saturday, 40 miles from home in western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Good as they are, the marchers don't seem so impressed with
their own talent. They're just doing what most fourth-graders in
Watkins Glen have done for the past 16 years. Come fifth grade,
fife-and-drumming will become a memory to savor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sort of a big deal, but it's sort of normal,'' fifer
Molly Bilinski said in Saturday's Rochester Democrat and Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Lindsay and his wife, Carol, who retired from their jobs as
music teachers at Watkins Glen Elementary last June, started the
band.
</P>
<P>
   ''The principal and I sat down and talked about how we would
like to do something special for the kids,'' Ed Lindsay told the
newspaper. ''I suggested a fife-and-drum band because it can have
14 kids or it can have 80 kids -- you just balance the number of
instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Scarcity of money also played a part. Recorders sell for under
$5, fifes for around $12 and Lindsay was able to obtain some drums
from an inactive drum and bugle corps.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-seven fourth-graders were in the original band. In their
first performance, on Memorial Day, ''we struggled to get down the
street, but they played both their songs,'' Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   After a few years, the band was drawing about 90 percent of all
fourth graders and dressed up in maroon-and-blue pullovers and
matching shorts. The Lindsays also began teaching the recorder in
third grade to prepare students for the band experience.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan Davis, who plays a single drum, knows that practice makes
all the difference. ''You do it for a while and it gets easier,''
he said as he rushed to a rehearsal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1335 </TRAILER>
