<DOCNO> APW20000603.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Plans Computer Grants  </HEADLINE>
By WALTER MEARS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- President Clinton announced $128 million in
federal grants Saturday to give computer training to American
teachers, saying a majority feel ill-prepared to use computers in
the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers must be ''as comfortable with a computer as they are
with a chalk board,'' the president said in his weekly radio
address, recorded in the Germany city where he met with world
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The grants, $44 million this year and the total of $128 million
over a three-year period, will support partnerships between teacher
colleges, elementary and secondary schools, community-based
organizations, and high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''In too many ways, the education budget making its way through
Congress simply doesn't make the grade,'' Clinton said, threatening
a veto unless it provides more school spending.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican Conference Chairman J.C. Watts countered that
the GOP is ''working to improve schools and develop new models
while the Clinton-Gore team continues to distort the facts on an
issue that's critical to this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Watts, R-Okla., said the grants ''may help train some
teachers,'' but he suggested a new approach is needed to bring
Internet skills to all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ''Republicans are working to lower tax and regulatory barriers
that prevent underserved communities from gaining access to the
Internet,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   In his address, Clinton said his administration is making
progress in ''bridging the digital divide'' to put more computers
in classrooms. He said 95 percent of schools and 63 percent of
classrooms now are wired for the Internet, a dramatic improvement
from the levels early in his first term.
</P>
<P>
   Weighing in from abroad on an issue in the presidential campaign
at home, Clinton said Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic
candidate to succeed him, deserves much of the credit for expanding
school computer programs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the next step must be to train more teachers in
computer instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ''America will need more than two million new teachers over the
next 10 years,'' Clinton said. ''We have to make sure every one of
them can use a computer to help students meet high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an Education Department survey of 3,560 teachers in
kindergarten through 12th grade found that only one in five felt
''very well prepared'' to use computers in their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Schools and Libraries Division of the Universal Service
Administrative Co., which is overseen by the Federal Communications
Commission, now distributes money to schools and libraries to help
pay for discounted Internet connections. More than $3.6 billion has
been committed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of that money -- collected on fees on telecommunications
companies and passed on to their customers -- helps pay for the
internal wiring schools and libraries need to hook their computers
together or to the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1344 </TRAILER>
