<DOCNO> APW20000603.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chian Marks Tiananmen Anniversary  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN LEICESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Families of those killed planned quiet memorials,
dissidents demanded redress and police tightened security Saturday
on the eve of the 11th anniversary of the Chinese government's
crackdown on the Tiananmen Square pro-democracy protests.
</P>
<P>
   In an open letter to Chinese President Jiang Zemin and Premier
Zhu Rongji, eight dissidents from northeast China said the
government was ''absolutely wrong'' to crush the seven weeks of
protests centered on the vast square in Beijing, a Hong Kong-based
human rights group said.
</P>
<P>
   The dissidents called for the release of political prisoners,
for political reforms and democracy and for compensation for
victims' families and the thousands of people imprisoned in an
ensuing nationwide crackdown, according to the Information Center
for Human Rights and Democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, drafted by dissident Liang Liwei and signed by the
seven others, also urged the government to reverse its verdict that
the demonstrations were a ''counterrevolutionary rebellion'' that
had to be quelled.
</P>
<P>
   Troops backed by tanks and armored carriers shot their way
through the Chinese capital on the night of June 3-4, 1989, killing
hundreds, possibly thousands, and ending the protests that
sometimes drew crowds of more than a million.
</P>
<P>
   The government has never allowed an investigation or a full
accounting of the dead and injured.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent commemorations, authorities stepped up security and
extra military police patrolled Saturday in front of Tiananmen
gate, which overlooks the square in central Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Beijing dissident Ren Wanding said police visited him
Friday and ''told me not to carry out any activities.''
</P>
<P>
   But that did not stop him from issuing a statement Saturday that
paid tribute to those ''who died for a just cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Ren also called for a reassessment of the demonstrations and of
a democracy movement in 1978-79 and student protests in 1986,
saying a ''just evaluation'' would be ''a cornerstone for social
democracy, popular reconciliation, national stability, people's
happiness and the strength and prosperity of the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Ding Zilin, a prominent campaigner for victims of the
crackdown whose 17-year-old son was killed, said plainclothes
police were stationed outside her house and that her phone had been
cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Ding were unsuccessful. The phone appeared to ring but
no one picked up, even though Ding's friends said she was home.
</P>
<P>
   Ding planned to light incense and ''silently remember her
child,'' said Zhang Xianling, who visited Ding on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, who also lost a 19-year-old son, said she placed flowers
under his portrait at home and would visit his grave.
</P>
<P>
   Su Bingxian, whose 21-year-old son was shot to death, said she,
her husband and their surviving two children would spend Saturday
evening together in commemoration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1356 </TRAILER>
