<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Toledo Faces Uphill Battle  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Alejandro Toledo looked more like a winner
than a loser when he addressed 50,000 supporters massed in a
downtown plaza after President Alberto Fujimori's tainted
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   The throng roared as he announced a campaign of ''peaceful
resistance'' to bring down Fujimori's ''dictatorship.''
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo, who has no organized party and became a serious
contender only in the final weeks before the first round of voting
April 9, faces a formidable task in keeping the anti-Fujimori
forces united behind his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Many Peruvians wonder whether he can pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   ''Toledo's true support is very small. Toledo is a mirage. You
see a lot of strength but when you try to put your hand on it, it's
not there,'' said Patricio Ricketts, a pro-Fujimori political
commentator.
</P>
<P>
   As Toledo continued with his crusade to galvanize support
against Fujimori, the foreign ministers of the Organization of
American States convened Sunday to discuss Peru's questioned
presidential runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign support could fade quickly for opposition forces within
Peru fighting for new, clean elections if Toledo does not maintain
pressure as well as his credibility in the coming months, political
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Sociologist Alberto Adrianzen said Toledo will have to keep his
backers mobilized until Fujimori's inauguration. ''That is going to
depend a lot on his leadership capacity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has vowed to put 4 million protesters into Lima's streets
on July 26 to block Fujimori's inauguration for a third five-year
term two days later.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he is traveling throughout Peru addressing
political rallies. But analysts say Peruvians may grow weary of his
fiery rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fujimori can bring the tanks into the streets but he will not
defeat us,'' Toledo bellowed to supporters Thursday night in
Canete, a coastal town south of Lima. ''They will first have to
pass over millions of Peruvians.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori shows no sign of being worried. In an interview
published last week, he said he did not expect Peruvians to keep
protesting day after day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Psychologically, after an election, people who are not
activists return to their daily lives,'' the 61-year-old Fujimori
said.
</P>
<P>
   He called Toledo ''a passing phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo boycotted the second-round runoff against Fujimori on May
28, accusing him of planning to rig the vote. Foreign monitors
withdrew when the government refused to delay the election to give
them time to study new vote-tabulation computer software. An OAS
mission said the election was ''far from what could be considered
free or fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first round Toledo had 40.2 percent of the vote to
Fujimori's 49.9 percent, blocking him from a majority and forcing a
runoff.
</P>
<P>
   But much of Toledo's support was an anti-Fujimori vote, not a
vote for what Toledo represented as a candidate, public opinion
pollsters say.
</P>
<P>
   He reached the runoff in an 11th-hour surge, in part because a
government smear campaign had destroyed two other opposition
candidates once viewed as strong threats to Fujimori's re-election
hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Toledo is unlikely to be a solid opposition voice in the
coming years,'' Piero Ghezzi, a Peruvian financial analyst with
Deutsche Bank in New York, predicted, noting he had very little
core support of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a 54-year-old U.S.-trained economist who grew up in
poverty, must move from being a political candidate to assuming the
leadership of a broad range of opposition parties, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   ''Toledo is the candidate but he's not the leader of the
opposition,'' said political analyst Santiago Pedraglio. ''There's
an important difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Peru's numerous opposition parties have a long history of not
cooperating. That was the case again in this year's elections.
Eight opposition parties fielded presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo also must contend with a government willing to use the
courts, tax investigations and intimidation by Peru's feared
intelligence service to smother opposition movements.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps his greatest challenge will be to counter damage to
his own image provoked by his waffling on key issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro Velasquez, a 52-year-old waiter in the San Isidro banking
district, said he had voted for Toledo, but now had doubts about
his ability to govern Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ''Toledo doesn't take firm positions,'' he said. ''He says one
thing and then he contradicts himself and I think that is the
reason that people are not going to support him, no matter how hard
he seeks a new election.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1358 </TRAILER>
