<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberal Party backs Clinton; Conservatives set to back Lazio  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton picked up
the backing of the Liberal Party's leadership today in her bid for
a U.S. Senate seat from New York.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Conservative Party leadership, meeting in Albany,
was set to endorse Clinton's Republican rival, Rep. Rick Lazio,
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous backing for Clinton's candidacy from the Liberal
Party's state committee came this morning during a party convention
held at a Manhattan hotel. The first lady was scheduled to address
the Liberal Party leaders in the wake of her endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are confident that today's endorsement of Hillary Rodham
Clinton brings her a giant step closer to victory in November,''
Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding said.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsements for Clinton and Lazio, the little-known Long
Island congressman who jumped into the race after New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani withdrew, could prove crucial in the Senate
race.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Long, the head of the Conservative Party, said Friday he
expected to deliver at least 350,000 votes for Lazio, a potentially
decisive boost in a close race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think our people are really energized,'' Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
also count votes from third-party ballot lines.
</P>
<P>
   The path was cleared for Clinton to get the Liberal Party nod
last month after Giuliani dropped out of the Senate race to deal
with his prostate cancer. One of Giuliani's closest political
advisers is Liberal Party leader Raymond Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's withdrawal from the race, and Lazio's quick entry
into it, also paved the way for the Republican and Conservative
parties to restore their traditional partnership in statewide
races. Long had refused to back Giuliani because of the Republican
mayor's strong support for abortion rights and his closeness to the
Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   While Lazio has said he supports abortion rights, he repeatedly
has voted to cut off federal Medicaid money to pay for poor women's
abortions and favors a ban on so-called ''partial-birth abortion.''
That has been enough to win Long's support.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican seeking statewide office in New York has won
without Conservative Party support since 1974. Conversely, no
Democrat has been elected governor or U.S. senator in New York
without Liberal Party backing since it was founded more than 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Lazio campaign: http://www.lazio.com
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign: http://www.hillary2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1407 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
