<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eritrea Says Ethiopia Attacked Port  </HEADLINE>
By CRAIG NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) -- Hopes of an imminent end to the ruinous
war between two of Africa's poorest countries faded Saturday, as
Eritrea accused Ethiopian forces of attacking military outposts
near its main Red Sea port.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of renewed fighting between the two Horn of
Africa neighbors came three days after Ethiopia declared the war
against its rival over and amid reports that Eritrea's humanitarian
crisis was deepening.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrean presidential spokesman Yemane Gebremeskel said
Ethiopian artillery and ground forces struck Eritrean military
positions near Assab at 3:30 a.m., and furious fighting raged for
seven hours.
</P>
<P>
   Yemane called for the immediate imposition of economic sanctions
against Ethiopia and urged the U.N. Security Council to lift its
arms embargo against Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, government spokeswoman
Selome Taddesse denied Eritrea's allegation, saying Ethiopia had
not launched any offensive on any front.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have made it publicly clear that as far as Ethiopia is
concerned, military operations are over. But if there are any
provocations by the Eritrean army, our defense forces have been
instructed to deal with them decisively,'' Selome said.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Ethiopia accused Eritrea of launching ''military
provocations'' to sink peace talks underway in Algeria. It was
unclear what provocation Ethiopia was referring to, although
Ethiopia said Saturday that Eritrean forces, using heavy artillery,
had attacked Ethiopian positions southwest of Assab on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia announced the end of its war with Eritrea on Wednesday,
saying it had retaken all land under dispute between the two
countries along their 620-mile border.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea has already pulled out of territory claimed by its
neighbor, including Bure. Ethiopia has said it is ready to withdraw
from uncontested Eritrean land captured during the recent 19-day
offensive if its neighbor joins a cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Yemane, the Eritrean spokesman, said Saturday's fighting
occurred on undisputed Eritrean territory, 23 miles west of Assab.
Eritrea withdrew its forces to that position one week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Still wary of Ethiopian aims, Eritrea earlier this week flew
troops and arms to Assab in case of an Ethiopian move on the port.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Security Council approved an arms embargo against
Eritrea and Ethiopia on May 17, five days after Ethiopian forces
invaded Eritrea, rekindling the on-again-off-again border war that
is believed to have killed tens of thousands of soldiers and
civilians and cost each side $1 million a day in military
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's purported attack came during indirect talks in the
Algerian capital, Algiers, between the two Horn of Africa
countries. The talks resumed Saturday, and a Western diplomat said
progress was being made, but slowly. The outcome apparently hinges
on details of Ethiopia's withdrawal and the security of the
long-disputed border.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Organization of African Unity, the
European Community and the United States are brokering the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the World Food Program said Saturday it would be
revising its estimate of war-affected Eritreans from 330,000 to as
high as 750,000. That number includes displaced Eritreans and those
in need of emergency food, spokeswoman Lindsey Davies said. Daily
aid flights from the Balkans of emergency food rations were to
begin Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sudan's Commission on Refugees said Saturday that the number of
Eritrean refugees seeking shelter in Sudan had risen to 52,953, an
increase of 20,000 in one week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1417 </TRAILER>
