<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan, Congolese Presidents Meet  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN LINNEE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- The presidents of Congo and Rwanda,
enemies in a 22-month civil war that has drawn five foreign armies
into Africa's third-largest nation, met Saturday in Kenya and
agreed to promote peace and to restore bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Kabila of Congo and Paul Kagame of Rwanda met in
Eldoret, 150 miles northwest of Nairobi, Kenyan President Daniel
arap Moi's office said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A Rwandan security source who accompanied Kagame to Eldoret said
it was the first time the two leaders had met since rebels, backed
by Rwanda and Uganda, staged an uprising in eastern Congo in August
1998 and came close to capturing the capital, Kinshasa, 1,000 miles
to the west.
</P>
<P>
   The intervention of troops from Angola, Zimbabwe and Namibia
halted the rebel offensive, but they went on to capture the eastern
third of the country, including the Congo River port town of
Kisangani.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Kenyan statement said the two leaders had agreed
''to work together to promote peace, security and stability between
their two countries and the region,'' the Rwandan source said no
deals had been struck.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized that before any real rapprochement can take place,
Kabila has to agree to deal with former members of the Rwandan
Armed Forces and interahamwe militia who took part in the 1994
genocide in Rwanda of at least half a million people, most of them
minority Tutsis. Thousands of the former soldiers and militia have
been recruited into the Congolese army.
</P>
<P>
   The source said Kabila made no commitment on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   But Rwandan government spokesman Joseph Bideri said it was
Rwanda's understanding the Kabila would cooperate in disassociating
himself from the Hutu militia.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of things were discussed ... and we will continue the
dialogue,'' Bideri said, adding that Rwandan state television would
broadcast the first images of Kagame and Kabila together since the
outbreak of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Before his election as president April 17, Kagame was
vice-president and defense minister in charge of Rwanda's
participation in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Both leaders reaffirmed their commitment to a peace accord
signed last July and August in the Zambian capital, Lusaka, by
Congo, three rebel organizations and the five foreign nations
involved. Under terms of the agreement, the United Nations is to
deploy 5,537 military observers to monitor the cease-fire and
troops to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda, who fought pitched battles in Kisangani last
August and last month, have completed their pullback to 62 miles
from the port, and South African military logistics personnel are
expected to travel to the town in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Moi made an official visit to Rwanda on May 12, and Kagame has
visited him several times in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   Both Rwanda and Uganda said they intervened on the side of the
rebels because Kabila failed to remove the former Rwandan soldiers
and militia as well as Ugandan rebels from their bases in eastern
Congo from which they were launching attacks on both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Congo and Rwanda never formally broke diplomatic ties, and
Kabila recently sent an emissary to Kigali.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1420 </TRAILER>
