<HEADLINE> Ruling: Photog can stage nude shoot below bridge  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Barely hours before its scheduled start, a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling Saturday cleared the way for a Manhattan
artist to photograph scores of naked people beneath the
Williamsburg Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm so excited,'' artist Spencer Tunick said after getting
word of his victory. ''I don't think that the government should own
your vision as an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials had sought an order blocking Tunick from staging
his picture in the early morning hours Sunday, but the Supreme
Court denied their application.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to happen,'' confirmed city Corporation Counsel
Michael Hess, who had argued against the photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came only 17 hours before Tunick's planned shoot in a
park beneath the bridge. Tunick, who has been arrested five times
at previous sessions, was elated by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just so happy,'' he said. ''I've been doing my work while
looking over my shoulder for five years. It's nice to know I can
have breakfast at home after we're finished.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, a federal appeals court in Manhattan ruled that
Tunick had a First Amendment right to take his unusual photos.
Tunick, who has battled with the Giuliani administration since
1994, had sued Police Commissioner Howard Safir last summer after a
heavy police turnout forced cancellation of one shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Tunick agreed to conduct his Sunday shoot between 5:15 a.m. and
5:45 a.m. Sunday in the East River Park. A turnout of between 125
and 150 nude models was expected.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said that while Tunick has won this battle, the war wasn't
over. ''We'll take each event as it happens,'' Hess said of any
future all-nude shoots.
</P>
<P>
   The next event, according to Tunick, will involve 400 nudes
inside Grand Central Terminal this November.
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Tunick has often photographed large groups of
nude people in public places. Some of his more unusual pictures
have attracted police attention.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 12, 1996, two of his nude models were arrested atop of a
Manhattan snowdrift, posed beneath an ice-cream parlor sign that
advertised ''Frozen Fantasies.''
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Eve 1994, Tunick and a model were arrested when
she posed nude on top of an 8-foot-high simulated Christmas tree
ornament at Rockefeller Center. Charges were dismissed in both
cases.
</P>
<P>
   One year ago, Tunick canceled a photo shoot when dozens of
officers with plastic handcuffs showed up to arrest anyone who
disrobed.
</P>
<P>
   The city had argued that New York law criminalizes public
nudity. Tunick maintained that state law does not prohibit nude
photography and that police interference violated his
constitutional rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
