<HEADLINE> Opposition Supporters Denied Bail  </HEADLINE>
By MISHA SAVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Serbian police detained 40
opposition activists, including an 11-year-old, in raids focusing
on an increasingly popular student group opposed to President
Slobodan Milosevic, a news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a court refused bail for two other supporters of the
Otpor student group, who last month were arrested after a brawl
with associates of Milosevic's son and charged with attempted
murder.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests took place in several towns across Serbia on Friday,
including 20 Otpor activists who were detained and questioned in
Smederevska Palanka, 35 miles southeast of Belgrade, the
independent Beta news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The 11-year-old was arrested in Ivanjica, in south-central
Serbia, for waving a flag with the Otpor symbol -- a clenched fist.
His father was also questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of Otpor -- or Resistance -- has long extended
beyond university campuses, leading to an increasing crackdown
against the group.
</P>
<P>
   The court in Milosevic's hometown extended the detention of
Otpor backers Momcilo Veljkovic and Radojko Lukovic for another
month until July.
</P>
<P>
   Veljkovic and Lukovic were beaten up in a May 2 fistfight with
associates of Milosevic's son in Pozarevac, 50 miles east of the
capital, and both suffered serious injuries. However, they were
treated as the perpetrators and charged with attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests caused outrage among opposition supporters and human
rights groups. Milosevic's police sealed off Pozarevac last month
to prevent a protest rally.
</P>
<P>
   At least two judges from the Pozarevac District Court resigned
last month in protest against government pressure to treat the
suspects as perpetrators, despite evidence to the opposite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
