<DOCNO> APW20000603.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Even party primaries now littered with attacks  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Slippery. A liar. A swindler. Shady.
</P>
<P>
   Voters and political professionals alike are inured by now to
nasty and negative campaigns. But usually the worst is saved for
November. This year, however, members of the same party have
violated any remaining semblance of protocol and gone at each other
full throttle with those labels, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional election analyst Stuart Rothenberg summarizes New
Jersey's primary races this way: ''Somewhere between entertaining
and revolting.''
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue reached rock bottom late last week when radio
stations in central New Jersey aired an ad implying a link between
Mike Pappas and the Ku Klux Klan because of the history of the
church he works for, Pillar of Fire.
</P>
<P>
   So outraged was former Gov. Tom Kean -- a frequent critic of
Pappas and supporter of Pappas' Republican rival, Dick Zimmer --
that he told the Pappas campaign he would be happy to defend him to
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is beyond the bounds of what I consider proper
politics,'' Kean said. ''I've lived and worked in campaigns, so I
get every mailing there is. And I've never seen anything like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pappas campaign presented evidence tying the group behind
the ad, ''Citizens for Tax Reform,'' to people associated with the
Zimmer campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer denounced the ad, but his campaign otherwise brushed
aside questions about its involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not going to go back and forth and play this little
game,'' said Zimmer campaign manager John Holub. ''The next thing
you know, he's going to say we shot Kennedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer leveled his own charges of unlawful coordination, between
Pappas and the anti-abortion factions supporting him. But Pappas
denied any involvement in mailers that looked suspiciously like his
own campaign material.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors are contributing to the tone of this year's
primary.
</P>
<P>
   First, much is at stake nationally. Leadership of the House and
the Senate could change based on the November election.
</P>
<P>
   Also, largely anonymous independent groups are proliferating and
often are responsible for the basest political assaults.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Citizens for Tax Justice'' attack on Pappas was one
example. In the 7th District, the so-called ''Council for
Responsible Government'' has sent mailings criticizing two of the
four Republicans seeking the nomination. In the 5th District, the
conservative Club for Growth is using a snippet of a three-year-old
quote to criticize Rep. Marge Roukema as too liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, campaign operatives bombard reporters with e-mails
that include charges and name-calling that their candidate wouldn't
utter personally for fear of being sullied. Nowhere has that been
more evident than in the gloves-off Democratic primary for Senate
between former Gov. Jim Florio and former Wall Street executive Jon
S. Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   In e-mails, the Corzine campaign has called Florio ''Governor
Tax,'' a man who ''has no remorse about lying'' and who is
''celebrating 10 years of misleading New Jersey.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio, meanwhile, has used the word ''obscene'' to describe
Corzine's spending and ''despicable'' to describe Corzine's use of
a private investigator in the campaign. Florio also alleged that
Goldman, Sachs was partner to a ''swindle'' while Corzine worked
there.
</P>
<P>
   In the 7th District House contest, Republican Patrick Morrisey
called Mike Ferguson ''slippery.'' In the Democratic primary in
that district, Jeff Golkin accused Union County Manager Michael
Lapolla of nothing less than ''a scandalous lack of ethics'' and
''a shakedown'' for taking money from county employees.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than use his first radio ad to introduce himself to
voters, Lapolla aired a parody portraying another opponent,
Maryanne Connelly, as flighty and indecisive. Connelly denounced
the ad as sexist.
</P>
<P>
   And what of clean campaign pledges, which now are proposed or
signed in most competitive races? More often than not, they become
hammers used to beat up each other.
</P>
<P>
   A Ferguson radio ad charged Joel Weingarten, another Republican
running for the House in the 7th District, with breaking a
clean-campaign pledge -- then went on to attack him.
</P>
<P>
   As he signed a ''framework for civility in government,'' Pappas
took the opportunity to assail Zimmer for ''shady'' campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Reed, who monitors campaigns as director of the Eagleton
New Jersey Project at Rutgers University's Eagleton Institute of
Politics, said voters are turned off -- even the party regulars who
actually vote in primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''Disrespectful, nasty, they wouldn't want to be treated that
way. That's what I'm hearing,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   Kean, now the president of Drew University, has seen the
campaign both as a political pro and as the father of Tom Kean Jr.,
a candidate for House this year. He said he urges college students
to go into politics, but the current campaign gives him pause.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been in rough campaigns,'' Kean said. ''I've run against
Jim Florio, and we attacked each other. But it was on issues, it
was on qualifications. It wasn't on personalities, and it wasn't
stuff put out at the last minute. This is a nasty turn that was
never there when was I was in politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1530 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tajik Regional Official Killed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUSHANBE, Tajikistan (AP) -- A regional leader in eastern
Tajikistan was shot and killed Saturday on his way home from the
capital, Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
   Armed assailants killed Sergei Davlatov, as well as his
bodyguard and driver, as they were driving in Davlatov's official
car toward his home region, Garm, the Interior Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Davlatov was a member of Tajik President Emomali Rakhmonov's
People's Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry said it was considering the attack a terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
   Tajikistan, a former Soviet republic in Central Asia, has been
plagued by political violence, despite a 1997 peace agreement that
ended a five-year civil war between the hard-line government and
mostly Islamic opposition.
</P>
