<DOCNO> APW20000603.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Ministry Chides UN Prosecutor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on Saturday
criticized the decision of the chief U.N. war crimes prosecutor not
to investigate allegations that NATO committed war crimes during
last year's air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian parliamentary commission and lawyers working for
Yugoslavia had produced evidence to support charges that NATO
committed war crimes during its 78-day bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   However, chief prosecutor Carla del Ponte told the Security
Council on Friday that there was no basis for an investigation into
NATO's conduct, and that she was satisfied NATO had not
deliberately targeted civilians or illegal military areas.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations against NATO included an airstrike on a bridge
as a passenger train was crossing, the bombing of a refugee convoy
near Djakovica, and the targeting of the Serbian TV building in
Belgrade. Serbian officials have said NATO bombs killed more than
300 people, but that number was not independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Foreign Ministry said Del Ponte's decision ''was not a
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not the first time the tribunal closes its eyes on cases
of violations of the norms of international humanitarian rights by
other participants in the conflict, thus demonstrating its
political bias,'' the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal was established seven years ago by the U.N.
Security Council to prosecute those responsible for atrocities in
the Balkans following the disintegration of Yugoslavia in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's decision is likely to further damage relations between
the tribunal and Yugoslavia, which has accused U.N. prosecutors of
bias and essentially cut off all cooperation with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1551 </TRAILER>
