<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Promotional bison attacked in Buffalo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Bison can't seem to catch a break in any
century here.
</P>
<P>
   The city steeped in a history of massive herds of buffalo
roaming the the area only to be hunted to near extinction in the
19th century now is the home of a bison victimized by vandals.
</P>
<P>
   Last week one of Buffalo's eight ''Wind Up/Round Up''
promotional bison in the ''Herd About Buffalo'' campaign had its
2-foot-tall windup key wrenched from atop its fiberglass body.
</P>
<P>
   ''People put their heart and soul into this project, and then to
have some cretin come along and vandalize it is unconscionable,''
said Lt. Larry Baehre of the Buffalo Police Department. ''If we do
catch these people, I hope they get the maximum fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Wind Up is part of a fund-raising stampede for charity and the
arts with support from the City of Buffalo. The project, while
showcasing the work of western New York artists, also aims to
enliven the city's landscape as more of the bison show up on city
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Morgulis, the artist who designed Wind Up, tried to
patch the critter up with some epoxy, tape and Band-Aids.
</P>
<P>
   ''Isn't it a drag? It must have taken a couple of people,
because the entire buffalo was turned around,'' Morgulis said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1609 </TRAILER>
