<DOCNO> APW20000603.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Planners say GOP convention shouldn't disrupt traffic  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- With 35,000 people expected to arrive for
the Republican National Convention, staying in hotels in
Pennsylvania, New Jersey and Delaware, a week of terrible traffic
could be in store -- but planners say they have things under
control.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't minimize the impact of the convention, but we
shouldn't sit and quake about managing it,'' said Andrew Warren, a
district administrator for the Pennsylvania Department of
Transportation. ''It's not something that needs to be feared. It's
something that needs to be managed.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren noted that there can be 80,000 or more people moving
toward the sports complex in South Philadelphia at once when there
are major events at Veterans Stadium, the First Union Center and
the First Union Spectrum on the same night. So he is not worried
about the convention, which is being held at the First Union Center
from July 31 to Aug. 3. Transportation officials have been working
with Republican Party officials for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said one way to keep the expressways from getting clogged
will be a fleet of lime-green tow trucks cruising the roads during
rush hours to get stalled cars and those with flat tires out of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sixty percent of all congestion is caused by just those minor
breakdowns,'' Warren said. The trucks, which will begin service by
July 1, are to remain in use after the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements that PennDOT plans include electronic signs
on Schuylkill Expressway ramps to give traffic information and
having PennDOT's control center at Valley Forge staffed 24 hours
during the convention instead of the usual 15. Also, PennDOT's
maintenance yard is to have a crew stationed there around the clock
to get to any crashes or spills quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''The convention has ... fairly predictable peak times for
transportation,'' convention spokesman Tim Fitzpatrick said. ''If
the schedule follows the '96 schedule, sessions will start after
rush hour has pretty well concluded, and end much later in the
evening.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Public Utility Commission, which oversees taxi
service, has authorized 150 new cabs for Philadelphia, with a
''passenger's bill of rights'' posted in every taxi.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of times, the first impression a person gets of your
city is that first cab ride, and we want to make sure passengers
get what they want,'' PUC spokesman Kevin Cadden said.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, officials said construction will be suspended on
major routes used to get into Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to ensure that every available lane will be open
during the convention,'' New Jersey Department of Transportation
spokesman John Dourgarian said.
</P>
<P>
   Delaware officials cannot make that promise, though, because a
major reconstruction of Interstate 95 had been planned for a long
time. By the time of the convention, the northbound lanes are to be
shut down. But officials there are doing what they can to make sure
alternate routes work as well as they can.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've done a lot of small improvements to roads that connect
to and from the city from (Interstate) 495,'' Delaware Department
of Transportation spokeswoman Michele Ackles said. ''We're pretty
comfortable right now that we've got a plan in place to make travel
not too difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1621 </TRAILER>
