<DOCNO> APW20000603.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Putin Meet in Moscow  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Clinton and Vladimir Putin dined on
trout, goose and spicy boar in a Kremlin summit dinner Saturday,
with Clinton intrigued by the new Russian president's suggestion he
has relaxed his stern opposition to a planned U.S. system to defend
against missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior administration official, briefing reporters later,
refused to specify whether Putin demonstrated a willingness to go
along with a modification of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty
that Clinton would need to build such a defense.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will not decide until fall whether to try to construct
one, now being tested.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to say anything whatsoever with regard to
details on the substance that characterize either side's
position,'' said the official, who declined to be further
identified. ''This is a very serious and focused beginning of a set
of conversations that are going to continue through the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting -- the leaders' first since Putin took office -- was
described as friendly, though the presidents did not address each
other as ''Bill'' and ''Vladimir.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There was an easy-going nature to the conversation,'' the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, nearing the end of a weeklong European tour, flew here
from a skull session in Berlin with the leaders of more than a
dozen nations. They talked about one of Clinton's favorite topics --
forging a ''Third Way'' of governance, a course between liberalism
and conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin talked for two hours and 45 minutes,
continuing even when they broke before dessert to tour the personal
residence of the Kremlin. Putin took Clinton to see his book-lined
study, a small chapel, and his workout room. He spoke an occasional
phrase in English, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The presidents were joined at dinner by only two aides, Strobe
Talbott, Clinton's envoy to Russia, and Sergei Prikhodko, deputy
chief of Putin's staff. On the menu: cabbage soup and cold spicy
wild boar, baked stag ham, trout and goose with red berry sauce.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner came a jazz concert. Band leader Oleg Lundstrem
brought along a saxophone just in case Clinton felt like making
some music, too.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of the summit, Putin said in an NBC-TV interview that
the ABM treaty must be preserved, calling that a condition for
further nuclear arms reductions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the same interview, he said he sees the potential missile
threat from states like North Korea. Putin suggested that a
different system, within the ABM treaty, could intercept missiles
near liftoff and protect Europe and Russia as well as the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are new threats arising that we must address but our
proposal is to answer them together,'' the Russian president said.
''And these proposals in our view have prospects. ... I think we,
on that point, will have a substantive and useful dialogue with
President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The American official said this was discussed, too, but he
withheld details.
</P>
<P>
   They also discussed international economics, the situation in
the Balkans, the strategic nuclear relationship between the United
States and Russia and Russia's war against rebellious Chechnya,
where fighting has flared anew. Rebel fighters have attacked
Russian troops across Chechnya and Russian warplanes bombarded the
southern mountains in the latest outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   But the most sensitive topic was the planned American missile
defense system -- a scaled-down version of Ronald Reagan's ''Star
Wars'' idea in the early 1980s, but intended to defend against
missile attacks from such states as North Korea and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed U.S. system would begin with 100 anti-missile
missiles in Alaska, to knock out attackers in space. Such a system
is barred by the ABM treaty. It was drafted in the era of East-West
mutual deterrence to assure both sides that neither would lose its
power to retaliate if hit.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is important is that President Putin is signaling that he
is open to discussions,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said in Berlin on Saturday, reflecting on Putin's ambiguous
comments.
</P>
<P>
   She told German journalists it was interesting that Putin seemed
to see some risk from North Korea and that he suggested ''we should
look at it together.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clinton and Putin will meet for more than six hours
and deliver statements on their conclusions. The president also
plans to field questions from Russians in a call-in radio show in
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton will become the first American president to
address the Duma, the lower house of the Russian parliament, before
he bids Putin goodbye, pays a courtesy call on former President
Boris Yeltsin and leaves for Kiev, Ukraine, and home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1627 </TRAILER>
