<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAS Target of Diplomatic Maneuvering  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Suddenly, everyone wants a piece of the
Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   After working for decades in relative obscurity, the 34-member
international body finds itself a target of diplomatic maneuvering
and protesters at its 30th general assembly beginning Sunday in
Windsor, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters who disrupted a World Trade Organization meeting in
Seattle in December and tried to interrupt the International
Monetary Fund-World Bank meeting in Washington in April say Windsor
is the next stop.
</P>
<P>
   The official agenda lacks any trade issues that inspired street
protests complete with pepper spray, damaged property and televised
images of police clubbing demonstrators in Seattle and Washington.	   But
protesters say some of the broad issues being discussed --
globalization and poverty -- also involve free trade. Apparently
gearing up for a confrontation, a group called the Coalition to
Shut Down the OAS held a workshop Friday at the University of
Windsor to discuss issues such as how to deal with pepper spray and
protesters' legal rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to have some kind of voice. ... Shut down the meeting
so that they listen and hear as they listened and heard in
Seattle,'' said Jean Grossholtz, a professor at Mount Holyoke
College in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Axworthy, the Canadian foreign affairs minister and
chairman of the OAS assembly, called threatened protests a
''perverse response'' to a meeting designed to discuss ''human
rights, democracy, corporate responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The very issues that the groups say they're interested in,
they're trying to forestall by shutting the meeting down,''
Axworthy said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Windsor and the neighboring city of Detroit, just
across the Detroit River, were shuttering windows and beefing up
police presence in anticipation of protests.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers in both cities will have riot gear, and Windsor
police will get gas masks. Across the street from the OAS
conference site, the CIBC Bank covered its windows but planned to
be open Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the OAS permanent council has asked the foreign
ministers heading to Canada to consider possible action against
Peru, where President Alberto Fujimori was the sole candidate in
last week's election run-off because his opponent, Alejandro
Toledo, boycotted what he believed was an unfair process.
</P>
<P>
   The head of an OAS observer mission at the election, Eduardo
Stein, said Peruvian authorities surprised the mission by
introducing new computer software for the vote count just days
before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Stein asked for a delay in the voting so that he could test the
software, but was turned down. The OAS mission then left Peru
before the run-off vote.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian officials have accused the OAS mission of failing to
remain neutral.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.S. official said Thursday that Washington wanted ''as
vigorous a response as possible'' from the OAS foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign ministers were unlikely to take strong action, such
as imposing sanctions, because some nations fear setting a
precedent of OAS intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Organization of American States: http://www.oas.org
</P>
<P>
   Protest coalition: http://www.tao.ca
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1645 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emissions test snags cost official his job  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The Division of Motor Vehicles official in
charge of New Jersey's problem-plagued emissions testing program
has quit.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Passeri stepped down recently from his $95,000-per-year job
as executive director of the state's Clean Air Program.
</P>
<P>
   News of his resignation came as state officials admit they're at
least a month away from fixing the emissions testing system, which
was supposed to be back in full operation by last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Top state officials refused comment on Passeri's resignation,
and he could not be reached for comment, The Star-Ledger of Newark
reported for Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if anyone had asked for Passeri's resignation, his
immediate supervisor, DMV director Dick Kamin said, ''I think that
kind of question should be put to the commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Commissioner James Weinstein refused to comment
on the resignation, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Neil Cohen, D-Union, said Passeri is being made
a scapegoat for the Whitman administration's failure on the issue,
which has angered thousands of motorists, some of whom had to
endure lines of up to four hours when the tougher new test debuted
in December.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like he's going to be the clear victim in a process
that began long before he became employed by the state,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   Passeri was responsible for coordinating the inspections program
overhaul with Parsons Infrastructure and Technology, the Pasadena,
Ca., company New Jersey hired to run its inspection stations.
</P>
<P>
   The new test, designed to more accurately measure tailpipe
pollution, was plagued by problems and breakdowns since it was
instituted last winter. Equipment failed or froze up in cold
weather, and employees struggled to operate the new system.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper reported Passeri ignored a consultant's warnings
before the new system was instituted and continually defended it,
even as it broke down.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as April 11, Passeri wrote a memo defending the
state's ongoing work with Parsons.
</P>
<P>
   Peter McDonough, a spokesman for Gov. Christie Whitman, would
not comment on Passeri's resignation, other than to say his
responsibilities have been transferred to Al Ari, an assistant
transportation commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey also faces a June 30 deadline to meet federal clean
air standards, a goal it is not likely to meet. Although the state
runs the risk of losing substantial transit aid for failing to meet
the deadline, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency has
indicated it will grant an extension.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1646 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0109 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Bush Reprieve Was Political  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Six of 10 Americans say George W. Bush
approved his first reprieve in a Texas death penalty case for
political reasons, according to a new poll. Bush supporters were
about evenly split on his motivation for approving the reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor and likely Republican presidential nominee
says he approved a 30-day reprieve for Ricky McGinn so that
potential DNA evidence that might exonerate him could be reviewed,
although the U.S. Supreme Court had earlier denied McGinn's
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Governor Bush makes decisions based on what's right, not on
public opinion polls or politics,'' Bush campaign spokesman Ray
Sullivan said Saturday. ''He believes it's right to allow DNA
evidence to be reviewed in the context of all the evidence if it's
relevant to the guilt or innocence of a person on death row.''
</P>
<P>
   Four in 10 Bush supporters said the decision was for political
reasons, while about the same number felt he did it based on the
facts.
</P>
<P>
   The Newsweek poll released Saturday indicated that Americans
overwhelmingly favor states permitting DNA testing in all death row
cases where it might prove an inmate's innocence or guilt, with 95
percent taking that stand. Almost that many agreed with a federal
requirement for all states to adopt such a policy.
</P>
<P>
   While Americans overwhelmingly support use of DNA testing when
it could prove an inmate's innocence, the death penalty is still
supported by three-fourths of the public. When asked what crimes
warrant the death penalty, four in 10 said only those inmates
convicted of the most brutal murders, mass murders and serial
killings. Only a fifth of those questioned opposed the death
penalty in all cases. A third of death penalty supporters say the
main reason they support it is because they believe it deters
others from committing violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential race remains close, according to the Newsweek
poll of 750 adults taken Thursday and Friday. Republican Bush was
at 44 percent and Democrat Al Gore at 43 percent. The error margin
was plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was ahead in several national polls in recent weeks, but
three polls in the last week had the race virtually even, including
two polls of likely voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is substantially ahead in the crucial race for electoral
votes, however. He leads in almost 20 states with more than
two-thirds of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidency.
Gore is ahead in fewer than 10 states with less than half the votes
he would need to win.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.newsweek.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1654 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Queen, Camilla Parker Bowles Meet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- After years of resistance, Queen Elizabeth II
relented Saturday and met socially with Prince Charles' companion
Camilla Parker Bowles at a private party.
</P>
<P>
   The queen had known Mrs. Parker Bowles many years before the
breakup of Prince Charles' marriage to Princess Diana. But because
the monarch is head of the Church of England, she reportedly has
avoided socializing with Parker Bowles out of concern that she
would appear to endorse a relationship that began in adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Public anger toward Parker Bowles appears to have subsided in
the nearly three years since Princess Diana's death, and the couple
are seen together with increasing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two hours after a Sky TV report of the meeting of the
queen and Parker Bowles, Buckingham Palace confirmed the two women
were at Highgrove, the prince's country home in western England,
for a 60th birthday party for ex-King Constantine of Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Sky said an unidentified source at Prince Charles' St. James's
Palace office had described the prince as ''pleased and grateful''
that the queen had at last decided to meet with his longtime
companion and that the meeting was ''characterized by warmth and
friendliness.''
</P>
<P>
   Early editions of The News of the World, a Sunday tabloid that
broke the story on its Web site Saturday, said the queen approached
Parker Bowles in the drawing room at Highgrove and that they
chatted for 10 minutes. The queen then went on to meet the European
royals gathered for Constantine's party.
</P>
<P>
   The queen knew Parker Bowles before and during her marriage to
Andrew Parker Bowles, who has long been familiar in royal circles
and once held the ceremonial post of ''Silver-Stick-in-Waiting to
the Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   But they have rarely met in public or private, and not since the
publicity that followed Princess Diana's revelation that the two
had had an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Prince William, 17, and his 15-year-old brother Prince Harry
also were present.
</P>
<P>
   William met Parker Bowles nearly two years ago and he and Harry
reportedly get along well with her and her two children.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles has been discreet but has made no secret of his
relationship, and the two went public with a much-photographed
appearance together in January 1999. In what appears to have been a
quiet campaign to win public acceptance, they have appeared
together in public with increasing frequency.
</P>
<P>
   The News of the World's royalty editor Clive Goodman told Sky
News on Saturday that the meeting at Highgrove will be interpreted
as a ''first step on the long and complicated road to remarriage.''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles has said he has no intention of remarrying.
Although experts have said there would be no constitutional problem
with such a marriage, it would present difficulties for his future
role as head of the Church of England, which opposes remarriage
after divorce.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
