<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians Resume Talks  </HEADLINE>
By JACK KATZENELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians have resumed their
talks on a permanent peace treaty, a Palestinian official said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting took place Thursday night and early Friday morning
said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He refused
to say where it was held.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations, which were previously being held in the
Swedish capital Stockholm, were moved to an undisclosed location,
presumed to be in Israel or the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
   Taking part were the speaker of the Palestinian parliament,
Ahmed Qureia, and Israeli Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions are aimed at achieving a framework for the final
status agreement between the two sides. On the agenda are the
thorniest issues, such as the permanent borders, the future of the
Palestinian refugees and control of Jerusalem. Little progress has
been made on these issues in six months of talks.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat accused each other last week of foot-dragging, saying the
other was not serious about reaching an agreement by a Sept. 13
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after a meeting with Barak in Lisbon, President Clinton
acknowledged that ''tough work'' was ahead for both sides, but said
an agreement was ''within view.''
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is due to arrive in the
Middle East by Monday for consultations with Arafat and Barak.
Arafat then will visit Washington for talks with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The President hopes to preside over the end the
Israeli-Palestinian conflict, before the end of his term, at a Camp
David style summit with Arafat and Barak in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   However he is not expected to convene the summit if he is not
sure that the agreement will be achieved. The decision on whether
to hold the summit is expected in the next few weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
