<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Islamic Leaders Cheered  </HEADLINE>
By RANJAN ROY
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUALA TERENGGANU, Malaysia (AP) -- Nearly 2,000 people cheered
Malaysia's Islamic leaders at an opposition party rally Saturday,
sending a grim message to the country's longtime ruling premier.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are prepared to sacrifice everything, including our lives,
to defend Islam against those who are corrupting it,'' opposition
leader Munir Zakaria told a crowd gathered in an indoor stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd responded with applause and cries of ''Allahu Akbar,''
Arabic for ''God is Great.''
</P>
<P>
   Munir's Pan-Malaysian Islamic Party, or PAS, could pose a
serious threat to the 19-year rule of Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
   Once little more than a small group of radical clerics, the
Islamic party stunned observers by winning the two northern states
in November elections and tripling its seats in the national
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the party -- which holds a majority in Kelantan and
Terengganu states -- have promised to seize more power in 2004
elections and replace the government it has criticized for not
being Islamic enough.
</P>
<P>
   In its two states, PAS has enforced strict Islamic codes not
found elsewhere in predominantly Muslim Malaysia, including a
restriction on alcohol, gambling and entertainment. The party has
also forced Muslim women to wear head scarves in public, often
against their wishes.
</P>
<P>
   While the party says its success stems from its conservative and
religious slant, others have attributed it to disaffection among
young Malays over the premier's harsh treatment of his former
deputy, Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   Anwar is now serving a six-year prison term for corruption, and
is on trial separately for alleged sodomy. His sacking and arrest
in September 1998 provoked violent street protests, which have
since subsided.
</P>
<P>
   The government -- led by Mahathir's United Malays National
Organization party -- has threatened to outlaw the flagrant use of
Islam for political gain. If proposed legislation is enacted, PAS
could be forced to drop the word Islam from its name.
</P>
<P>
   Some warned, though, that using federal and legislative muscle
to curb the Islamic could provoke a violent backlash in the
Southeast Asian country.
</P>
<P>
   ''It could lead to uneasiness in the country. We fear it could
lead to demonstrations and unrest,'' said Nasharuddin Mat Isa, the
party's secretary general.
</P>
<P>
   Mahathir's 14-party coalition controls more than two-thirds of
parliamentary seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1706 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
