<DOCNO> APW20000603.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Lincoln Papers Sell For $104,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Two letters written by President Lincoln sold
for $104,000 at auction Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Trocano, a spokeswoman for Dargate Auction Galleries in
Pittsburgh, said one letter, which sold for $54,000, was Lincoln's
appointment of former Ohio governor and presidential campaign rival
Salmon P. Chase to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The other, which sold for $50,000, was a handwritten note
summoning Chase to Washington for advice after South Carolina left
the Union in 1860, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The letters came from two descendants of Chase's attorney,
Trocano said.
</P>
<P>
   She wouldn't identify the descendants or the buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Another letter, to Chase from Union Gen. William Tecumseh
Sherman, sold for $26,000. In the letter, Sherman advised Chase to
delay allowing blacks to vote after the Civil War because he feared
the war would resume.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 1728 </TRAILER>
