<DOCNO> APW20000603.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liberals back Hillary Clinton; Conservatives opt for Lazio  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton, labeled a far-left
liberal by critics, accepted the backing of New York's Liberal
Party on Saturday while her Republican Senate rival Rick Lazio,
dubbed a right-wing conservative by the first lady, embraced the
Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   In Albany, the Conservatives opened their session with an
invocation from the party treasurer, Jim Gay, in which he called
for ''the defeat of evil'' and then identified that as ''the
candidate of the Democratic and Liberal parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also came out swinging. While not mentioning his opponent
by name, he told the Conservatives he believed ''this is a job that
I must earn, not one that you are handed because of your last
name.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is one thing we have learned over these last several
years, it is this: character counts; integrity matters; and the
truth is the foundation upon which our democracy exists,'' added
the little-known congressman from Long Island in coming the closest
yet to raising the specter of the Clinton scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in New York City and out from under the shadow of
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, the leaders of the Liberal Party met at a
Manhattan hotel to unanimously bless Clinton's candidacy and
directly take on the issue of her being a carpetbagger.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being a New Yorker is a matter of spirit, not a matter of
origin,'' said Martin Begun, a Liberal party vice chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I respect the history of this party,'' said Clinton, standing
next to party leader Raymond Harding, who called himself ''a close
friend'' of Giuliani -- until recently Clinton's Republican
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsements could spell the difference in a close race.
</P>
<P>
   By the numbers, the advantage would appear to go to Lazio, who
became the GOP's candidate after the New York City mayor withdrew
from the race last month to battle prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party had 171,496 members while the Liberal
Party had 92,074 members as of March, according to the latest
figures from the state Board of Elections.
</P>
<P>
   More important may be the votes the parties can produce at the
polls. In losing his bid for a fourth Senate term in 1998,
Republican Alfonse D'Amato collected more than 250,000 votes on the
Conservative Party line. Democratic winner Charles Schumer nabbed
just over 50,000 votes on the Liberal line.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long predicted he
could turn out at least 350,000 votes for Lazio this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very happy about getting the Conservative Party
nomination,'' Lazio said. ''I'll take that deal any day.''
</P>
<P>
   No Republican seeking statewide office in New York has won
without Conservative Party support since 1974. Conversely, no
Democrat has been elected governor or U.S. senator in New York
without Liberal Party backing since it was founded more than 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the endorsements served to highlight the favorite negative
themes emanating from each campaign. The first lady has been
portraying Lazio as a right-wing buddy of former House Speaker Newt
Gingrich while Lazio has denounced Clinton as the candidate of the
''far left.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said Saturday that Clinton's acceptance of the Liberal
Party backing ''speaks to who she is.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady declined to characterize Lazio's embrace of the
Conservative Party, but campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson later
said, ''It is unsurprising that Rick Lazio has picked up the
Conservative Party endorsement given his opposition to common sense
gun-control measures and his support for restricting a woman's
right to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   The path was cleared for Clinton to get the Liberal Party nod
after Giuliani quit the Senate race last month to battle prostate
cancer. One of Giuliani's closest political advisers has been
Harding. He quickly lined up with Clinton after the mayor withdrew
from the race.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's departure also opened the way for the Republican and
Conservative parties to restore their traditional partnership in
statewide races. Long had refused to get behind Giuliani because of
the mayor's strong support for abortion rights and his closeness to
the Liberal Party.
</P>
<P>
   While Lazio has said he is an abortion rights supporter, he has
repeatedly voted to cut off federal Medicaid money to pay for poor
women's abortions and favors a ban on what critics call
''partial-birth abortion.'' That was enough to win Long's support.
</P>
<P>
   But Lazio's support for abortion rights in general has caused
the anti-abortion Right to Life Party to go its own way in the
Senate race, a situation that could cost Lazio some votes.
</P>
<P>
   Even among the Conservative Party leaders, the backing for Lazio
was not unanimous Saturday because of the abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pro-life ... and I don't believe he's as conservative as
they say he is,'' explained Tom Clark of Nassau County on Long
Island as he cast the lone vote against Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in an interview with CNN after attending the
Conservative Party convention, Lazio said he believed the
anti-abortion plank of the national GOP's platform should be
removed, a position also being pushed by New York Gov. George
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it needs to come out. I think we need to stay silent
on the issue. It's a divisive issue,'' Lazio said. ''I think our
main thrust should be on changing the culture as opposed to
criminalizing abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Lazio said he would not be bothered if George W.
Bush selects a staunchly anti-abortion running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also told CNN that he favors a 12-year term limit for
senators and he reiterated his decision not to take campaign money
from the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party backing can be critical in New York elections.
Three-term Democratic incumbent Mario Cuomo was beaten by
Republican George Pataki in the 1994 governor's race on the
strength of the 328,695 votes he received on the Conservative Party
line.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
count votes they receive on third-party ballot lines.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Independence Party, the state arm of the national
Reform Party, will hold its state nominating convention on Monday
in Albany. On Saturday, Clinton said she would not attend the
convention or seek the party's backing because of the possibility
conservative presidential candidate Pat Buchanan would be at the
top of its ticket. Lazio, while criticizing Buchanan, has said he
is willing to run on the line even if Buchanan is also on the
ticket. Lazio aides said Saturday they weren't certain if he would
attend the Independence Party convention.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-03-00 1811 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Backed by NY Liberal Party  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Locked in a tight race where every vote
could count, Hillary Rodham Clinton accepted the backing of New
York's Liberal Party on Saturday while her Republican Senate rival
Rick Lazio was embraced by the Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
   However support for Lazio, who favors abortion rights for women,
was not unanimous because of his views on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pro-life ... and I don't believe he's as conservative as
they say he is,'' explained Tom Clark of Nassau County as he cast
the lone vote against Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with CNN after attending the Conservative Party
convention, Lazio said he believed the anti-abortion plank of the
national GOP's platform should be removed, a position also being
pushed by New York Gov. George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it needs to come out ... It's a divisive issue,''
Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the leaders of the Liberal Party met at a Manhattan
hotel to bless Clinton's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being a New Yorker is a matter of spirit, not a matter of
origin,'' said Martin Begun, a Liberal party vice-chair.
</P>
<P>
   He cited famed New Yorkers who, like Clinton, were born out of
state, including Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who was born in
Tulsa, Okla., and whose Democratic seat she is seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party backing can be critical in New York elections.
Three-term Democratic incumbent Mario Cuomo was beaten by
Republican George Pataki in the 1994 governor's race on the
strength of the 328,695 votes he received on the Conservative Party
line
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to
count votes they receive on third-party ballot lines.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican seeking statewide office in New York has won
without Conservative Party support since 1974. At the same time, no
Democrat has been elected governor or U.S. senator in New York
without Liberal Party backing since it was founded more than 50
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Billing themselves the nation's longest existing third party,
the Liberals have in the past backed New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and other candidates of various political affiliations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I respect the history of this party,'' said Clinton, standing
next to party boss Ray Harding, who called himself ''a close
friend'' of Giuliani -- until recently Clinton's main opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Conservative Party leadership handed its backing to
the little-known congressman from Long Island at a nominating
convention in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a job that I must earn, not one that you are handed
because of your last name,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The developments could spell the difference in a close race. By
the numbers, the advantage would appear to go to Lazio, who became
the GOP's candidate after the New York City mayor withdrew from the
race last month to battle prostate cancer. Recent polls show
Clinton and Lazio in a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party had 171,496 members while the Liberal
Party had 92,074 members as of March, according to the latest
figures from the state Board of Elections.
</P>
<P>
   More important may be the votes the parties can produce at the
polls. In losing his bid for a fourth Senate term in 1998,
Republican Alfonse D'Amato collected more than 250,000 votes on the
Conservative Party line. Democratic winner Charles Schumer nabbed
just over 50,000 votes on the Liberal line.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long predicted he
could turn out at least 350,000 votes for Lazio this year.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsements also highlighted the favorite negative themes
of each campaign. The first lady has been portraying Lazio as a
right-wing buddy of former House Speaker Newt Gingrich while Lazio
has denounced Clinton as the candidate of the ''far left.''
</P>
</TEXT>
