<DOCNO> APW20000603.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan, Perot Factions Tussle  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Patrick Buchanan and his supporters told
Reform Party veterans in California that his White House bid would
save Ross Perot's group from destroying itself.
</P>
<P>
   But state party leaders weren't feeling conciliatory Saturday,
moving toward splitting from the national party this fall and deny
Buchanan ballot access in the nation's largest state.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party in Minnesota has already broken ties with the
national party and other state parties are considering the move.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we're not united, we can't reach out and get those
conservative Republicans, we can't get those union Democrats, we
can't get those folks who voted for Ross Perot and have walked away
from politics,'' Buchanan told about 400 people in attendance at
the state's Reform Party convention.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Perot, a Texas billionaire, said the price of
being rescued by Buchanan-- accepting his conservative social
positions -- is too high.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's not rescuing us; it may be just the opposite,'' said Bob
Ferrario of Los Gatos, Calif., who is attending the California
convention. ''He just wants to use it as a platform for his social
philosophy, but that's not what we're about. We're centrist.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan promised to do his best to unite the party if he
receives the nomination at the convention Aug. 10-13 in Long Beach.
He appealed for an end to bickering or risk harming the party's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we win this battle and we've got the delegates, I would ask
people even if they disagree: What's good is it going to do then to
keep arguing and damage our cause?'' Buchanan asked.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who bolted the GOP in October after being overshadowed
by other candidates for the third straight presidential election,
would receive $12.6 million in federal funding if he is nominated
by the Reform Party at its August convention. A state-by-state
drive to secure delegates has made him the leader among some 10
candidates for the nomination, though he has been unable to break
roughly 4 percent in national polls.
</P>
<P>
   Perot received 19 percent in the 1992 presidential election and
8 percent in 1996. Unless the bickering stops, Buchanan said, the
party won't achieve those results.
</P>
<P>
   Some state and national party leaders would rather take that
chance than accept Buchanan, his staunch anti-abortion positions
and his rejection of any running mates that are homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, eight of 13 members of the state party's
governing board approved a resolution that said the state
organization would split from the national party after the
convention, unless Buchanan agrees:
</P>
<P>
   --to ''affirm'' the party's practice of electing a vice
presidential candidate at the national convention, rather than
leaving it up to the presidential candidate
</P>
<P>
   --to apply no ''litmus tests'' to any running mate
</P>
<P>
   --to make no attempt to change the national party's platform to
reflect his social issues
</P>
<P>
   Asked during a question-and-answer period to respond to each
point, Buchanan said cryptically that while the convention
''obviously'' picks the vice presidential hopeful, ''my running
mate will be pro-life.'' He has said in the past that he would not
run on the same ticket as anyone who favors aborton rights.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan did not respond to the question about litmus tests, but
he said he would not try to add his social views to the party
platform this year.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has said that if he were nominated to the top of the
ticket, he would also be the head of the party and would expect the
organization to reflect his views.
</P>
<P>
   His vague answers meant the state board of directors likely
would submit the resolution Sunday on breaking free on Sunday to
the roughly 180 state delegates for approval.
</P>
<P>
   John Hagelin and Charles Collins, other Reform presidential
candidates, also spoke and promised to unite the party by keeping
their focus away from social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Though the convention voted to exclude about 60 Buchanan
supporters from the proceedings over the weekend, his supporters
were a voluble presence at the Furama Hotel. They jumped to their
feet, screaming, ''Go Pat Go,'' when he entered the ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Lois Jackson took solace in her candidate's style.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every good party needs a good leader,'' said Lois Jackson, a
retired teacher from San Diego. ''If it can be rescued, he's the
only one who can do it at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Perot is watching from the sidelines in Dallas - for now. He has
made clear to those close to him that he has no intention of
attending a convention at which Buchanan is nominated.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrario acknowledged Buchanan isn't the only cause for the
volatile state of the party.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were fighting, we had no charismatic leader, so we were
vulnerable to a takeover by someone like Buchanan,'' he said.
''It's partly the party's own fault.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
