<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, June 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Backed by NY Liberal Party
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Locked in a tight race where every vote could count,
Hillary Rodham Clinton accepted the backing of New York's Liberal Party today
while her Republican Senate rival Rick Lazio was embraced by the Conservative
Party. However support for Lazio, who favors abortion rights for women, was not
unanimous because of his views on the subject. ''I'm pro-life ... and I don't
believe he's as conservative as they say he is,'' explained Tom Clark of Nassau
County as he cast the lone vote against Lazio.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Bush Reprieve Was Political
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Six of 10 Americans say George W. Bush approved his first
reprieve in a Texas death penalty case for political reasons, according to a new
poll. Bush supporters were about evenly split on his motivation for approving
the reprieve. The Texas governor and likely Republican presidential nominee says
he approved a 30-day reprieve for Ricky McGinn so that potential DNA evidence
that might exonerate him could be reviewed, although the U.S. Supreme Court had
earlier denied McGinn's appeals.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel, Palestinians Resume Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israel and the Palestinians have resumed their talks on a
permanent peace treaty, a Palestinian official said Saturday. The meeting took
place Thursday night and early Friday morning said the official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. He refused to say where it was held. The negotiations,
which were previously being held in the Swedish capital Stockholm, were moved to
an undisclosed location, presumed to be in Israel or the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Putin Meet in Moscow
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Clinton and Vladimir Putin dined on trout, goose and
spicy boar in a Kremlin summit dinner Saturday, with Clinton intrigued by the
new Russian president's suggestion he has relaxed his stern opposition to a
planned U.S. system to defend against missile attacks. But a senior
administration official, briefing reporters later, refused to specify whether
Putin demonstrated a willingness to go along with a modification of the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty that Clinton would need to build such a defense.
Clinton will not decide until fall whether to try to construct one, now being
tested.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FDA OK's Heart Clot-Busting Drug
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new clot-busting drug approved by federal regulators can
reduce the time it takes to treat heart attack victims from 90 minutes to five
seconds, using a single swift injection to dissolve clots that choke off the
heart's blood supply. Tenecteplase, made by Genentech Inc., won Food and Drug
Administration approval yesterday and will be made widely available as soon as
possible to treat the nation's biggest killer, company officials said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Russia Ministry Chides U.N. Prosecutor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on Saturday criticized the
decision of the chief U.N. war crimes prosecutor not to investigate allegations
that NATO committed war crimes during last year's air campaign against
Yugoslavia. A Russian parliamentary commission and lawyers working for
Yugoslavia had produced evidence to support charges that NATO committed war
crimes during its 78-day bombing campaign. However, chief prosecutor Carla del
Ponte told the Security Council on Friday that there was no basis for an
investigation into NATO's conduct, and that she was satisfied NATO had not
deliberately targeted civilians or illegal military areas.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Marks Tiananmen Anniversary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Families of those killed planned quiet memorials, dissidents
demanded redress and police tightened security Saturday on the eve of the 11th
anniversary of the Chinese government's crackdown on the Tiananmen Square
pro-democracy protests. In an open letter to Chinese President Jiang Zemin,
eight dissidents said the government was ''absolutely wrong'' to crush the seven
weeks of protests centered on the Beijing square, a Hong Kong-based human rights
group said. To prevent commemorations, extra military police patrolled today in
front of Tiananmen gate, which overlooks the square.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Braves Defeat Yankees 11-7
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- New York's Roger Clemens and Atlanta's Greg Maddux faced each
other for the first time today but hardly looked like two pitchers with nine Cy
Youngs between them. Instead, Javy Lopez came through with a two-out, two-run
double in the seventh inning and the Braves slugged their way to an 11-7 victory
over the Yankees.
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER 
</P>
