<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Election Council Named  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER TOOTHAKER
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- One week after Venezuela's election
council resigned amid accusations of incompetence, a new council
was named Saturday whose members were chosen in part for their lack
of political ties.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the five-member board by Venezuela's interim
legislature came after a high court suspended last Sunday's
national elections, citing technical glitches that threatened the
transparency of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of the Supreme Tribunal of Justice -- the country's
highest court -- and mounting pressure from both pro-government and
opposition parties led to the resignation of the election council.
</P>
<P>
   The suspension of elections comes at a critical time for this
South American nation of 23 million people. Politically, the
country has been in limbo since President Hugo Chavez pushed
through a new constitution last year and dissolved the congress.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelans were slated to vote for more than 6,000 offices as
called for by the new constitution. It requires the
''re-legitimization'' of most public offices including the
presidency, congress, governorships and most local posts.
</P>
<P>
   The naming of the new council was a response to calls for a more
transparent process. The selection of previous council members was
widely criticized since they were hand-picked by Chavez's political
allies.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the new council were chosen for their management
skills, technical capacity, and lack of political ties. The new
members were chosen from a list of close to 350 candidates who were
nominated by Venezuela's civil organizations, including academic
and professional associations.
</P>
<P>
   Elias Jaua, vice president of the temporary congress, said he
hoped the new council will help restore public trust.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are people who have never had political ties and will
generate the confidence that the country requires,'' said Jaua.
</P>
<P>
   Elias Santana, a representative of Queremos Elegir, one of two
group's who asked the high court to suspend national elections,
said the new council's first job will be to clean up the
institution and rid it of all the ''political ties.''
</P>
<P>
   A new election date was expected to be announced next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
