<HEADLINE> Democratic candidates hit urban areas to get out the vote  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTCLAIR, N.J. (AP) -- Jon Corzine started at the head of the
parade but within minutes few could keep up, not the drum corps,
not classic cars, not even the son of Martin Luther King, Jr.,
called in to rally voters for Tuesday's election.
</P>
<P>
   The multimillionaire Democratic candidate for U.S. Senate seemed
to sprint from handshake to handshake, once jogging across the
street through marchers to greet an elderly woman walking alone
with a cane. Residents cheered his name, promised support and some
joked about autographs.
</P>
<P>
   As Corzine coasted through Montclair's African American Day
Parade on Saturday, supporters strolled behind, reminding any who
would listen they were there for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're even going to bring Martin Luther King's son because we
need all the votes we can,'' shouted Assemblywoman Nia Gill,
D-Essex.
</P>
<P>
   On the first day of the last weekend before the primary, both
Democratic candidates targeted urban areas across the state,
reminding all who would listen that Tuesday is the day they need
voters the most.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Jim Florio began the day at a bagel shop in
Livingston before stops in Secaucus, Harrison, Elizabeth and
Trenton by mid-afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In the shadow of the Statehouse, Florio introduced himself and
wife Lucinda over and over again to people at Trenton's Heritage
Days. With each greeting, Florio reminded potential voters he was
once governor and now he wants to be senator.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's all about energizing people,'' Florio said. His plan was
to spend the weekend in urban areas, surrounded by crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ''The most important thing to do is to get them to come out and
vote,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine started in Montclair and planned a lengthy tour of
Newark's North Ward and then to Trenton and back up to a rally in
Paterson.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King III planned to accompany Corzine at each
point. When the two met eight months ago at a fund-raising dinner
in Atlanta, King said he decided to support Corzine, a former
chairman of Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I heard the ideas he was espousing, about health care,
about education, about inclusion, I felt he was the kind of
candidate I would want to see in the U.S. Senate,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine supporters repeatedly said money is not an issue -- not
even the $33 million he plans to spend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see all the other guys doing that. He's going to need it for
sure, but right now he's spending his own money,'' said Sam Pinkard
of Montclair.
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Frager planned to vote for Corzine no matter what he
eventually shells out of his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't see a problem with that,'' she said. ''What he's
saying is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen-year-old Anthony Austin said he did have one problem
with Corzine's millions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you wanted to get elected that bad, why not spend $100
million if he's got $400 million,'' Austin said as he watched
Corzine speedwalk along the parade route.
</P>
<P>
   Florio's backers often greeted him emotionally. They reminisced
from his term as governor and even talked about his $2.8 billion
tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''What he's doing today should have been done all over
Trenton,'' Mai-Tai McDonald said as she and her granddaughter
snacked in Mill Hill Park.
</P>
<P>
   Florio had just walked past, asking ''for your consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people have the wrong impression of him,'' McDonald
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
