<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Kennedy Accepts Nomination  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWELL, Mass. (AP) -- U.S. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, evoking the
memory of his late brothers John and Robert, accepted the
Democratic nomination Saturday for a seventh six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stand here today and think of my brothers,'' Kennedy told
the 2,100 delegates to the state party convention. ''I continue to
be guided by my brother John's ideals -- that we ask not what our
country can do for us, but what we can do for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little debate over the nomination, and Kennedy, a
senator since 1962, is heavily favored to win the November general
election. Republican Jack E. Robinson and Libertarian candidate
Carla Howell are challenging him.
</P>
<P>
   In a half-hour address, Kennedy, 68, touted his achievements in
the Senate and pledged to keep fighting on issues like education,
the environment and labor rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will win the battle to pass the patients' rights bill,'' he
said. ''We need decisions made by doctors, not by accountants of
HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   On the subject of campaign finance, Kennedy said it is time to
enact reform ''once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's tell the HMOs and the NRA and other special interest
groups their contributions will not prevail,'' he said. ''Their
gold is fool's gold.''
</P>
</TEXT>
