<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seattle's Piniella Believes In Mesa  </HEADLINE>
By JIM COUR
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Although Jose Mesa hasn't pitched for the Seattle
Mariners since his disastrous eighth inning in Tampa Bay last
Sunday, he'll be back on the mound soon.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella said before Saturday night's game between
the Mariners and San Diego Padres that he still has confidence in
the team's former closer.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been working with our pitching coach with altering his
delivery,'' Piniella said. ''Bryan (Price) told me yesterday he was
ready for game action again. So we'll get him back in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, 34, has been the target of boos at Safeco Field this
season. His horrendous performance in Tampa Bay's 11-run eighth
inning in Seattle's 14-4 loss last weekend, when he gave up seven
hits and eventually was ejected for throwing at Mike DeFelice, led
to speculation this week that the Mariners might release the
veteran right-hander, who is in the final year of a two-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mariners think Mesa can help them in their bid for the
AL West title.
</P>
<P>
   And Piniella denied he was holding Mesa out of games at Safeco
for public relations purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm trying to get him the right opportunity,'' Piniella said.
''I've been trying to find him the right spot. Certainly, I'd pitch
him at home. We'll pitch him at home or away. I'm just trying to
get him a nice spot to get him in. I've just been giving him a
little time to digest what the pitching coach has been trying to
get across.''
</P>
<P>
   After tying the Mariners' record with 33 saves in 38
opportunities last season, Mesa lost his closer's job to Japan's
Kazuhiro Sasaki in spring training. In 20 games this season, he has
an 8.14 ERA and a 2-4 record in 24 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Mesa recorded a major league-high 46 saves in 48
opportunities for Cleveland, setting a franchise record for saves
in a single season for the Indians. He has 137 career saves.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's had a lot of success in baseball,'' Piniella said of
Mesa, who played for Cleveland from 1992-98. ''Yes, your confidence
can wane. But with one good game, we can get him back on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Price, Seattle's first-year pitching coach, said he's moved Mesa
from the left to right side of the rubber in an effort to deceive
hitters and improve his control. Mesa still has a menacing fastball
that averages 92-96 mph with a top of 97 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wants the ball and he wants to turn this around,'' Price
said. ''I think he's confident that good things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Price said the boos that Mesa has been subjected to at Safeco
have been painful.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got to anticipate them until he turns it around,'' Price
said. ''But he can get the people back on his side. He can get them
to embrace him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
