<HEADLINE> Iran Said Linked to Pan Am Bombing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An Iranian defector says he has evidence that
Iran planned and financed the 1988 bombing of Pan Am flight 103,
which exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people.
</P>
<P>
   The defector, who says he is Ahmad Behbahani, coordinator of
Iran's terrorism operations for a decade or more, told CBS New's 60
Minutes that he has documents to prove his claims in an interview
scheduled to air Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA is debriefing Behbahani, now in protective custody in
Turkey, according to CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Two Libyans, Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa
Fhimah, who have been accused of planting the bomb in the Pan Am
jet's cargo hold, are in the midst of their trial before Scottish
judges on a former U.S. Air base in the Netherlands. They have
pleaded innocent, blaming two Syrian-based Palestinian factions
instead.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion over Lockerbie killed 259 Pan Am passengers and 11
people on the ground.
</P>
</TEXT>
