<P>
 Saturday, June 3, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
70,000 Rally for Elian in Cuba
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- A day after a massive march demanding the return of 6-year-old
Elian Gonzalez, a reported 70,000 people rallied in eastern Cuba, demanding the
boy be repatriated immediately. ''We raise our voices so our enemies can hear
us: Bring back Elian!'' Madelin Gonzalez, one of a dozen speakers, shouted from
the stage in Banes, in the eastern province of Holguin. The rally followed a
massive march in Havana on Friday by a reported half-million women angered by
the latest delay in Elian's return to his communist homeland.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sen. Kennedy Accepts Nomination
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOWELL, Mass. (AP) -- U.S. Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, evoking the memory of his
late brothers John and Robert, accepted the Democratic nomination today for a
seventh six-year term. ''I stand here today and think of my brothers,'' Kennedy
told the 2,100 delegates to the state party convention. ''I continue to be
guided by my brother John's ideals -- that we ask not what our country can do
for us, but what we can do for our country.'' In a half-hour address, Kennedy,
68, touted his achievements in the Senate and pledged to keep fighting on issues
like education, the environment and labor rights.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Former Secretary of Treasury Dies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- William Edward Simon, secretary of the treasury in the Nixon
and Ford administrations and the ''energy czar'' credited with easing public
fears during the 1970s oil crisis, died today, NBC reported. He was 72. NBC said
Simon died from complications from pulmonary fibrosis in Santa Barbara, Calif.
Simon had responsibility for the oil import program and quickly became expert on
the nation's escalating energy problems.
</P>
