<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 20:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Friends Battle For Stanley Cup  </HEADLINE>
By TOM CANAVAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Growing up in a small Canadian town in Nova Scotia
about 20 years ago, Jon Sim and Colin White were like most young
boys playing hockey.
</P>
<P>
   In their wildest dreams, they hoped that one day they would be
playing for the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The variable the two nearly lifelong friends never expected was
that they would live out their dream, playing against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Sim is actually reliving the dream, playing in his second
straight Cup final as a forward with the defending champion Dallas
Stars. White is getting his first chance to put his name on the Cup
as a rookie defenseman with the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really weird, especially coming from a small town,''
White said Saturday before Game 3 of the best-of-seven series. ''I
don't know if there was anyone in the Stanley Cup finals or even
played in the NHL from there. There probably was, but Jon took the
Cup home last year and that was the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully I will this year, but we're just taking it one game
at a time,'' said the 22-year-old White, 2{ months younger than
Sim.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening two games of the series, Sim and White have come
together and their friendship was forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Both players finished their checks. There was no trash talking
among friends.
</P>
<P>
   ''We both keep our mouths shut,'' White said. ''When it's all
said and done, there will be plenty to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sim said it has been fun seeing White on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy for him,'' Sim said. ''We've played each other quite
a bit, and all the bumping and grinding against each other is kind
of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   White said that while growing up in New Glasgow, a town of
10,000, there was no comparing the two players who were coached by
Sim's father. The 5-foot-10 Sim was a skilled scorer. The 6-4,
215-pound White was a banger on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was always the top player on the team,'' White said. ''He
was the team leader back then and I'm sure he'll have that
responsibility someday here.''
</P>
<P>
   White said the one constant is that back home their parents will
be rooting for both of them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We pretty much grew up in each other's household,'' White
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Sim brought the Stanley Cup home last summer, White's
parents saw hockey's most prestigious award.
</P>
<P>
   ''I wasn't home,'' White said. ''I was down in New Jersey trying
to make the team so I really didn't get to see it. My family went
over to see it and it was shared around the town.''
</P>
<P>
   One way or the other, the Cup is going back to New Glasgow this
summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 2038 </TRAILER>
