<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Chmura: I Will Be Released  </HEADLINE>
By TODD RICHMOND
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Green Bay tight end Mark Chmura, facing trial
on charges he sexually assaulted his 17-year-old baby sitter, said
the team has told him he will be released.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today I am saddened to announce that after eight wonderful
seasons, my tenure with the Green Bay Packers will be over,''
Chmura said Saturday during a news conference at attorney Gerald
Boyle's office. His lawyers said the formal release will come
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has always been a dream of mine to end my playing career
with the Green Bay Packers. Unfortunately, it does not appear that
will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Chmura had sex with the girl without her consent
in a bathroom at his friend Robert Gessert's Hartland home after a
night of drinking at a post-prom party. The teen was once a baby
sitter for Chmura's two children.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Packers general manager Ron Wolf called Chmura's friend and
attorney John Drana on Wednesday to inform him of the team's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf made no reference to the criminal case, Drana said.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura, 31, signed a five-year, $15 million contract in 1998.
The deal included a $3 million signing bonus. By releasing him
after June 1, the Packers gain $900,000 in salary cap room that
could be used to sign free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, his (Wolf's) word was, 'We have certain guidelines
we live by. I don't make them. Mark doesn't make them. We need the
salary cap room,''' Drana said.
</P>
<P>
   Packers officials did not immediately return calls Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura was near tears and his voice quivered as he read a
statement during the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked Wolf and Packers president Bob Harlan and apologized
to Packers fans for the ''mess that has been brought upon you.'' He
asked them to withhold judgment until he can present his case.
</P>
<P>
   ''To the greatest fans in all of sport, it has been a true honor
to wear the green and gold on your behalf,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura, nicknamed ''Chewy,'' became one of the game's elite
tight ends during the Packers' run to consecutive Super Bowl
appearances in 1997 and 1998. He was drafted out of Boston College
in the sixth round in 1992 and made the Pro Bowl three times.
</P>
<P>
   He missed all but two games last season with a neck injury that
caused partial paralysis in his arms and threatened to end his
career. He had planned to play in the upcoming season and
participated in the team's first mini-camp in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Packers took tight end Bubba Franks with their first-round
draft pick less that a week after Chmura's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Packers center Frank Winters, one of Chmura's closest friends on
the team, watched from behind a line of television cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is going to be a tough time,'' Winters said. ''I'm just
trying to be there and support him. He's doing a lot better than he
did when I first talked to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Drana said Chmura wants to play football again but he wouldn't
comment on whether any teams have expressed interest. Boyle, who
must keep track of Chmura's whereabouts as a condition of bail,
said he would allow Chmura to leave Wisconsin if another team wants
him.
</P>
<P>
   Chmura's agent Eric Metz said Saturday night that no team could
contact him until Chmura is officially released by the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a retirement speech,'' Drana said, although he and
Boyle said Chmura hasn't been able to rehabilitate his neck since
the allegations broke.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every ounce of my energy has been spent to rid myself and my
family of these untruthful allegations,'' Chmura said.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle said Chmura, listed at 6-foot-5 and 255 pounds in the
Packers' media guide, has lost 20 pounds since he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is like a serious illness,'' Boyle said. ''You can't get
your mind off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chmura is charged with third-degree sexual assault for allegedly
having sex with the girl. He could face 10 years in prison and a
$10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   An 18-year-old woman said Gessert fondled her while they were in
a hot tub. Gessert, 43, is charged with third- and fourth-degree
sexual assault and also has denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are due back in court June 23 to enter a plea. No trial
date has been set.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 2100 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0150 </DOCNO>
