<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Saturday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressINTERLEAGUE:
Tigers-Cubs:
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT: Days don't get much better than Saturday was for Jeff
Weaver. He pitched the Tigers to a victory, and he played at
Wrigley Field. ''When I heard I was starting at Wrigley, I was
fired up about it,'' he said. ''It was fun. The sun was out, the
wind was blowing in -- you can't ask for a better day in Chicago. I
wish every park was like this. With the history and the fans so
enthusiastic, it gets you really pumped up to pitch here.'' ... The
Tigers' victory was their first at Wrigley Field since Oct. 10,
1945, when they beat the Cubs 9-3 in Game 7 of the World Series.
... Juan Gonzalez, nursing a strained left foot, went 1-for-4 with
an RBI.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: SS Ricky Gutierrez, on the DL since May 25 with a
separated right shoulder, might be back for next weekend's
Cubs-White Sox series. ''It's going to be close,'' manager Don
Baylor said. ''We're looking at Friday, it could be Sunday.''
Gutierrez has only thrown soft toss, but he'll start taking
grounders in the next day or so. That will give Baylor a better
idea of when Gutierrez will be ready to go. ''I'm not going to put
him on the field until he's ready to throw from the hole,'' Baylor
said. ... Sammy Sosa homered at Wrigley Field for the first time
since May 10 -- a span of 42 at-bats at home. ''Don't remind me,''
Sosa said, smiling. ''Every player goes through that. I still
believe in myself.'' ... Cubs relievers allowed a run Saturday for
the first time in more than eight games -- a span of 18 innings.
Orioles-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Orioles manager Mike Hargrove will miss the final two
games of the series in Montreal to attend his son Andy's high
school graduation in Cleveland. Bench coach Jeff Newman will
substitute for Hargrove on Saturday night and Sunday. ... The
Orioles are 12-24 since April 22 when they were a season-high six
games over .500. ... Albert Belle had hit safely in 26 of his last
29 games entering Saturday night's game, going 37-for-111 (.333)
over that stretch. ... SS Mike Bordick has started in all of
Baltimore's 53 games.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: 2B Jose Vidro missed his first start of the season
Saturday night due to a sprained ligament in his right middle
finger. Vidro, who injured his finger two weeks ago while diving
back to first base, received a cortisone shot before the game and
is expected to miss three games. ... RF Vladimir Guerrero and 1B
Lee Stevens are the only remaining Expos to have started each of
Montreal's 52 games. ... RHP starter Mike Thurman was also given a
cortisone shot in his injured right elbow Saturday. Thurman is
currently on the 15-day disabled list with tendinitis for the
second time this season.
Blue Jays-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: Craig Grebeck, a former Marlins player, is hitless in
his last four games and is 1-for-23 (.043) in his last six. ...
Shannon Stewart is batting .471, with two home runs and nine RBIs
in his last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: RHP Alex Fernandez, on the DL since May 18 due to a
strained ligament in his right elbow and a sore rotator cuff in his
right shoulder, was in Birmingham, Ala., Thursday to be examined by
Dr. James Andrews. The examination confirmed that there was no
ligament tear. Since the inflammation in his elbow hasn't
completely subsided, however, Fernandez was instructed not to throw
for at least two more weeks. ... LF Cliff Floyd, best known for his
offensive skills, has made several spectacular defensive plays
recently, including a leaping catch that kept Toronto from tying
Friday's series opener in the ninth inning. ''He's getting to the
point now where you're more surprised when he doesn't catch
those,'' CF Preston Wilson said.
Royals-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals made several roster moves before
Saturday's game. They recalled RHP Jeff D'Amico from Triple-A Omaha
and activated OF Todd Dunwoody from the DL. To clear roster spots,
OF Mark Quinn was optioned to Omaha and C Jorge Fabregas was
designated for assignment. ... One night after getting a
season-high 19 hits in Boston, the Royals got only four on Friday
against the Pirates. ... Pittsburgh native Jason Rakers always
wanted to pitch at Three Rivers Stadium. On Friday, he did, but
gave up five runs in the eighth inning and let a 4-3 deficit get
out of reach. Rakers got in trouble by walking the first two
hitters, then was the victim of some well-placed hits. ''He's a
control pitcher so the two walks were very uncharacteristic,''
manager Tony Muser said. ''Nerves were undoubtedly a factor as
Rakers' parents and friends were on hand.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: How did interim manager Rick Renick celebrate
Friday's win? ''I went home and went to bed,'' Renick said. He
filled in for Gene Lamont, who was in Florida for his daughter's
high school graduation. The win goes on Lamont's record, even
though he was more than 1,000 miles away because of the baseball
policy on keeping stats for managers. ... 3B Aramis Ramirez has hit
.383 in 30 games since he was sent to Triple-A Nashville. His
recall to the Pirates is not imminent, though. The organization
wants to see some adjustments in Ramirez's swing that will let him
drive the ball with more authority. In his absence, the club is
getting by with a combination of veteran utility players, Luis Sojo
and Mike Banjamin.
Devil Rays-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: The Devil Rays began the night 0-10 in games started
by opposing left-handers. LHP Al Leiter started for the Mets. ...
Fred McGriff needed two hits to reach No. 2,000 in his career. He
hit his 400th home run Friday night. ... LF Greg Vaughn was back in
the starting lineup for the first time since leaving a game May 26
with a strained right hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: C Mike Piazza was back in the starting lineup for the
first time since being cut on the forehead by Gary Sheffield's
backswing Wednesday night in Los Angeles. Piazza spent part of
Friday at a hospital getting a CAT scan after feeling groggy. For
the first time this season, Piazza was wearing the hockey-style
catcher's mask, which affords more protection. He wore it a few
times last season. ... IF-OF Lenny Harris joined the Mets, a day
after they got him from Arizona for LHP Bill Pulsipher. Harris was
popular when he played for the Mets in 1998, and was all smiles as
he renewed acquaintances. He was given the former locker of another
talkative player no longer with the team -- Rickey Henderson. To
make room for Harris, the Mets optioned C Vance Wilson to Triple-A
Norfolk.
Red Sox-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: The condition of Pedro Martinez's strained left ribcage
remained the same and the two-time Cy Young award winner is
expected to make his next start on June 8 when Boston hosts
Cleveland in a makeup game. ... 2B Jeff Frye has batted in every
spot in the order except fourth this season. ... The Red Sox
optioned RHP John Wasdin to Triple-A Pawtucket and recalled RHP Rob
Stanifer. Wasdin was 0-2 with a 4.56 ERA in 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: 3B Scott Rolen, who sprained his left ankle on May
23, is responding to treatment and expected to return to the lineup
on June 9. ... LHP Scott Aldred, who has a tear in his right
shoulder, will likely have season-ending surgery within the next
week.
Twins-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Midre Cummings is more than halfway to the team
record for pinch-hits in a season. His two-run single Friday night
made him 10-for-22. The team record is 19 by Chip Hale in 1996. ...
The rest of the team is 5-for-33 pinch-hitting this season. ...
Sean Bergman gave up a first-inning homer to Barry Larkin on
Saturday, the sixth he'd allowed to right-handed hitters this
season. He's also given up six to left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Michael Tucker, in a 9-for-11 spurt, was in left
field for a second straight day in place of Dmitri Young, in a
5-for-40 slump. ... Barry Larkin's first-inning homer Saturday was
only his second hit in 16 at-bats. ... The Reds are one of only
three teams without a complete game (San Diego and Kansas City are
the other two).
Yankees-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: C Jorge Posada took a foul ball off his right knee in
the second inning and had to leave the game. X-rays were negative
and Posada was listed as day-to-day. Paul O'Neill also had to leave
in the sixth because of soreness in his lower right leg. He was
replaced by Shane Spencer. ... Derek Jeter tied his career high
with four hits, the 11th time he has done it. The SS had a chance
to break the mark but walked in the seventh and the ninth. He had
reached base seven straight times since Friday, with five hits and
two walks.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Manager Bobby Cox missed the game to attend the high
school graduation of his daughter Skyla. He was replaced by bench
coach Pat Corrales. ... 3B coach Ned Yost arrived at the clubhouse
in a coat and tie after attending the graduation of his son, Ned
Yost IV. The teen-ager, a baseball star at suburban Lassiter High,
will attend the University of Georgia next season. ... Relief
pitcher Greg McMichael said it will be at least four weeks before
he throws again, not two weeks as the team reported Friday.
McMichael, who went on the DL retroactive to May 28, has a slight
tear in his right rotator cuff, a similar injury to the one that
required surgery in October. The team hopes surgery will not be
required this time. ... Fernando Lunar had his first RBI with a
groundout.
White Sox-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: There is a reason the Chicago White Sox are winning
this season. ''Chemistry,'' Frank Thomas said. ''It's as simple as
that. We've got 25 guys here defending the house and if somebody
breaks in we'll fight them together. We have 25 guys here that love
each other. Everyone picks up each other. I've been on a lot of
ballclubs, but this one here I have a special feeling about.''
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: Shane Reynolds allowed only one earned run in taking
his second straight loss on Friday, but that's been happening to
him all season. He's allowed two or fewer earned runs in eight of
his 12 starts and the Astros are 3-5 in those eight games. ''It's
kind of unbelievable,'' he said. ''We're in a place right now where
a lot of us haven't ever been. The ball's just not bouncing our
way. Nobody likes this. It's just something we've got to work on.''
Indians-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Jim Thome and Manny Ramirez, who's on the DL with a
strained left hamstring, are moving up the team's career home run
list. Entering Saturday night's game, they were tied for sixth at
211. Andre Thornton is fifth at 214. ... The Indians had used 19
pitchers, including five rookies. That figure does not include
Scott Sanders, who started a rainout against Detroit May 18. ...
The three hits the Indians got against Darryl Kile and two
relievers Friday were a season low. ... The Indians are considering
trying Russell Branyan, called up from Triple-A Buffalo on Tuesday,
in right or left field. Manager Charlie Manuel doesn't think it
would take Branyan, a third baseman in the minors, to adapt.
Branyan hit .253 with 16 homers and 46 RBis in 41 games at Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: Fernando Vina had his right elbow wrapped in the
clubhouse before Saturday night's game, the spot where he got hit
by a pitch for the major league-leading 13th time the night before.
He led the AL with 25 hit by pitches in 1998. ''I don't move out of
the way, I hold my ground,'' Vina said. ''Sometimes that's smart
and sometimes it's not smart. You've got to be careful because it
can knock you out for a while.'' ... An official scoring change
removed an error from Vina, who ranged far to his right to glove
Jim Thome's smash in the sixth, but then bobbled the ball. ''In my
eyes, I went a long ways to even get in front of that ball,'' said
Vina, who has one error and had a 59-game errorless streak stopped
last month. ''Most guys don't even get in front of that, and he
didn't hit a 20-hopper.'' ... The Cardinals failed to homer Friday
night for only the eighth time in 54 games. They lead the majors
with 100 homers, 11 more than runnerup Toronto.
Diamondbacks-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Arizona had lost three consecutive one-run games on the
road before Friday's 5-4 victory over the Rangers. ... The
Diamondbacks have not lost more than three games in a row since
June 20-23 last year when they lost four in a row. ... Friday's
starter Brian Anderson has faced 115 batters without allowing a
walk. He also had a stretch of 156 batters in his last six starts
of 1998. ... LHP Bill Pulsipher, who Arizona acquired from the Mets
on Friday in a trade for Lenny Harris, was designated for
assignment Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: Texas put CF Ruben Mateo on the 15-day DL after the
rookie broke his right leg in Friday's game. He will miss the rest
of the season after a rod was surgically inserted in his femur. ...
Manager Johnny Oates said Gabe Kapler, still nursing a quadriceps
injury, will likely play center in Mateo's absence. ... The Rangers
purchased the contract of OF Scott Podsednik from Tulsa of the
Texas League Saturday. His stay will be short as Texas plans to
bring up a pitcher Monday to fill injured Darren Oliver's spot in
the rotation.
Padres-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: With two hits Friday night against the Seattle
Mariners, Tony Gwynn raised his career batting average as a DH to
.205. In nine career games as a DH, Gwynn was 8-for-39 with four
doubles and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: RHP Jose Mesa hasn't pitched for the Mariners since his
disastrous eighth inning in Tampa Bay last Sunday, but he will
soon. Manager Lou Piniella said before Saturday night's game
between Seattle and San Diego that he still has confidence in the
Mariners' former closer. ''He's been working with our pitching
coach with altering his delivery,'' Piniella said. ''Bryan (Price)
told me yesterday he was ready for game action again. So we'll get
him back in there.''
Giants-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: OF Ellis Burks was held out of Saturday's game
because of sore knees. ''He's a little sore today,'' Giants manager
Dusty Baker said. ''I also didn't like the matchup and wanted more
left-handed bats in the lineup.'' ... 1B J.T. Snow was scratched
from the starting lineup with the stomach flu. ... C Doug Mirabelli
was also scratched from the lineup with irritation in his right
eye. He was taken to San Francisco's St. Francis Hospital to be
examined by the team eye doctor. ... With Friday night's 5-4 loss
to the A's, the Giants fell to 3-12 in one-run games. ''I woke up
mad this morning,'' Baker said. ''I'm tired of losing one-run
games. I'm sick of it.''
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: The A's presented their all-Century team before
Saturday's game. The Manager of the Century, Connie Mack, was
represented by his daughter Ruth Mack-Clark, 86, who made her first
trip to the Coliseum for the presentation. She said her father
would probably like the current home run pace. ''He'd be happy to
have them hit home runs,'' said Mack-Clark. ''I'm sure he would
like it.'' Mack-Clark used to drive her father to and from the
ballpark and ''learned a lot about baseball. He taught me how to
keep score and he'd write 'K' for a strikeout because it was like a
knockout, and he was a big boxing fan too.'' Mack-Clark said
current A's first baseman Jason Giambi reminded her of former
Philadelphia A's slugger Jimmie Foxx, another member of the
all-Century team. ... Rickey Henderson was named Player of the
Century for the A's and was scheduled to attend the presentation,
but a bad back forced him to cancel plans. ... The A's activated DH
John Jaha from the 15-day DL before the game and sent 3B Adam Piatt
to Triple-A Sacramento of the PCL.
Dodgers-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: The Dodgers placed OF Geronimo Berroa on the 15-day
DL with a bruised left foot and designated left-handed reliever
Trever Miller for assignment. They also purchased the contract of
left-hander Onan Masaoka from Triple-A Albuquerque. ... Going into
Saturday's game against Anaheim, the Dodgers were the only NL team
with five players who have at least nine homers -- Gary Sheffield
(15), Eric Karros (15), Todd Hundley (13), Shawn Green (10), and
Kevin Elster (9).
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: SS Kevin Stocker, just acquired from Tampa Bay, dropped
a popup for an error on the first ball he handled. Stocker had made
seven errors in his last three games with Tampa Bay, and has 12
this season. ... Going into Saturday's game against the Dodgers,
the Angels led the AL in team batting at .292 after ranking last in
the league in 1999 at .256.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Rockies-Brewers:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Tom Goodwin is on pace to steal a club-record 64
bases. The mark is held by Eric Young (53). ... Colorado
left-handed relievers have been outstanding. Brian Bohanon, Mike
Myers and Gabe White are a combined 8-0 with a 1.57 ERA out of the
bullpen. ... Utility INF Aaron Ledesma turned 29 Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Milwaukee called up Santiago Perez from Triple-A
Indianapolis to take the roster spot of Mark Loretta, who went on
the 15-day disabled list Friday with a broken bone in his left
foot. Perez was batting .291 with two homers and 18 RBIs for the
Indians. Loretta has never been on the major league disabled list.
He had played an average of 142 games a year in his first three
full major league seasons. ... The Brewers are the wildest team in
the majors. They average 5.21 walks per game; second is Cincinnati
at 4.72.
</P>
