<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP candidates seek attention, support, after debates showing some contrasts </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The Republican candidates for U.S. Senate
are hitting the streets and mailboxes this weekend and, in the case
of the two perceived front-runners, the TV airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs is an effort to wake voters up about Tuesday's primary,
to win recognition, to denounce each other and -- perhaps toughest
of all -- to swim against the tide of Democrat Jon Corzine's $33
million spending spree as he tries to win the primary on the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is hard to get heard through all of that,'' said state Sen.
William Gormley, R-Atlantic, one of the GOP contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley's chief GOP opponent, U.S. Rep. Bob Franks, R-Berkeley
Heights, agreed: ''His spending is obscene. There is no other way
to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party, however, is not intimidated by Corzine
himself as a potential November opponent should he defeat former
Gov. Jim Florio Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state Republican chairman, Garabed Haytaian, said Corzine's
lavish ads have detailed an ultra-liberal agenda for giant federal
programs that are budget-busters and will make easy targets for the
GOP nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ''When all is said and done, we don't have to do a whole lot of
opposition research on those guys. They'll have done it for us,''
Haytaian said.
</P>
<P>
   Also chasing the GOP nomination are Essex County executive Jim
Treffinger and Ramapo College professor Murray Sabrin. Treffinger
is a former Democrat now veering to the right of the frontrunners,
and Sabrin, who ran for governor as a Libertarian in 1997,
outflanks them all on the conservative wing, with backing from the
anti-abortion and gun-owner lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Franks and Gormley stand as the perceived front-runners by
virtue of their moderate views, their county endorsements, in which
Franks has an edge, and their money, in which Gormley has an edge.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger has joined the leaders by raising more than $1
million and has firm support in Essex and Passaic counties, but
political analysts said he has made little headway outside that
base.
</P>
<P>
   All three are recognized members of the Republican Party and so
have tried to dismiss Sabrin as a renegade outsider with extremist
views. Sabrin has spent much of the primary campaign downplaying
positions he took in the 1997 gubernatorial campaign with regard to
the national libertarian platform, which opposes criminal laws
against drug use, prostitution and other ''victimless'' crimes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Sabrin still holds the libertarian view that
individual communities should decide whether activities such as
prostitution are legal or illegal -- but he doesn't espouse that
opinion unless asked.
</P>
<P>
   Franks has been after Gormley over his links to Florio, to
Democratic tax increases and to casino money, and Gormley has been
after Franks over his hesitation on New Jersey's ban on
semi-automatic rifles and on the Clinton impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   And Treffinger and Sabrin have been at each other sharply in the
contest for conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   But through the course of five debates, Franks, Gormley and
Treffinger were parallel more often than not, differing mostly in
their appeal for credibility. Sabrin, the odd man out on
organizational support, was often the odd man out on ideology as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Five debates over the past four weeks did highlight some
distinctions.
</P>
<P>
   Treffinger and Gormley attacked Franks for his support of a
House bill giving land owners the right to sue in federal court
when local regulations impair the resale value of their property.
They said it would diminish local authority to manage land use.
Franks said it was a fairness issue.
</P>
<P>
   Franks last week said he had opposed New Jersey's semi-automatic
weapons ban because it took away guns that had been lawfully
purchased. Gormley and Treffinger supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley opposed school vouchers. Franks said they were a good
idea but the federal government should not have a hand in it.
Treffinger supported federal school vouchers in troubled school
districts, claiming they would actually save tax dollars because
private school tuition is cheaper than the per-pupil cost in public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrin denounced his three Republican opponents as hypocritical
for opposing the medical procedure opponents call ''partial birth
abortion'' while sanctioning other forms of abortion. It also hard
to recall any Republican candidate more dedicated to gun rights
than Sabrin, who believes a well-armed citizenry would reduce
crime.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sabrin made provocative remarks in each of the GOP's
five debates. Before a live audience at the Jewish Community Center
of West Orange last week, Sabrin said he was so troubled by the
overgrowth of federal bureaucracy, he feared the nation was headed
toward totalitarianism comparable to the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who knew Hitler was coming? But he did come,'' Sabrin said,
and several in the audience gasped at the analogy.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrin also denounced affirmative action as a form of ''racial
profiling,'' and he said NATO air strikes against the Serbs were
criminal. ''We actually killed more people with our own bombs than
the Serbians killed in Kosovo,'' he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
