<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rose Art Says Talc Not in Crayons  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Rose Art, the second-leading maker of crayons in
the United States, said it no longer uses talc as a strengthening
agent in its crayons.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer reported last month that Rose Art
and other crayons contained asbestos, presumably from talc.
Saturday, the newspaper said Rose Art crayons purchased and tested
Friday contained no cancer-causing asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier tests of 32 of 40 crayons by Rose Art, Crayola and Prang
brands found tremolite and anthophyllite asbestos, the newspaper
had said. Lab analysts said the asbestos may have been introduced
in the talc, a mineral that helps bind crayons.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know whether there is asbestos or not in the talc, but
I do know that we no longer used talc in our crayons,'' said Rose
Art president Lawrence Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   Rosen said the company stopped using talc 15 months ago not
because of health concerns but because ''it made a better, smoother
drawing crayon.''
</P>
<P>
   Crayola and Prang have said there is no asbestos in their
crayons.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission will release
findings of its crayon analysis late next week, spokesman Russ
Rader said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
