<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shock 77, Monarchs 74  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY ATKINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Detroit rookie Edwina Brown scored
three of her nine points in the final minute to help the Shock open
the season with a 77-74 victory over the Sacramento Monarchs on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Yolanda Griffith had 24 points and eight rebounds for the
Monarchs (1-1), who consider themselves a threat to dethrone
Houston as WNBA champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs, who never led in the second half, had a chance to
take a one-point lead, but Ruthie Bolton-Holifield missed two free
throws with 1:24 remaining, allowing Detroit to cling to a 72-71
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento's Ticha Penicheiro drove the lane with 34.7 seconds
left, but was denied by the Shock's Dominique Canty.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs got yet another chance when, following a timeout,
Detroit's Elena Tornikidou threw the ball away on the inbounds
play.
</P>
<P>
   But Canty got the best of Penicheiro on another attempt to drive
the lane, this time knocking the ball away. Tornikidou came up with
the loose ball and Brown, a first-round draft pick out of Texas,
sank two free throws for a three-point lead with 18.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Tornikidou, who led Detroit with 18 points, made two free throws
for a 76-71 lead with 8.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Penicheiro made it a two-point game again with on a 3-pointer
with 2.2 seconds remaining, but Brown hit a free throw with 1.2
left to ice it for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs, who were sluggish in the first half of their
opening victory against the expansion Seattle Storm on Wednesday,
fell behind early in the first half of this game, too.
</P>
<P>
   Astou Ndiaye-Diatta pulled down eight rebounds, helping Detroit
to a 19-15 edge in rebounds in the first 20 minutes. That helped
the Shock, who outrebounded Sacramento 34-26 for the game, to a
15-9 edge in fast-break points.
</P>
<P>
   With Tornikidou directing the floor game and scoring 12 points,
mostly in transition, the Shock opened a 10-point lead late in the
half and led 45-37 at the break. It also helped that Detroit made
10 free throws while the Monarchs, who didn't get to the line until
the final minute of the half, made only two.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento came to life to start the second half, however.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, the WNBA's most valuable player last season, scored
four points as the Monarchs opened the half with a 10-4 burst,
closing the gap to 49-47 with 16:28 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs tied it 51-51 on a jumper by Bolton-Holifield less
than two minutes later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-03-00 2211 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000603.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-03 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies 9, Red Sox 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mike Lieberthal homered twice and drove in
five runs as the Philadelphia Phillies sent the Boston Red Sox to
their fourth straight loss, 9-3 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   With Pedro Martinez scratched because of a sore left ribcage,
knuckleballer Tim Wakefield (1-4) made his third start of the
season for Boston, which matched its longest losing streak of the
season. Wakefield gave up all six runs -- four earned -- and seven
hits in 4 2-3 innings and Boston dropped to 5-7 against
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal had an RBI single in the third, a solo homer in the
sixth and a three-run shot in the eighth off Rob Stanifer.
Lieberthal, who has seven homers this year, had his first
multihomer game of the season, the fifth of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf (5-3), coming off a six-hitter against Los Angeles, struck
out nine in seven innings, allowing two runs, three hits and four
walks. He gave up Carl Everett's RBI single in the fourth, and
Nomar Garciaparra's leadoff homer in the sixth .
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's homer was the 100th of his career. He is 12-for-20
in his last five games.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia went ahead in the first inning when Lieberthal's
one-out grounder went right through the legs of third baseman
Wilton Veras, allowing Kevin Sefcik to score from second on the
error.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia made it 3-0 in the third after Doug Glanville led
off with a single and stole second, and Bobby Abreu reached on a
passed ball as he struck out and the knuckleball eluded catcher
Jason Varitek. Lieberthal and Pat Burrell followed with RBI
singles.
</P>
<P>
   Sefcik hit a sacrifice fly in the fourth for a 4-1 lead. After
Lieberthal's homer in the sixth,
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies made it 4-1 in the fourth with a sacrifice fly by
Sefcik, and added two more runs in the sixth on Lieberthal's first
homer and a bases-loaded walk by Glanville.
</P>
<P>
   Boston scored an unearned run in the eighth off Chris Brock on
consecutive errors by shortstop Desi Relaford and Everett's
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Lieberthal had six RBIs at Montreal on May 19, 1999. ...
Frye was 0-for-4, snapping his 12-game hitting streak. ...
Lieberthal has thrown out four of the last six runners attempting
to steal.
</P>
</TEXT>
