<HEADLINE> Storm systems leaves thousands without power, cleaning up  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Utility crews and homeowners worked Saturday to clean
up the
damage of a storm system that spawned funnel clouds, downed trees
and knocked out power to tens of thousands across Connecticut.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several accidents were blamed on the storms that moved through
the state Friday evening, including one that killed a 35-year-old
woman in Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Dawn Addario, of Southbury, was driving a pickup
truck on Route 67 near the Oxford line about 9 a.m. Saturday when a
tree fell on her vehicle. She was pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Utilities workers, with the aid of 37 crews from
Boston Edison, were working to restore power to the more than
65,000 homes that lost electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a lot of damage,'' said NU spokesman Terrence
McIntosh, adding police in the Fairfield County town of Newtown
alone reported 77 utility poles down. ''That's what's going to take
the most time.''
</P>
<P>
   Danbury, Bethel and Ridgefield also were hard hit with more than
30 percent of homes losing power. As of late Saturday, 19,558
outages remained.
</P>
<P>
   ''You couldn't see out the window,'' Julie Ball, of East Granby,
told WFSB-TV after reporting hail the size of quarters Friday.
''You couldn't see anything but storm.''
</P>
<P>
   A tornado warning was issued for the Winsted area just before 6
p.m. Friday and funnel clouds were reported in Cheshire, Old
Saybrook and Granby.
</P>
<P>
   But the National Weather Service said no tornadoes touched down
in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''A funnel cloud is just a cloud that is rotating,'' said
meteorologist Charlie Foley. ''A tornado is a funnel cloud that
dips to the surface.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that contact with the ground that produces devastating
damage, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Cheshire, police Lt. Frank Bradley said damage was isolated
to the northeastern section of town, where trees blocked roads and
the lawns of homes were strewn with tree limbs and debris.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's pretty bad,'' he said. ''I don't know exactly what hit up
there, but it did significant damage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
