<HEADLINE> Melissa Ann Jeka wins Miss Pennsylvania pageant  </HEADLINE>
AP Photos
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, Pa. (AP) -- The fifth time was a charm for Melissa Ann
Jeka, Miss Allegheny Valley, who won the Miss Pennsylvania
competition Saturday evening at Lehigh University.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm elated,'' said Jeka, 23, of Warminster, Bucks County, who
had entered the Miss Pennsylvania pageant four times before and had
made it to the finals each year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year she was second runner-up, her highest finish before
donning the crown before 800 people as the 2000 winner.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the culmination of many tries, and many years of hard
work,'' said Jeka, who will compete in the Miss America competition
on October 14 in Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, who also receives a $5,000 scholarship, will sign a
contract at a 10 a.m. breakfast on Sunday morning at a Holiday Inn
in Fogelsville. She said she is not sure what is in store but
promised to work hard.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know it's a job, and I'm going to treat it like a job,'' she
said.''This is a dream come true, so I plan to soak up every bit of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner, who graduated from Archbishop Wood High School and
attended Penn State, danced modern &AMP; classical ballet during the
talent portion of the contest. She hopes to go into public
relations but dreams of dancing on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Jeka wants to use her influence to discourage kids from smoking
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up was Kira Delgado, 23, of Levittown, Miss
Neshaminy, who is studying elementary education at West Chester
University and hopes to be a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Jeka placed first in Thursday swimsuit competition, while
Delgado won Thursday's talent and Friday's swimsuit competition.
</P>
<P>
   Misty Dawn Clymer, Miss Penn State, was the second runner-up.
Autumn Marisa, Miss Armstrong County, and Nikesha Moore, Miss
Central Pennsylvania, rounded out the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   Jeka will try to fill the shoes of 1999-2000 Miss Pennsylvania,
Susan Spafford of Erie, who became the second runner up in Miss
America last year. Spafford's finish was the highest for a
Pennsylvania contestant since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The competition featured 26 contestants, ranging in age from 17
to 24, who qualified during smaller local competitions. Eight
graduated from college in May. All receive at least $200 for
competing.
</P>
<P>
   Contestants compete in four categories: private interview,
swimsuit, evening wear and talent. Each contestant also selects a
platform statement on a social issue. Spafford chose to promote
music education in public schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
